{"title_page": "Barclays", "text_new": "{{about|the British banking firm|items that may be pluralised as \"Barclays\"|Barclay (disambiguation)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Barclays plc<!--Please do not change to Barclays Bank PLC, which is a subsidiary of the holding company-->\n| logo = Barclays logo.svg\n| logo_size = 250px\n| image = Barclays HQ.jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| image_caption = The Barclays Head Office in London\n| type = [[Public limited company]]\n| traded_as = {{lse|BARC|fourway=GB0031348658GBGBXSET0}}<br>{{nyse|BCS}}<br>[[FTSE 100 Index|FTSE 100 Component]]\n| industry = [[Bank]]ing<br>[[Financial services]]\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|1690|11|17|df=yes}} in the [[City of London]], [[Kingdom of England]]\n| location_city = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| key_people = Nigel Higgins<br>{{small|(Group Chairman)}}<br>[[Jes Staley]]<br>{{small|(Group Chief Executive)}}\n| products = [[Retail Banking]]<br>[[Commercial Banking]]<br>[[Investment Banking]]<br>[[Wholesale Banking]]<br>[[Private Banking]]<br>[[Wealth Management]]\n| revenue = {{increase}} [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]21.632 billion (2019)<ref name=ar>{{cite web |url=https://home.barclays/content/dam/home-barclays/documents/investor-relations/ResultAnnouncements/2019FYResults/20200213-Barclays-PLC-FY19-Results-Announcement.pdf |title=Annual Results 2019 |accessdate=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n| operating_income = {{increase}} \u00a34.357 billion (2019)<ref name=ar/>\n| net_income = {{increase}} \u00a33.354 billion (2019)<ref name=ar/>\n| assets = {{increase}} \u00a31.140 trillion (2019)<ref name=ar/>\n| equity = {{increase}} \u00a364.429 billion (2019)<ref name=ar/>\n| num_employees = 85,000 (2020)<ref>{{cite web| url=https://joinus.barclays/eme/about-us/| title=About us| publisher=Barclays| accessdate=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n| divisions = Barclays UK<br>[[Barclays Investment Bank]]<br>Barclays Corporate Bank<br>Barclays Private Bank<br>Barclays Payments<br>Barclays US Consumer Bank\n| homepage = {{URL|https://www.barclays.co.uk/}}\n}}\n\n'''Barclays plc<!--Please do not change to Barclays Bank plc, which is a subsidiary of the holding company Barclays plc. It is legally abbreviated to plc not PLC.-->''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|\u0251\u02d0r|k|l|i|z|,_|-|l|e\u026a|z}})<!--Please do not remove /r/ after /\u0251\u02d0/, since Wikipedia guidelines for English Pronunciation recommend a diaphonemic transcription, an abstraction of speech sounds that accommodate General American, Received Pronunciation, Canadian English, South African, Australian, and New Zealand pronunciations; i.e rhotic and non rhotic pronunciations.--> is a British multinational [[Investment banking|investment bank]]<!-- Its investment banking arm is a separate institution to its financial services. They are separate components that add up to the diversified services of the company. Leave as \"investment bank and financial services company\".--> and [[financial services]] company, headquartered in [[London]]. Apart from investment banking, Barclays is organised into four core businesses: [[Retail banking|personal banking]], [[Commercial bank|corporate banking]], [[wealth management]], and [[investment management]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.home.barclays/about-barclays/business-structure.html| title=Business Structure| publisher=Barclays}}</ref>\n\nBarclays traces its origins to the [[goldsmith]] banking business established in the City of London in 1690.<ref name=archives>{{citation| url=https://www.archive.barclays.com/items/show/5419| title=Barclays \u2013 A Quick History| publisher=archive.barclays.com| accessdate=16 August 2017}}</ref> James Barclay became a partner in the business in 1736. In 1896, several banks in London and the English provinces, including [[Backhouse's Bank]] and [[Gurney's Bank]], united as a [[joint-stock company|joint-stock]] bank under the name Barclays and Co. Over the following decades, Barclays expanded to become a nationwide bank. In 1969, Barclays deployed the world's first [[Automated teller machine|cash dispenser]]. Barclays has made numerous corporate acquisitions, including of London, Provincial and South Western Bank in 1918, [[British Linen Bank]] in 1919, Mercantile Credit in 1975, [[the Woolwich]] in 2000 and the North American operations of [[Lehman Brothers]] in 2008.\n\nBarclays has a primary listing on the [[London Stock Exchange]] and is a constituent of the [[FTSE 100 Index]]. It has a secondary listing on the [[New York Stock Exchange]]. \n\nAccording to a 2011 paper by Vitali et al., Barclays was the most powerful [[transnational corporation]] in terms of ownership and thus [[corporate power|corporate control]] over [[Global financial system|global financial stability]] and [[market competition]], with [[Axa]] and [[State Street Corporation]] taking the 2nd and 3rd positions, respectively.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://images.zeit.de/wissen/2012-05/s37-infografik-wirtschaft.pdf |title=Wem geh\u00f6rt die Welt? |accessdate=16 August 2017 |url-status=dead |trans-title=Who owns the world? | work=[[Die Zeit]] |date=31 March 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161004225112/http://images.zeit.de/wissen/2012-05/s37-infografik-wirtschaft.pdf |archivedate=4 October 2016 |language=German}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title=The Network of Global Corporate Control| first1=Stefania| last1=Vitali| first2=James B.| last2=Glattfelder| first3=Stefano| last3=Battiston| last-author-amp=yes| journal= PLOS ONE|volume = 6|issue = 10|pages = e25995| date=26 October 2011| doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0025995|pmid = 22046252|pmc = 3202517| arxiv=1107.5728|bibcode = 2011PLoSO...625995V}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===1690 to 1900===\nBarclays traces its origins back to 1690 when [[John Freame]], a [[Quaker]], and Thomas Gould started trading as [[goldsmith]] bankers in [[Lombard Street, London]]. The name \"Barclays\" became associated with the business in 1736, when Freame's son-in-law James Barclay became a partner.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aboutbarclays.co.uk/content/detail.asp?NewsAreaID=138 |accessdate=30 January 2007 |title=Company History |work=Barclays Newsroom: Business History\n|publisher=Barclays}} See also: ''Barclays: The Business of Banking, 1690\u20131996'' by Margaret Ackrill and Leslie Hannah; Cambridge UP, 2001 {{ISBN|0-521-79035-2}}</ref> In 1728 the bank moved to 54 Lombard Street, identified by the 'Sign of the Black Spread [[Eagle (heraldry)|Eagle]]', which in subsequent years would become a core part of the bank's visual identity.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aboutbarclays.co.uk/content/detail.asp?NewsAreaID=138 |accessdate=11 May 2008 |title=Company History |work=Barclays.lk \u2013 About us: Our History {{!}} 1690\u20131972 |publisher=Barclays}}</ref>\n\nThe Barclay family were connected with slavery, both as proponents and opponents. David and Alexander Barclay were engaged in the slave trade in 1756.<ref>{{cite book |last=Williams |first=Eric |date=1964 |title=Slavery and Capitalism |location=London |publisher= Deutsch|page=116 }}</ref> [[David Barclay of Youngsbury]] (1729\u20131809), on the other hand, was a noted [[abolitionism in the United Kingdom|abolitionist]], and [[Verene Shepherd]], the [[history of Jamaica|Jamaican historian]] of [[diaspora studies]], singles out the case of how he chose to [[manumission|free his slaves]] in [[English Jamaica|that colony]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shepherd|first1=Verene|title=Freedom in the era of slavery: The case of the Barclay brothers in Jamaica|url=http://old.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20080224/news/news3.html|accessdate=15 January 2018|publisher=The Gleaner|date=24 February 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 1776 the firm was styled \"Barclay, Bevan and Bening\" and so remained until 1785, when another partner, John Tritton, who had married a Barclay, was admitted, and the business then became \"Barclay, Bevan, Bening and Tritton\".<ref>(Gamble 1923,46).</ref>\nIn 1896 several banks in London and the English provinces, notably [[Backhouse's Bank]] of [[Darlington]]<ref>{{cite book| first1=Margaret| last1=Ackrill| first2=Leslie| last2=Hannah| title=Barclays: The Business of Banking, 1690-1996| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yAwipk34KP0C| year=2001| publisher=Cambridge University Press| isbn=978-0-521-79035-2| page=57}}</ref> and [[Gurney's Bank]] of [[Norwich]] (both of which also had their roots in Quaker families), united under the banner of Barclays and Co., a [[joint-stock company|joint-stock]] bank.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.heritagecity.org/research-centre/industrial-innovation/the-gurney-family-and-banking-in-norwich.htm| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100717225313/http://www.heritagecity.org/research-centre/industrial-innovation/the-gurney-family-and-banking-in-norwich.htm| url-status=dead| archive-date=17 July 2010| title=The Gurney family and banking in Norwich| publisher=Heritage City| accessdate=19 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== 1900 to 1945 ===\n\n[[File:1 Crossroads Sutton Surrey London.JPG|thumb|265px|The Barclays Bank branch in [[Sutton, London|Sutton]], southern Greater London, which was originally a branch of London and Provincial prior to acquisition by Barclays]]\n\nBetween 1905 and 1916 Barclays extended its branch network by making acquisitions of small English banks. Further expansion followed in 1918 when Barclays amalgamated with the [[London, Provincial and South Western Bank]] and in 1919 when the [[British Linen Bank]] was acquired by Barclays Bank, although the British Linen Bank retained a separate board of directors and continued to issue its own banknotes (see [[Banknotes of the pound sterling]]).<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.stirlingarchives.scot/2016/02/15/bank-and-agents-house-british-linen-bank-balfron-1923/| title=Bank and Agent's House, British Linen Bank| publisher=Stirling Archives| accessdate=19 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1925 the [[Colonial Bank (West Indies)|Colonial Bank]], [[National Bank of South Africa]] and the [[Anglo-Egyptian Bank]] were amalgamated and Barclays operated its overseas operations under the name Barclays Bank (Dominion, Colonial and Overseas)\u2014Barclays DCO.<ref name=pohl/> In 1938 Barclays acquired the first Indian exchange bank, the [[Central Exchange Bank of India]], which had opened in London in 1936 with the sponsorship of [[Central Bank of India]].<ref>Raychaudhuri ''et al.'', eds. (1983), Vol. 2, p.782.</ref>\n\nIn 1941 during the German [[occupation of France]], a branch of Barclays in Paris headed by Marcel Cheradame worked directly with the invading force.<ref name=Cheradame>{{cite web| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/1999/mar/28/theobserver7| title=Holocaust shame of Barclays| publisher=The Guardian| accessdate=1 January 2019}}</ref> Senior officials at the bank volunteered the names of Jewish employees as well as ceding an estimated one hundred Jewish bank accounts to the German occupiers.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/237392.stm| title=Barclays to compensate Jews | publisher=BBC News| accessdate=1 January 2019}}</ref> The Paris branch used its funds to increase the operational power of a large quarry that helped produce steel for the Germans. There was no evidence of contact between the head office in London and the branch in Paris during the occupation. Marcel Cheradame was kept as the branch manager until he retired in the sixties.<ref name=Cheradame/>\n\n===1946 to 1980===\nIn May 1958, Barclays was the first UK bank to appoint a female bank manager. [[Hilda Harding]] managed Barclays' Hanover Square branch in London until her retirement in 1970.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.archive.barclays.com/items/show/662 |title=Head Office Circular announcing the appointment of Hilda Harding as branch manager |publisher=Barclays |date=15 May 1958 |accessdate=25 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Atmplaque.jpg|thumb|right|A plaque in [[Enfield Town|Enfield]], United Kingdom commemorating the installation of the world's first [[Automated teller machine|cash machine]] by Barclays in 1967]]\nIn 1965, Barclays established a US affiliate, Barclays Bank of California in San Francisco.<ref>{{cite news| work=Investors chronicle and stock exchange gazette| date=5 December 1969| volume=10| page=922| title=Barclays}} Accessed 4 May 2012.</ref><ref>{{cite news| author=Leith McGrandle| work=Accountancy| date=5 December 1969| volume=85| page=54 |title=Barclays}} Accessed 4 May 2012.</ref>\n\nBarclays launched the first credit card in the UK, [[Barclaycard]], in 1966. On 27 June 1967, Barclays deployed the world's first [[Automated teller machine|cash machine]], in [[Enfield Town|Enfield]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3AQAAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA32|title=Insert card here|accessdate=4 May 2012| publisher=CIO Magazine| date=July 1988}}</ref><ref name=bbc25607>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/6230194.stm |title=The man who invented the cash machine |accessdate=4 May 2012 |publisher=BBC News |date=25 June 2007 |first=Brian |last=Milligan }}</ref> The British actor [[Reg Varney]] was the first person to use the machine.<ref name=bbc25607/>\n\nIn 1969, a planned merger with [[Martins Bank]] and [[Lloyds Bank]] was blocked by the [[Competition Commission (United Kingdom)|Monopolies and Mergers Commission]], but the acquisition of [[Martins Bank]] on its own was later permitted. Also that year, the [[British Linen Bank]] subsidiary was sold to the [[Bank of Scotland]] in exchange for a 25% stake, a transaction that became effective from 1971. Barclays DCO changed its name to Barclays Bank International in 1971.<ref name=pohl>{{cite book| author=European Association for Banking History| editor-last1=Pohl| editor-first1=Manfred| editor-last2=Freitag| editor-first2=Sabine| title=Handbook on the history of European banks| date=1994| publisher=E. Elgar| location=Aldershot, Hants, England| isbn=9781781954218| pages=1198\u20131199| url=https://books.google.com/?id=eXvfNDHpfWwC&lpg=PA1198&dq=%22barclays%20bank%20international%22%20established&pg=PA1193#v=onepage&q=%22barclays%20bank%20international%22%20established&f=false|accessdate=10 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn August 1975, following the [[Secondary banking crisis of 1973\u20131975|secondary banking crash]], Barclays acquired Mercantile Credit Company.<ref>{{cite book| title=The secondary banking crisis, 1973\u201375: its causes and course| first1=Margaret| last1=Reid| publisher=Macmillan| year=1982| isbn=978-0-333-28376-9 |page=128| url=https://books.google.com/?id=_XmuAAAAIAAJ&q=The+secondary+banking+crisis,+1973-75:+its+causes+and+course&dq=The+secondary+banking+crisis,+1973-75:+its+causes+and+course| accessdate=4 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n===1980 to 2000===\nIn 1980, Barclays Bank International expanded its business to include commercial credit and took over American Credit Corporation, renaming it Barclays American Corporation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/Barclays-plc-Company-History.html |accessdate=28 March 2009 |title=Barclays plc |work=Funding Universe}}</ref>\n\nDuring 1985 <ref name=a2020214>MJ Larson, G Schnyder, G Westerhaus, J Wilson (2013) \u2014 [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Kb7cAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA53&dq=Barclays+Group&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiNhKqB-NHnAhUJQ8AKHVoDCSsQ6AEIOzAC#v=onepage&q=Barclays%20Group&f=false p.53] in (Andrea Colli, Abe De Jong, Martin Jes Iversen editors) [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Kb7cAAAAQBAJ&dq=Barclays+Group&source=gbs_navlinks_s Mapping European Corporations: Strategy, Structure, Ownership and Performance] published by [[Routledge]], September 13 2013 {{ISBN|1135754446}}, {{ISBN|9781135754440}} - accessed 2020-02-14</ref> Barclays Bank and Barclays Bank International merged, and as part of the corporate reorganisation the former Barclays Bank plc became a group holding company,<ref name=pohl/> renamed Barclays Group Plc<ref name=a2020214/>, and UK [[retail banking]] was integrated under the former BBI, and renamed ''Barclays Bank PLC'' from ''Barclays Bank Limited''.<ref name=pohl/>\n\nIn 1986 Barclays sold its South African business operating under the [[First National Bank (South Africa)|Barclays National Bank]] name after protests against Barclays' involvement in South Africa and its [[apartheid]] government. Also that year Barclays bought de Zoete & Bevan and Wedd Durlacher (formerly Wedd Jefferson)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sas-space.sas.ac.uk/2762/ |title=Abstract \u2013 SAS-Space |publisher=Sas-space.sas.ac.uk |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> to form Barclays de Zoete Wedd (BZW), now known as the [[Barclays Investment Bank]], and to take advantage of the [[Big Bang (financial markets)|Big Bang]] on the [[London Stock Exchange]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.linkedin.com/company/bzw-barclays-de-zoete-wedd- |title=About BZW (Barclays de Zoete Wedd) |publisher=LinkedIn |accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nBarclays introduced the ''Connect'' card in June 1987, the first [[debit card]] in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite book |title=Law of bank payments |first1=Michael |last1=Lerego |publisher=FT Law & Tax |year=1996 |isbn=978-0-7520-0037-4 |page=472 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=anVMAQAAIAAJ&q=Law+of+bank+payments+Michael+Lerego&dq=Law+of+bank+payments+Michael+Lerego |accessdate=4 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The banking revolution: salvation or slaughter? : how technology is creating winners and losers |first1=Mark |last1=Carrington |first2=Philip |last2=Langguth |first3=Thomas |last3=Steiner |publisher=Financial Times Pitman |year=1997 |isbn=978-0-273-63055-5 |page=119 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=fid2QgAACAAJ&dq=The+banking+revolution:+salvation+or+slaughter |accessdate=4 May 2012}} {{Dead link |date=March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, Barclays sold Barclays Bank of California, which at that time was the 17th-largest bank in California measured by assets, to [[Wells Fargo]] for US$125&nbsp;million in cash.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/01/16/business/company-news-wells-fargo-to-buy-barclays-in-california.html |title=Wells Fargo to Buy Barclays in California |accessdate=4 May 2012 |work=The New York Times |date=16 January 1988 |first=Lawrence M. |last=Fisher}}</ref>\n\n[[Edgar Pearce]], the \"Mardi Gra Bomber\", began a terror campaign against the bank and the supermarket chain [[Sainsbury's]] in 1994.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/318913.stm |title=Mardi Gra bomber jailed |publisher=BBC News |date=14 April 1999 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Barclays bought Wells Fargo Nikko Investment Advisors (WFNIA) and merged it with BZW Investment Management to form [[Barclays Global Investors]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/06/19/business/barclays-may-soon-purchase-wells-fargo-nikko.html |title=Barclays may well soon buy Wells Fargo Nikko |work=The New York Times |date=19 June 1995 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nTwo years later, in 1998, the BZW business was broken up and parts were sold to [[Credit Suisse First Boston]]: Barclays retained the debt business which formed the foundation of what is now Barclays Capital.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4885056.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102215642/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4885056.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2 November 2012 |title=Revealed: what Credit Suisse really thinks about BZW |date=14 November 1997 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, in an unusual move as part of the trend at the time for [[free ISP]]s, Barclays launched an internet service called Barclays.net: this entity was acquired by [[British Telecom]] in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barclays.net |title=Barclays webpage |accessdate=18 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070517045409/http://www.barclays.net/ |archivedate=17 May 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2000, Barclays took over the recently de-mutualised Woolwich PLC, formerly [[the Woolwich]] Building Society,<ref>{{Cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/875639.stm |title= Barclays buys rival Woolwich |publisher= BBC News |date= 11 August 2000 |accessdate= 18 April 2011}}</ref> in a \u00a35.4 billion acquisition. Woolwich thus joined the Barclays group of companies, and the Woolwich name was retained after the acquisition. The company's head office remained in [[Bexleyheath]], south-east [[London]], four miles from the original head office in [[Woolwich]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/875639.stm Barclays buys rival Woolwich] BBC News, 11 August 2000</ref>\n\n===21st century===\n[[File:Barclays Bank, Stratford-upon-Avon - DSC08949.JPG|thumb|right|A Barclays branch in [[Stratford-upon-Avon]], United Kingdom]]\nIn 2001 Barclays closed 171 branches in the UK, many of them in rural communities: Barclays called itself \"The Big Bank\" but this name was quickly given a low profile after a series of embarrassing PR stunts.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/everythings-big-at-barclays-the-chairmans-pay-has-quadrupled-just-as-171-branches-are-closing-722358.html |title=Everything is big at Barclays: the chairman's pay has quadrupled just as 171 branches are closing |work=The Independent |location=UK |date=31 March 2000 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 October 2001, Barclays and [[Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce|CIBC]] agreed to combine their [[Caribbean]] operations to establish a joint venture company known as [[FirstCaribbean International Bank]] (FCIB).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/cibc-barclays-planning-caribbean-joint-venture/article18416752/|title=CIBC, Barclays planning Caribbean joint venture|date=24 July 2001|website=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Barclays bought the American credit card company [[Juniper Bank]] from [[Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce|CIBC]], re-branding it as \"Barclays Bank Delaware\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Timmons |first=Heather |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/08/19/business/barclays-pays-293-million-for-us-credit-card-issuer.html |title=Barclays pays $293&nbsp;million for US credit card issuer |work=The New York Times |date=19 August 2004 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> The same year saw the acquisition of Banco Zaragozano, the 11th-largest Spanish bank.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Timmons |first=Heather |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/05/09/business/barclays-agrees-to-buy-spanish-bank-in-cash-deal.html |title=Barclays agrees to buy Spanish bank in cash deal |location=SPAIN |work=The New York Times |date=9 May 2003 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nBarclays took over sponsorship of the [[Premier League]] from [[Barclaycard]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportbusiness.com/news/160512/barclays-secures-fa-premier-league-sponsorship |title=Barclays secures FA Premier League sponsorship |publisher=Sportbusiness.com |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> In May 2005, Barclays moved its group headquarters from [[Lombard Street, London|Lombard Street]] in the [[City of London]] to [[One Churchill Place]] in [[Canary Wharf]]. Also in 2005 Barclays sealed a \u00a32.6bn takeover of [[Absa Group Limited]], South Africa's largest retail bank, acquiring a 54% stake on 27 July 2005.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/low/business/3683830.stm |title=Barclays looks to buy Absa stake |publisher=BBC News |date=23 September 2004 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nThen in 2006, Barclays purchased the HomEq Servicing Corporation for US$469&nbsp;million in cash from [[Wachovia]] Corp.<ref>{{cite web |first=Aaron |last=Siegel |date=23 June 2006 |url=http://www.investmentnews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20060623/REG/606230708/1094/INDaily03 |title=Barclays buys Wachovia unit for $469&nbsp;million |work=InvestmentNews |accessdate=16 August 2017}}</ref> That year also saw the acquisition of the financial website CompareTheLoan<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comparetheloan.co.uk |title=Cheap Homeowner Loans , Compare Loans , UK Secured Loans |publisher=Comparetheloan |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> and Barclays announcing plans to rebrand Woolwich branches as Barclays, migrating Woolwich customers onto Barclays accounts and migrating back-office processes onto Barclays systems\u2014the Woolwich brand was to be used for Barclays mortgages.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mad.co.uk/BreakingNews/BreakingNews/Articles/dc366386b91141a4bd605f83c3d36f8c/Barclays-plans-rebrand-of-Woolwich.html |title=Barclays plans rebrand of Woolwich |publisher=Mad.co.uk |date=28 June 2006 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> Barclays also exited retail-banking operations in the Caribbean-region which extended as far back as 1837 through selling of its joint venture stake in FirstCaribbean International Bank (FCIB) to CIBC for between $989 million and $1.08 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/caribbean/news/story/2006/12/printable/061228_barclays.shtml |title=Barclays sells Caribbean stake |date=28 December 2006|publisher=BBC|accessdate=2 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2007, Barclays announced that it had purchased the naming rights to the [[Barclays Center]], a proposed 18,000-seat arena in [[Brooklyn]], New York, where the [[New Jersey Nets]] planned to relocate.<ref>{{cite news |date=17 January 2007 |url=http://www.ny1.com/archives/nyc/all-boroughs/2007/01/17/nets-new-arena-reportedly-to-be-called-barclays-center-NYC_65958.old.html |title=Nets' new arena reportedly to be called Barclays Centre |publisher=[[NY1]] |accessdate=16 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170817163058/http://www.ny1.com/archives/nyc/all-boroughs/2007/01/17/nets-new-arena-reportedly-to-be-called-barclays-center-NYC_65958.old.html |archive-date=17 August 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n\n\n====Abandoned merger with ABN AMRO====\nIn March 2007, Barclays announced plans to merge with [[ABN AMRO]], the largest bank in the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite press release |date=20 March 2007 |url=http://www.newsroom.barclays.co.uk/content/Detail.asp?ReleaseID=985&NewsAreaID=2 |title=Barclays and ABN AMRO Announce Outline of Preliminary Discussions |publisher=Barclays |accessdate=18 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107012336/http://www.newsroom.barclays.co.uk/content/Detail.asp?ReleaseID=985&NewsAreaID=2 |archivedate=7 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Werdigier |first=Julia |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/19/business/19deal.html |title=Barclays Bank Makes Inquiry on Takeover of ABN Amro |work=The New York Times |date=19 March 2007 |accessdate=2 February 2012}}</ref> However, on 5 October 2007 Barclays announced that it had abandoned its bid,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/low/business/7029297.stm |title=Barclays abandons ABN Amro offer |publisher=BBC News |date=5 October 2007 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> citing inadequate support by ABN shareholders. Fewer than 80% of shares had been tendered to Barclays' cash-and-shares offer.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mollenkamp |first=Carrick |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB119158340445950068?mod=googlenews_wsj |title=Barclays's CEO Shifts to Plan B |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=3 February 2011 |accessdate=18 April 2011 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> This left the consortium led by [[Royal Bank of Scotland]] free to proceed with its counter-bid for ABN AMRO.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cityam.com/index.php?news=8833 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090125174939/http://www.cityam.com/index.php?news=8833 |url-status=dead |archive-date=25 January 2009 |title=Does RBS's acquisition of ABN AMRO really do what it says on the tin? |work=[[City A.M.]] |date= |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nTo help finance its bid for ABN AMRO, Barclays sold a 3.1% stake to [[China Development Bank]] and a 3% stake to [[Temasek Holdings]], the investment arm of the Singaporean government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marketwatch.com/news/story/barclays-looks-east-fund-new/story.aspx?guid=%7B273CEEA5-1246-44E0-B0B4-B1AAC48C312B%7D |title=Barclays looks East to fund ABN AMRO purchase |work=[[MarketWatch]] |date=23 July 2007 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2007, Barclays agreed to purchase Equifirst Corporation from [[Regions Financial Corporation]] for US$225&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9501E7D71E30F933A15752C0A9619C8B63 |title=Barclays to buy sub-prime lender |work=The New York Times |date=20 January 2007 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> That year also saw Barclays Personal Investment Management announcing the closure of their operation in Peterborough and its re-siting to Glasgow, laying off nearly 900 members of staff.<ref>{{cite news |date=8 May 2014 |publisher=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-27321589/ |title=Barclays To Cut 19,000 Jobs Over Three Years |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Financing====\nOn 30 August 2007, Barclays was forced to borrow \u00a31.6&nbsp;billion (US$3.2&nbsp;billion) from the [[Bank of England]] sterling standby facility. This is made available as a last-resort when banks are unable to settle their debts to other banks at the end of daily trading.<ref>{{cite news |first1=Ashley |last1=Seager |first2=Larry |last2=Elliott |first3=Julia |last3=Kollewe |last-author-amp=yes |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2007/aug/31/money |title=Barclays admits borrowing hundreds of millions |work=The Guardian |location=UK |date= 31 August 2007 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> Despite rumours about liquidity at Barclays, the loan was necessary due to a technical problem with their computerised settlement network. A Barclays spokesman was quoted as saying \"There are no liquidity issues in the U.K markets. Barclays itself is flush with liquidity.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Menon |first=Jon |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601102&sid=aqA8hFXWD3JY&refer=uk |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930055730/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601102&sid=aqA8hFXWD3JY&refer=uk |url-status=dead |archive-date=30 September 2007 |title=UK & Ireland |publisher=Bloomberg |date=31 August 2007 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 November 2007, Barclays shares dropped 9% and were even temporarily suspended for a short period of time, due to rumours of a \u00a34.8&nbsp;billion (US$10&nbsp;billion) exposure to bad debts in the US. However, a Barclays spokesman denied the rumours.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/7087451.stm |title=Barclays denies bad debt rumour |publisher=BBC News |date=9 November 2007 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nBarclays sought to raise capital privately, avoiding direct equity investment from the UK government, which was offered to boost its capital ratio.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lee |first=Peter |url=http://www.euromoney.com/Article/2225039/Barclays-keeps-apologizing-for-saving-the-bank.html |title=Barclays keeps apologizing for saving the bank |work=[[Euromoney]]}}</ref> Barclays believed that \"maintaining its independence from government was in the best interests of its shareholders\".<ref>{{cite news |date=2 April 2013 |work=The Wall Street Journal |url=http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/SalzReview04032013.pdf |title=An Independent Review of Barclays' Business Practices |accessdate=25 April 2014 |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2008, Barclays attempted to raise \u00a34.5&nbsp;billion through a non-traditional rights issue to shore up its weakened [[Tier 1 capital|Tier 1 capital ratio]], which involved a rights offer to existing shareholders and the sale of a stake to [[Sumitomo Mitsui Banking Corporation]]. Only 19% of shareholders took up their rights leaving investors [[China Development Bank]] and [[Qatar Investment Authority]] with increased holdings in the bank.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/7513178.stm |title=Barclays share sale raises \u00a34.5bn |publisher=BBC News |date=18 July 2008 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nBarclays launched a further round of capital raising, approved by special resolution on 24 November 2008, as part of its overall plan to achieve higher capital targets set by the UK's [[Financial Services Authority]] to ensure it would remain independent.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.euromoney.com/Article/2038377/Abigail-Hofman-The-loser-list.html#strategy |title=Abigail Hofman: The loser list |work=Euromoney |date=30 October 2008}}</ref> Barclays raised \u00a37&nbsp;billion from investors from Abu Dhabi and Qatar.<ref name=nytqatar>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/01/business/worldbusiness/01barclays.html |title=Barclays Seeks $11.8 Billion From Abu Dhabi and Qatar |date=1 November 2008 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=19 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.euromoney.com/Article/2059789/Abigail-with-attitude-More-zeroes-than-heroes.html#barclays |title=Abigail Hofman: More zeroes than heroes \u2013 Barclays |work=Euromoney |date=1 December 2008}}</ref> Existing Barclays shareholders complained they were not offered full pre-emption rights in this round of capital raising, even threatening to revolt at the extraordinary meeting. Sheikh Mansour and Qatar Holding agreed to open up \u00a3500&nbsp;million of their new holdings of reserve capital instruments for clawback. Existing investors now took this up.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.euromoney.com/Article/3198818/Barclays-Qatari-capital-raising-timeline.html |title=Barclays' Qatari capital-raising timeline |work=Euromoney |first=Erica |last=Jeffery |date=12 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Barclays bought the credit card brand Goldfish for US$70&nbsp;million gaining 1.7&nbsp;million customers, and US$3.9&nbsp;billion in receivables.<ref>{{cite news|\n url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/banking_and_finance/article3330860.ece| title=Barclays buys Goldfish as US Group calls time on credit cards| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611162430/http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/banking_and_finance/article3330860.ece |date=8 February 2008 |archive-date=11 June 2011 |first1=Miles |last1=Costello |first2=Siobhan |last2=Kennedy |work=[[The Times]] |url-access=subscription }}</ref> Barclays also bought a controlling stake in the Russian retail bank Expobank for US$745&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/banking_and_finance/article3473418.ece| title=Barclays seals Expobank deal in Russia| work=The Times| first1=Miles |last1=Costello| date=3 March 2008| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081008015533/http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/banking_and_finance/article3473418.ece |archive-date=8 October 2008}}</ref> Later in the year Barclays commenced its [[Pakistan]] operations with initial funding of US$100&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news| work=Pakistan Daily| url=http://www.daily.pk/business/businessnews/6078.html?task=view| title=Barclays Bank UK commences operation in Pakistan|  date=25 July 2008| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080912123124/http://www.daily.pk/business/businessnews/6078.html?task=view |archive-date=12 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n====Lehman Brothers acquisition====\n[[File:Lehman Brothers Times Square by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|The former headquarters of [[Lehman Brothers]] in New York City, now owned by Barclays]]\n[[File:BBNY.jpg|right|thumb|300px|The New York building at night]]\nOn 16 September 2008, Barclays announced its agreement to purchase, subject to regulatory approval, the investment-banking and trading divisions of [[Lehman Brothers]] (including its New York skyscraper) which was a United States financial conglomerate that had filed for bankruptcy.<ref>{{cite news| last=Treanor| first=Jill| title=Barclays to buy Lehman Brothers assets| url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/sep/16/barclay.lehmanbrothers1| newspaper=The Guardian| date=16 April 2013| location=London}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 September 2008, a revised version of the deal, a US$1.35&nbsp;billion (\u00a3700&nbsp;million) plan for Barclays to acquire the core business of Lehman Brothers (mainly Lehman's US$960&nbsp;million [[Midtown Manhattan]] office skyscraper, with responsibility for 9,000 former employees), was approved. After a seven-hour hearing, New York [[United States bankruptcy court|bankruptcy court]] Judge James Peck ruled:\n{{quote|\"I have to approve this transaction because it is the only available transaction. Lehman Brothers became a victim, in effect the only true icon to fall in a tsunami that has befallen the credit markets. This is the most momentous bankruptcy hearing I've ever sat through. It can never be deemed precedent for future cases. It's hard for me to imagine a similar emergency.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/7626624.stm |title=Judge approves $1.3bn Lehman deal |publisher=BBC News |date=20 September 2008 |accessdate=18 April 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110512055650/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/7626624.stm| archivedate= 12 May 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n\nLuc Despins, the creditors committee counsel, said: \"The reason we're not objecting is really based on the lack of a viable alternative. We did not support the transaction because there had not been enough time to properly review it.\" In the amended agreement, Barclays would absorb US$47.4&nbsp;billion in securities and assume US$45.5&nbsp;billion in trading liabilities. Lehman's attorney [[Harvey R. Miller]] of [[Weil, Gotshal & Manges]], said \"the purchase price for the real estate components of the deal would be US$1.29&nbsp;billion, including US$960&nbsp;million for Lehman's New York headquarters and US$330&nbsp;million for two New Jersey data centres. Lehman's original estimate valued its headquarters at US$1.02&nbsp;billion but an appraisal from CB Richard Ellis this week valued it at US$900&nbsp;million.\" Further, Barclays will not acquire Lehman's Eagle Energy unit, but will have entities known as Lehman Brothers Canada Inc, Lehman Brothers Sudamerica, Lehman Brothers Uruguay and its Private Investment Management business for high-net-worth individuals. Finally, Lehman will retain US$20&nbsp;billion of securities assets in Lehman Brothers Inc that are not being transferred to Barclays.<ref>{{cite news |last=Chasan |first=Emily |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/rbssFinancialServicesAndRealEstateNews/idUSN1932554220080920 |title=Judge approves Lehman, Barclays pact |agency=Reuters |date=20 September 2008 |accessdate=18 April 2011| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090626052050/https://www.reuters.com/article/rbssFinancialServicesAndRealEstateNews/idUSN1932554220080920| archivedate=26 June 2009 |url-status= live}}</ref> Barclays had a potential liability of US$2.5&nbsp;billion to be paid as [[severance package|severance]], if it chooses not to retain some Lehman employees beyond the guaranteed 90 days.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1988&dat=20080921&id=wYkxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=s6kFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1538,1373426 |title=Judge says Lehman can sell units to Barclays |agency=[[Associated Press]] |first=Vinnee |last=Tong |date=21 September 2008 |work=[[The Argus-Press]] |location=[[Owosso, Michigan]] |page=6A}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title=Barclays clinches deal to buy Lehman assets for $2bn| url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/sep/17/barclay.lehmanbrothers| date=16 September 2008| first1=David| last1=Teather| first2=Jill| last2=Treanor| work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, Barclays was ordered to pay $15&nbsp;million in settlement charges that alleged the bank had failed to maintain an adequate internal compliance system after its acquisition of Lehman Brothers during the 2008 financial crisis.<ref>{{cite news| agency=Reuters| date=23 September 2014| title=Barclays to pay $15&nbsp;million over compliance failures tied to Lehman deal| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/09/23/us-sec-barclays-violations-idUSKCN0HI1ZE20140923}}</ref>\n\n====2009 to present====\n[[File:Barclays Global Investors HQ, south side 1.JPG|thumb|The former headquarters of Barclays Global Investors in San Francisco, United States. Barclays sold Barclays Global Investors to [[BlackRock]] in 2009.]]\n[[Reuters]] later reported that the [[HM Treasury|British government]] would inject \u00a340&nbsp;billion (US$69&nbsp;billion) into three banks including Barclays, which might seek over \u00a37&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/innovationNewsIndustryMaterialsAndUtilities/idUSTRE49B37P20081012?sp=true |title=British banks set for 40&nbsp;billion pound rescue: sources |agency=Reuters |date=12 October 2008 |first1=John |last1=Bowker |first2=Ralph |last2=Gowling |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> Barclays later confirmed that it rejected the Government's offer and would instead raise \u00a36.5&nbsp;billion of new capital (\u00a32&nbsp;billion by cancellation of dividend and \u00a34.5&nbsp;billion from private investors).<ref name=nytqatar/><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.bankingtimes.co.uk/13102008-barclays-confirms-65bn-fundraising/| title=Barclays confirms \u00a36.5bn fundraising| \n archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014034029/http://www.bankingtimes.co.uk/13102008-barclays-confirms-65bn-fundraising/| date=13 October 2008| archive-date=14 October 2008| work=Banking Times}}</ref>\n\nBarclays' share price fell 54% in June 2009 after the [[International Petroleum Investment Company]] (IPIC), which had invested up to \u00a34.75&nbsp;billion in November 2008, sold 1.3&nbsp;billion Barclays shares.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.euromoney.com/Article/2231148/Euromoney-40th-anniversary-special-Focus-on-Ipic.html |title=Euromoney 40th anniversary special: Focus on Ipic | work=Euromoney |date=June 2009}}</ref>\n[[Qatar Investment Authority|Qatar Holding]] sold a 3.5% stake worth \u00a310&nbsp;billion in October 2009,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.euromoney.com/Article/2350993/Abigail-with-attitude-Barclays-tea-leaves.html |title=Abigail with attitude: Barclays' tea leaves |work=Euromoney |first=Abigail |last=Hofman |date=3 December 2009}}</ref> and a further sale of warrants worth around \u00a3750&nbsp;million in November 2012, but remains one of the bank's largest shareholders.<ref name=\"Euromoney\">{{cite news| first=Erica| last=Jeffery| url=http://www.euromoney.com/Article/3198818/Barclays-Qatari-capital-raising-timeline.html |title=Barclays' Qatari capital-raising timeline |work=Euromoney |date=12 May 2014}}</ref> In July 2012, Barclays revealed that the FSA was investigating<ref name=\"Euromoney\"/> whether the bank adequately disclosed fees paid to [[Qatar Investment Authority]]. In August 2012, the [[Serious Fraud Office (United Kingdom)|Serious Fraud Office]] announced an investigation into the Middle East capital raising. The [[Financial Services Authority]] announced an expansion of the investigation into the Barclays-Qatar deal in January 2013, focusing on the disclosure surrounding the ownership of the securities in the bank.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/47d412ce-6bd1-11e2-a700-00144feab49a.html |title=Barclays in Qatar loan probe |work=Financial Times |date=31 January 2013 |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2009, the press reported that further capital may be required and that while the government might be willing to fund this, it may be unable to do so because the previous capital investment from the Qatari state was subject to a proviso that no third party might put in further money without the Qataris receiving compensation at the value the shares had commanded in October 2008.<ref>[http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/banking_and_finance/article5570035.ece John Varley perplexed as Barclays' share price dives] ''The Times'', 23 January 2009</ref> In March 2009, it was reported that in 2008, Barclays received billions of dollars from its insurance arrangements with [[American International Group|AIG]], including US$8.5 billion from funds provided by the United States to bail out AIG.<ref>{{cite news| title=Big European Banks Benefit from AIG Bailout| url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/29714822| first1=Mary| last1=Thompson| first2=Steve| last2=Liesman| date=5 August 2010| publisher=[[CNBC]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| first=Eamon| last=Javers| url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0309/20039.html| title=AIG ships billions in bailout abroad| work=[[Politico]]| date=15 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 June 2009, Barclays sold its Global Investors unit, which included its exchange-traded fund business, [[iShares]], to [[BlackRock]] for US$13.5 billion.<ref>{{cite news |agency=Press Association |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2009/jun/12/blackrock-to-buy-barclays-bank-arm |title=US giant BlackRock buys arm of Barclays bank |work=The Guardian |location=UK |accessdate=21 February 2010 |date=12 June 2009}}</ref> Standard Life sold Standard Life Bank to Barclays in October 2009. The sale was completed on 1 January 2010.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/8326313.stm Barclays buys Standard Life Bank] BBC News. 26 October 2009</ref> On 11 November 2009, Barclays and [[First Data]], a global technology provider of information commerce, had entered into an agreement according to which Barclays would migrate a range of card portfolios to First Data's issuing and consumer finance platform.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.finextra.com/fullpr.asp?id=30902 |title=First Data reports Barclays contract |publisher=Finextra.com |date=11 November 2009 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> On 13 February 2010, Barclays announced it would pay more than \u00a32&nbsp;billion in bonuses.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/8514650.stm |title=Barclays bank bonuses expected to reach \u00a32bn |publisher=BBC News |date=13 February 2010 |accessdate=21 February 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100220174039/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/8514650.stm| archivedate= 20 February 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> In March 2011 it was reported that Barclays had overtaken [[Santander UK]] to claim top spot as the UK's most complained against bank, with the country's official banking regulator, the [[Financial Services Authority]] having recorded 276,315 new customer complaints against Barclays Bank during the second half of 2010.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/barclays-tops-fsa-rankings-for-bank-complaints-2257800.html Barclays tops FSA rankings for bank complaints.] The Independent 31 March 2011</ref> Barclays nevertheless ranks only third in the UK among the mainstream clearing banks in terms of the number of its branches. Inline with costs cut, Barclays cut 1,400 jobs during the first half of 2011 and cut another 1,600 jobs for the rest of 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/08/02/us-barclays-idUSTRE77114Q20110802 |title=Barclays to cut 3,000 jobs as profit sags |date=2 August 2011 | publisher=Reuters}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2012, the trading names of Barclays Capital, Barclays Wealth and Barclays Corporate were each changed to simply \"Barclays\", as part of an effort to simplify the operations of the company and to promote greater integration between its divisions.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thisismoney.co.uk/money/news/article-2117723/Barclays-drops-Capital-Diamond-puts-end-BarCap-brand.html| title=Barclays drops the name 'Capital' from its investment bank division as the bank aligns under one name| accessdate=11 June 2012| work=This is Money| date=20 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2012 Barclaycard acquired Analog Analytics, a digital coupon and daily deal business similar to [[Groupon]].<ref name=LN1>{{cite web| last1=Bigelow| first1=Bruce| title=Barclaycard Acquires Social Couponing Startup Analog Analytics| url=http://www.xconomy.com/national/2012/06/04/barclaycard-acquires-social-couponing-startup-analog-analytics/| website=xconomy.com| accessdate=6 April 2015| ref=LN1}}</ref><ref name=LN2>{{cite web| last1=Kamanec| first1=Kara| title=Barclays Group PLC Member, Barclaycard, Purchases Analog Analytics| url=http://www.dailydealmedia.com/726barclays-group-plc-memeber-barclaycard-purchases-analog-analytics/| website=dailydealmedia.com| accessdate=6 April 2015|ref=LN2}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2012, Barclays announced it had agreed to buy the ING Direct UK business of the [[ING Group]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Barclays to acquire ING Direct UK |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-19880659 |publisher=BBC News |date=9 October 2012 |accessdate=19 June 2013}}</ref> The transfer of the business to Barclays was approved at the High Court on 20 February 2013 and ING Direct was renamed Barclays Direct and will be integrated into the existing Barclays business within two years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ingdirect.co.uk/saleannouncement.asp |title=Barclays welcomes customers of ING Direct UK |website=Barclays Direct |accessdate=19 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2013, Barclays announced a net loss of \u00a31.04&nbsp;billion for 2012, its first annual loss in two decades, together with plans to cut 3,700 jobs, reduce annual costs by \u00a31.7&nbsp;billion, and scale back its retail banking activities in Europe and Asia.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-02-12/barclays-to-cut-3-700-jobs-after-full-year-loss.html |title=Barclays to Cut 3,700 Jobs After Full-Year Loss |date=12 February 2013 | work=Bloomberg}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, Barclays announced it would cut 19,000 jobs over three years with 12,000 jobs cut in 2014. Investment banking will cut 2,000 jobs in 2014 and up to 7,000 jobs totally in 2016 making the investment banking portion shrink from 50 per cent in 2014 to 30 per cent of Barclay's assets in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ky3.com/news/business/Barclays-to-shed-19-000-jobs-over-three-years/21049046_25870878 |title=Barclays to shed 19,000 jobs over three years |first=Sophia |last=Yan |date=8 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140524062136/http://www.ky3.com/news/business/Barclays-to-shed-19-000-jobs-over-three-years/21049046_25870878 |archivedate=24 May 2014 |publisher=[[KYTV (TV)|KYTV News]]}}</ref>\n\nBarclays announced in June 2015 that it would sell its US wealth and investment management business to [[Stifel]] for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite news|author=Richa Naidu |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/06/08/us-barclayswealth-stifel-financial-m-a-idUSKBN0OO1CB20150608 |title=Stifel to buy former Lehman brokerage from Barclays |agency=Reuters |date=9 June 2015 |accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nBarclays sold its Retail Banking unit in Spain to [[CaixaBank]] in 2014. At its peak, Barclays had 5,100 employees and 600 offices in Spain. In 2014 the bank had 2,800 employees and 270 offices. With the sale, Caixabank acquired around 550,000 new retail and private banking clients and 2,400 employees.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/caixabank-to-buy-barclays-retail-banking-in-spain-1409515069| work=The Wall Street Journal| first=Jeannette| last=Neumann| title=Caixabank to Buy Barclays Retail Banking in Spain| date=1 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/fae5d374-3147-11e4-8313-00144feabdc0.html#axzz3hmjgufeX|title=Barclays loses \u00a3500m on sale of Spanish business |work=Financial Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-08-31/caixabank-to-buy-barclays-spain-units-for-1-05-billion| work=Bloomberg News| first=Charles| last=Penty| title=CaixaBank to Buy Barclays's Spanish Unit for 1.1 Billion| date=1 September 2014|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, it was announced that Barclays has plans to sell its Africa business amid falling profits.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/03/01/barclays-to-sell-african-bank-and-slash-dividend-as-profits-fall/ |title=Barclays to sell African bank and slash dividend as profits fall |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=1 March 2016 |first=Tim |last=Wallace |access-date=2 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, Barclays announced a deal that allowed its UK customers to use [[Apple Pay]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-35968102 |title=Barclays bank joins Apple Pay in UK |last=Kelion |first=Leo |work=BBC News |access-date=5 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe bank announced in May 2017 that it would sell \u00a31.5 billion worth of shares of its [[Barclays Africa Group]] subsidiary as part of its strategy to refocus its business from Africa to the UK and US.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-barclays-africa/barclays-shares-rise-on-report-of-africa-stake-sale-idUKKBN18R1KL|title=Barclays set to sell 1.5 billion pound stake in Africa business|date=31 May 2017|work=Reuters|access-date=8 September 2017}}</ref> In September 2017, Barclay's sold off the last part of its retail banking segment on continental [[Europe]] after selling its [[France|French]] retail, wealth and investment management operations to [[AnaCap Financial Partners|AnaCap]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/d3970784-0bc3-3ccf-95f7-83a051e4b1cc|title=Barclays continues pullback with final exit from European retail banking|last=|first=|date=|website=Financial Times|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nTo ward off the effects of [[Brexit]], Barclays borrowed \u00a36 billion from the [[Bank of England]] between April and June 2017, as part of a post-referendum stimulus package launched in August 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cityam.com/271591/barclays-and-lloyds-gbp10bn-borrowing-boost-bank-england|title=Barclays and Lloyds in \u00a310bn BoE borrowing boost|last=Jolly|first=Jasper|date=7 September 2017|access-date=8 September 2017|language=en}}</ref> The former boss of Barclays, [[Bob Diamond (banker)|Bob Diamond]], opined in an interview with ''[[The Independent]]'' in September 2017 that the [[City of London]] would feel a stronger negative impact from [[Brexit]] than generally expected.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/brexit-latest-bank-jobs-move-new-york-london-barclays-bob-diamond-eu-leave-a7935546.html|title=Ex-Barclays boss predicts Brexit-hit London will lose out to New York|date=8 September 2017|work=The Independent|access-date=8 September 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref> Diamond argued that both banking jobs and legal and support operations would eventually relocate to the [[Continental Europe|Continent]].<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n==Operations==\nBarclays' operations are organised within two business 'clusters': [[Wholesale banking|Corporate]] and [[Investment Banking]] and [[wealth management|Wealth]] and [[Investment management|Investment Management]]; and [[retail banking|Retail]] and [[business banking|Business Banking]].<ref name=grouporg>{{cite web |url=https://www.home.barclays/barclays-investor-relations/investing-in-barclays/fact-sheet.html |title=About Barclays |publisher=Group Barclays |accessdate=16 August 2017}}</ref> The Corporate and Investment Banking and Wealth and Investment Management cluster comprises three business units: Corporate banking; [[Barclays Investment Bank|Investment banking]]; and [[Barclays Wealth|Wealth and investment management]].<ref name=grouporg/> The Retail and Business Banking cluster comprises four business units: Africa Retail and Business Banking; [[Barclaycard]] (credit card and loan provision); Europe Retail and Business Banking; and UK Retail and Business Banking.<ref name=grouporg/>\n\n===Principal divisions and subsidiaries===\n[[File:Barclays group worldwide locations.png|thumb|A map showing the countries of the world in which Barclays currently has operations]]\nBarclays' principal divisions and subsidiaries include:\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Barclaycard]] \u2013 global credit card business\n* Barclays Bank LLC (Russia)\n* Barclays Bank plc \u2013 UK corporate bank\n* Barclays Bank UK plc \u2013 UK retail bank\n* Barclays Bank Delaware (formerly Barclaycard US, originally Juniper Bank, acquired 2003)\n* Barclays Corporate\n* Barclays Croatia\n* Barclays Execution Services\n* Barclays France\n* Barclays India\n* Barclays Indonesia<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/7865195.stm |title=Barclays slides after downgrade |publisher=BBC News |date=2 February 2009 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bankakita.co.id/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=38&Itemid=1 |title=Bank Akita News |accessdate=30 December 2009 |language=id |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721120204/http://www.bankakita.co.id/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=38&Itemid=1 |archive-date=21 July 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n* [[Barclays Investment Bank]]\n* Barclays Private Clients International \u2013 subsidiary based in the [[Isle of Man]] with branches in the [[Channel Islands]]\n* Barclays Morocco\n* Barclays Mauritius\n* [[First National Bank (South Africa)|Barclays National Bank]]: former vice chairman, [[Julian Ogilvie Thompson]].\n* Barclays Pakistan\n* Barclays Partner Finance\n* Barclays Portugal (162 branches)<ref name=spain>{{cite news |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/mergersNews/idUKL271397520080902 |title=Barclays mulls Spanish insurance stake sale |agency=Reuters |date=2 September 2008|accessdate=18 April 2011 |first=Steve |last=Slater}}</ref>\n* Barclays Rise (fintech accelerator with locations in New York, London, Manchester, Vilnius, Cape Town, Tel Aviv and Mumbai)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thinkrise.com/|title=Think Rise - Home|website=thinkrise.com|access-date=2 February 2017}}</ref>\n* Barclays Shared Services Chennai (India)\n* Barclays Shared Services Noida (India)\n* Barclays Technologies Centre China (closed)\n* Barclays Technologies Centre India\n* Barclays Technologies Centre Singapore (closed)\n* Barclays Technologies Centre Lithuania\n* [[Barclays Wealth]] \u2013 provides stockbroking and [[Offshore bank|offshore]] and [[private banking]]\n* Firstplus Financial Group plc\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Branches and ATMs===\n[[File:Barclays Bank, Park Lane Branch - geograph.org.uk - 218753.jpg|thumb|A Barclays branch on [[Park Lane (road)|Park Lane]] in London, United Kingdom]]\n[[File:Le Green Hall (Vilnius) (7692990530).jpg|thumb|Barclays office in [[Vilnius]], Lithuania]]\nBarclays has over 4,750 branches in about 55 countries and of which about 1,600 are in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/mergersNews/idUKLG49160920080916 |title=Key facts about Barclays |agency=Reuters |date=16 September 2008 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> In the UK, Barclays also offers some personal banking services through branches of the [[Post Office Ltd|Post Office]]. Most Barclays branches have 24/7 [[Automated teller machine|ATMs]]. Barclays customers and the customers of many other banks can use Barclays ATMs for free in the UK, although in some other countries fees are charged. Barclays is a member of the [[Global ATM Alliance]], an alliance of international banks which allows each banks' customers to use their ATM or [[debit card]] at all other member banks with no ATM access fees when travelling internationally.<ref>[http://www.atmmarketplace.com/article.php?id=1886 \"Five big banks form Global ATM Alliance\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070507142245/http://www.atmmarketplace.com/article.php?id=1886 |date=7 May 2007}}, ATMmarketplace.com. 9 January 2002. Retrieved 22 June 2007.</ref>\n\n===Senior management===\nThe Group Chairman is Nigel Higgins (ex-CEO of [[Rothschild & Co]]), who succeeded [[John McFarlane]] on 2 May 2019.\n\nOn 28 October 2015 Barclays announced that [[Jes Staley]], managing partner at [[BlueMountain Capital]], ex-CEO of [[J.P. Morgan & Co.]] and member of the board of directors of [[UBS]], has been appointed as Group Chief Executive Officer of Barclays effective 1 December 2015.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.home.barclays/news/2015/10/barclays-appoints-jamesestaley-as-group-chief-executive.html| title=Barclays appoints James E. Staley as Group Chief Executive| publisher=Barclays}}</ref>\n\n====Group Executive Committee==== \n\nThe current members of Barclays' Executive Committee are:<ref name=\"leadership\">{{cite web |title=Barclays Leadership |url=https://home.barclays/who-we-are/structure-and-leadership/leadership/ |website=home.barclays |accessdate=14 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Jes Staley]] (Group Chief Executive Officer)\n* Tushar Morzaria (Group Finance Director)\n* Matt Hammerstein (Chief Executive Officer of Barclays UK)\n* Paul Compton (President of Barclays Bank PLC (BBPLC))\n* Mark Ashton-Rigby (Group Chief Operating Officer and Chief Executive Officer of Barclays Execution Services (BX))\n* Ashok Vaswani (Global Head of Consumer Banking and Payments)\n* Stephen Dainton (Global Head of Markets)\n* Joe McGrath (Global Head of Banking)\n* Alistair Currie (Global Head of Corporate Banking)\n* Bob Hoyt (Group General Counsel)\n* Tristram Roberts (Group Human Resources Director)\n* Laura Padovani (Group Chief Compliance Officer)\n* C. S. Venkatakrishnan (Group Chief Risk Officer)\n* Lindsay O'Reilly (Group Chief Internal Auditor)\n\n====Board of directors====\n\nThe current members of Barclays'Group board of directors are:<ref name=\"leadership\"/>\n* Nigel Higgins (Group Chairman)\n* [[Jes Staley]] (Group Chief Executive)\n* Tushar Morzaria (Group Finance Director)\n* [[Ian Cheshire (businessman)|Sir Ian Cheshire]] (Chairman of Barclays Bank UK PLC and Barclays Group Non-Executive Director)\n* Mary Francis CBE (Barclays Group Non-Executive Director)\n* Diane Schueneman (Barclays Group Non-Executive Director)\n* Mike Ashley (Barclays Group Non-Executive Director)\n* Tim Breedon CBE (Barclays Group Non-Executive Director)\n* Crawford Gilles (Senior Independent Director)\n* Mary Anne Citrino (Barclays Group Non-Executive Director)\n* Dawn Fitzpatrick (Barclays Group Non-Executive Director)\n* Matthew Lester (Barclays Group Non-Executive Director)\n\n==Sponsorships==\n[[File:Barclays Cycle Hire, St. Mary Axe, Aldgate.jpg|thumb|right|A [[Barclays Cycle Hire]] docking station in central London]]\nBarclays sponsored the [[2008 Dubai Tennis Championships]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dubaitennischampionships.com/ |title=Dubai Tennis Championships |publisher=Dubai Tennis Championships |date=20 February 2011 |accessdate=18 April 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204233458/http://www.dubaitennischampionships.com/ |archivedate=4 December 2008 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nBarclays was the sponsor of the [[Barclays Cycle Hire]] scheme in London from 2010 to 2015, as part of a \u00a325&nbsp;million deal with Transport for London.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2010/jul/27/boris-johnson-london-cycle-hire-barclays |title=Boris Johnson's London Cycle Hire scheme flogs our birthright to Barclays |accessdate=28 April 2012 |work=The Guardian |date=27 July 2010 |first=Justin |last=McGuirk}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10182833 |title=Barclays' \u00a325m sponsorship of London cycle hire scheme |accessdate=28 April 2012 |publisher=BBC News |date=28 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n===Compensation to Jewish Holocaust survivors===\nIn 1998, Barclays Bank agreed to pay $3.6m to Jews whose assets were seized from French branches of the British-based bank during World War II.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news| title=Barclays to Compensate Jews| work=[[BBC News]]| publisher=BBC.com| date=17 December 1998| accessdate=13 September 2013| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/237392.stm}}</ref> Barclays, along with seven French banks, was named in a lawsuit filed in New York on behalf of Jews who were unable to reclaim money they deposited during the Nazi era.<ref name=\"bbc\"/>\n\n===Financial support for the government in Zimbabwe===\nBarclays helped to fund President [[Robert Mugabe]]'s government in [[Zimbabwe]].<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article2848046.ece Barclays bankrolls Mugabe\u2019s brutal regime] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007172946/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article2848046.ece |date=7 October 2008}}</ref> The most controversial of a set of loans provided by Barclays is the \u00a330 million it gave to help sustain land reforms that saw Mugabe seize white-owned farmland and drive more than 100,000 black workers from their homes. Opponents have called the bank's involvement a 'disgrace' and an 'insult' to the millions who have suffered human rights abuses.<ref>{{cite news |first1=Antony |last1=Barnett |first2=Christopher |last2=Thompson |url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/2007/jan/28/accounts.Zimbabwenews |title=Barclays' millions help to prop up Mugabe regime |work=The Guardian |location=Manchester |date=28 January 2007 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> Barclays spokesmen say the bank has had customers in Zimbabwe for decades and abandoning them now would make matters worse, \"We are committed to continuing to provide a service to those customers in what is clearly a difficult operating environment\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Macleod |first=Murdo |url=http://news.scotsman.com/zimbabwe/Barclays-helping-to-fund-Mugabe.3497546.jp |title=Barclays' 'helping to fund Mugabe regime' |work=The Scotsman |date=11 November 2007 |accessdate=18 April 2011 |location=Edinburgh}}</ref>\n\nBarclays also provides two of Mugabe's associates with bank accounts, ignoring European Union sanctions on Zimbabwe.<ref>{{cite web|last=Macleod |first=Murdo |url=http://scotlandonsunday.scotsman.com/zimbabwe/Barclays-helping-to-fund-Mugabe.3497546.jp |title=Barclays 'helping to fund Mugabe regime' |work=The Scotsman |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> The men are Elliot Manyika and minister of public service Nicholas Goche. Barclays has defended its position by insisting that the EU rules do not apply to its 67%-owned Zimbabwean subsidiary because it was incorporated outside the EU.<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/africa/article4232283.ece Robert Mugabe henchmen backed by Barclays] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604144412/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/africa/article4232283.ece |date=4 June 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Accusations of money laundering===\nIn March 2009, Barclays was accused of violating international anti-[[money laundering]] laws. According to the NGO [[Global Witness]], the Paris branch of Barclays held the account of Equatorial Guinean President [[Teodoro Obiang Nguema Mbasogo|Teodoro Obiang]]'s son, [[Teodoro Nguema Obiang Mangue|Teodorin Obiang]], even after evidence that Obiang had siphoned oil revenues from government funds emerged in 2004. According to Global Witness, Obiang purchased a [[Ferrari]] and maintains a mansion in [[Malibu, California|Malibu]] with the funds from this account.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/7936335.stm |title= Barclays 'corrupt regime' claim |accessdate=9 March 2009 |last=Shankleman |first=Martin |date=11 March 2009 |publisher=BBC News |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090314035815/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/7936335.stm |archivedate=14 March 2009| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA 2010 report by the Wall Street Journal described how [[Credit Suisse]], Barclays, [[Lloyds Banking Group]], and other banks were involved in helping the [[Alavi Foundation]], [[Bank Melli Iran|Bank Melli]], the Iranian government, and/or others circumvent US laws banning financial transactions with certain states. They did this by 'stripping' information out of wire transfers, thereby concealing the source of funds. Barclays settled with the government for US$298&nbsp;million.<ref>\"Probe Circles Globe to Find Dirty Money\", Carrick Mollenkamp, ''The Wall Street Journal'', 3 September 2010</ref>\n\n===Tax avoidance===\n{{further|tax avoidance}}\nIn March 2009, Barclays obtained an injunction against ''[[The Guardian]]'' to remove from its website confidential leaked documents describing how SCM, Barclays' structured capital markets division, planned to use more than \u00a311 billion of loans to create hundreds of millions of pounds of tax benefits, via \"an elaborate circuit of [[Cayman Islands]] companies, US partnerships and [[Luxembourg]] subsidiaries\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2009/mar/17/barclays-guardian-injunction-tax |title=Barclays gags Guardian over tax |work=[[The Guardian]] |date= 17 March 2009|accessdate=2 February 2012 |location=London}}</ref> In an editorial on the issue, ''The Guardian'' pointed out that, due to the mismatch of resources, tax-collectors ([[HMRC]]) now have to rely on websites such as [[WikiLeaks]] to obtain such documents,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2009/mar/17/barclays-tax-secret-documents |title=Editorial: Barclays' secret documents |work=The Guardian |date=24 January 2012 |accessdate=2 February 2012 |location=London}}</ref> and indeed the documents in question have now appeared on WikiLeaks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/wiki/The_Guardian:_Censored_Barclays_tax_avoidance_leaked_memos%2C_16_Mar_2009 |title=Barclays Bank gags Guardian over leaked memos detailing offshore tax scam |publisher=WikiLeaks |date=16 March 2009 |accessdate=2 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090414025059/http://wikileaks.org/wiki/The_Guardian%3A_Censored_Barclays_tax_avoidance_leaked_memos%2C_16_Mar_2009 |archivedate=14 April 2009  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://weblogs3.nrc.nl/klaver/2009/03/17/guardian-moet-documenten-van-site-verwijderen/ |title=Marie-Jose Klaver \" Guardian moet documenten van site verwijderen |work=NRC Handelsblad |accessdate=2 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120802105804/http://weblogs3.nrc.nl/klaver/2009/03/17/guardian-moet-documenten-van-site-verwijderen/ |archivedate=2 August 2012 }}</ref> Separately, another Barclays [[whistleblower]] revealed several days later that the SCM transactions had produced between \u00a3900 million and \u00a31 billion in tax avoidance in one year, adding that \"The deals start with tax and then commercial purpose is added to them.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Felicity Lawrence and [[David Leigh (journalist)|David Leigh]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2009/mar/19/new-barclays-tax-whistleblower-claims |title=New whistleblower claims over \u00a31bn Barclays tax deals |work=The Guardian |date= 19 March 2009 |accessdate=2 February 2012 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012 Barclays was forced to pay \u00a3500&nbsp;million in tax which it had tried to avoid. Barclays was accused by [[HMRC]] of designing two schemes that were intended to avoid substantial amounts of tax. Tax rules forced the bank to tell the UK authorities about its plans.<ref name=\"BBCFeb28\">{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-17181213| title=Barclays Bank told by Treasury to pay \u00a3500 million avoided tax| work=[[BBC News]]| accessdate=29 February 2012| date=28 February 2012}}</ref> [[David Gauke]], [[Exchequer Secretary to the Treasury]], said that \"We do not take today's action lightly, but the potential tax loss from this scheme and the history of previous abuse in this area mean that this is a circumstance where the decision to change the law with full retrospective effect is justified.\"<ref name=\"BBCFeb28\"/>\n\n===Rate-fixing scandal===\n{{main|Libor scandal}}\nIn June 2012, as a result of an international investigation, Barclays Bank was fined a total of \u00a3290&nbsp;million (US$450&nbsp;million) for manipulating the daily settings of London Interbank Offered Rate ([[Libor]]) and the Euro Interbank Offered Rate ([[Euribor]]). The United States Department of Justice and Barclays officially agreed that \"the manipulation of the submissions affected the fixed rates on some occasions\".<ref name=\"usdoj statement of facts\">{{cite web| url=http://www.justice.gov/iso/opa/resources/9312012710173426365941.pdf | title=Statement of Facts| publisher=United States Department of Justice| date=26 June 2012| accessdate=11 July 2012}}</ref> The bank was found to have made 'inappropriate submissions' of rates which formed part of the Libor and Euribor setting processes, sometimes to make a profit, and other times to make the bank look more secure during the financial crisis.<ref name=bbc_libor_manipulation/> This happened between 2005 and 2009, as often as daily.<ref name=cbs_libor_manipulation/>\n\nThe [[BBC]] said revelations concerning the fraud were \"greeted with almost universal astonishment in the banking industry.\"<ref>{{cite news| first=Ian| last=Pollock| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-18622907| title=Libor scandal: Who might have lost?| work=BBC News |date=28 June 2012| accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> The UK's [[Financial Services Authority]] (FSA), which levied a fine of \u00a359.5&nbsp;million ($92.7&nbsp;million), gave Barclays the biggest fine it had ever imposed in its history.<ref name=cbs_libor_manipulation>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-505123_162-57462315/barclays-to-pay-$453m-for-attempting-to-manipulate-rates/| title=Barclays to pay largest civil fine in CFTC history| work=CBS News| date=27 June 2012| accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref> The FSA's director of enforcement described Barclays' behaviour as \"completely unacceptable\", adding \"Libor is an incredibly important benchmark reference rate, and it is relied on for many, many hundreds of thousands of contracts all over the world.\"<ref name=bbc_libor_manipulation/> The bank's chief executive [[Bob Diamond (banker)|Bob Diamond]] decided to give up his bonus as a result of the fine.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/business/2012-06/28/c_123339718.htm| title=Barclays to pay over 450 million dollars to settle charges regarding LIBOR| agency=Xinhua News Agency| date=27 June 2012| accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref> [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] politician [[Lord Oakeshott]] criticised Diamond, saying: \"If he had any shame he would go. If the Barclays board has any backbone, they'll sack him.\"<ref name=bbc_libor_manipulation>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-18612279|title=Barclays fined for attempts to manipulate Libor rates |publisher=BBC News |date=27 June 2012 |accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref> The US Department of Justice has also been involved, with \"other financial institutions and individuals\" under investigation.<ref name=bbc_libor_manipulation/> On 2 July 2012, Marcus Agius resigned from the chairman position following the interest rate rigging scandal.<ref>{{cite news |agency=Reuters |title=Barclays chairman resigns over interest rate rigging scandal |url=http://profit.ndtv.com/News/Article/barclays-chairman-to-resign-over-interest-rate-rigging-scandal-307175 |accessdate=2 July 2012 |newspaper=NDTV profit |date=2 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120704215734/http://profit.ndtv.com/News/Article/barclays-chairman-to-resign-over-interest-rate-rigging-scandal-307175 |archivedate=4 July 2012  }}</ref> On 3 July 2012, Bob Diamond resigned with immediate effect, leaving Marcus Agius to fill his post until a replacement is found.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-18685040 |title=Barclays boss Bob Diamond resigns amid Libor scandal |publisher=BBC News |date=3 July 2012 |accessdate=30 July 2012}}</ref> Within the space of a few hours, this was followed by the resignation of the Bank's chief operating officer, Jerry del Missier.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://business.inquirer.net/68943/bob-diamond-quits-as-barclays-ceo |title=Bob Diamond quits as Barclays CEO |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |accessdate=25 April 2014}}</ref> Barclays subsequently announced that Antony Jenkins, its existing chief executive of Global Retail & Business Banking would become group chief executive on 30 August 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=25068045&ticker=BARC:LN |title=Executive Profile Antony P. Jenkins |publisher=[[Bloomberg Business]] |date=23 June 2015}}</ref> On 17 February 2014 the [[Serious Fraud Office (United Kingdom)|Serious Fraud Office]] charged three former bank employees with manipulating Libor rates between June 2005 and August 2007.<ref name=\"SFO-arrests\">{{cite news |url=http://www.londonmercury.com/index.php/sid/220121417/scat/fad6c6ce3bc72160/ht/Three-former-Barclays-staff-charged-for-alleged-Libor-rates-manipulation |archive-url=https://archive.today/20140218021810/http://www.londonmercury.com/index.php/sid/220121417/scat/fad6c6ce3bc72160/ht/Three-former-Barclays-staff-charged-for-alleged-Libor-rates-manipulation |url-status=dead |archive-date=18 February 2014 |title=Three former Barclays staff charged for alleged Libor rates manipulation |work=London Mercury |date=17 February 2014 }}</ref> Four employees were jailed in July 2016 for up to six-and-a-half years, with two others cleared after a retrial.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-39514924|title=Traders found not guilty in Libor retrial|last=Johnston|first=Chris|date=2017-04-06|access-date=2019-04-28|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===Qatari capital raising regulatory investigations===\nBarclays' June and November 2008 capital raisings are the subject of investigations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.euromoney.com/Article/3198818/Category/17/ChannelPage/0/Barclays-Qatari-capital-raising-timeline.html |title=Barclays' Qatari capital-raising timeline |work=Euromoney |date=21 May 2013}}</ref>\nThe UK's [[Serious Fraud Office (United Kingdom)|Serious Fraud Office]] commenced its investigation in August 2012. In October 2012, the [[United States Department of Justice]] and the [[US Securities and Exchange Commission]] informed Barclays they had commenced an investigation into whether the group's relationships with third parties who assist Barclays to win or retain business are compliant with the US [[Foreign Corrupt Practices Act]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://reports.barclays.com/ar12/financialstatements/notes/accrualsprovisionslegalproceedingsandcontingentliabilities/30competitionandregulatorymatters.html |title=30 Competition and regulatory matters \u2013 Annual Report 2012 |publisher=Barclays.com}}</ref>\nThe [[Financial Services Authority]] announced an expansion of the investigation into the Barclays-Qatar deal in January 2013, focusing on the disclosure surrounding the ownership of the securities in the bank.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/47d412ce-6bd1-11e2-a700-00144feab49a.html |title=Barclays in Qatar loan probe |work=Financial Times |date=31 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nBarclays had sought to raise capital privately, avoiding direct equity investment from the [[Government of the United Kingdom]] and, therefore, a bailout. The result was Abu Dhabi's \u00a33.5&nbsp;billion investment in the bank, a deal in which [[Sheikh Mansour bin Zayed al Nahyan|H.H. Sheikh Mansour bin Zayed Al Nahyan]] made a profit of \u00a33.5&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.euromoney.com/Article/3198637/Category/17/ChannelPage/0/Revealed-The-truth-about-Barclays-and-the-Abu-Dhabi-investment.html |title=Revealed: The truth about Barclays and the Abu Dhabi investment |publisher=Euromoney.com |date=30 April 2013}}</ref>\nMuch of the focus to date has been on the injections by Qatar in June and November 2008, notably the so far unproven allegation that Barclays lent Qatar the money to invest in the bank. Other questions include what happened to the \u00a3110&nbsp;million in fees paid by Barclays ostensibly to Sheikh Mansour, and the \u00a366&nbsp;million provided by Barclays to the Qataris for unexplained \"advisory fees\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.euromoney.com/Article/3198635/Barclays-needs-to-come-clean-about-its-Gulf-investments.html |title=Barclays needs to come clean about its Gulf investments |publisher=Euromoney.com |date=30 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, following a five-year investigation by the UK's [[Serious Fraud Office (United Kingdom)|Serious Fraud Office]] covering Barclays' activities during the [[financial crisis of 2007\u20132008]], former CEO [[John Silvester Varley|John Varley]] and three former colleagues, [[Roger Jenkins (banker)|Roger Jenkins]], [[Thomas Kalaris]] and [[Richard Boath]], were charged with [[Conspiracy to defraud|conspiracy to commit fraud]] and the provision of [[Financial assistance (share purchase)|unlawful financial assistance]] in connection with capital raising.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-40338220 |title=Barclays charged with fraud in Qatar case |work=BBC News |date=1 January 1970 |accessdate=20 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Jill |last=Treanor |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2017/jun/20/sfo-charges-barclays-bank-executives-ceo-2008-qatar-fundraising |title=Senior Barclays bankers charged with fraud over credit crunch fundraising |work=The Guardian |date=1 January 1970 |accessdate=20 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, the Serious Fraud Office charged Barclays with \"unlawful financial assistance\" related to billions of pounds raised from the Qatar deal.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-43029731|title=Barclays Bank charged over Qatar loans| date=12 February 2018| work=BBC News| access-date=12 February 2018| language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===US electricity market manipulation===\nIn July 2013 US energy regulator the [[Federal Energy Regulatory Commission]] (FERC) ordered Barclays to pay \u00a3299 million fine penalty for attempting to manipulate the electricity market in the US. The fine by FERC relates to allegations in December 2008.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/jul/17/us-energy-regulator-barclays-fine US energy regulator orders Barclays to pay \u00a3299m fine] The Guardian 17 July 2013</ref>\n\n===Gold price manipulation===\nIn May 2014 the [[Financial Conduct Authority]] fined the bank \u00a326&nbsp;million over systems and controls failures, and conflict of interest in relation to the bank and its customers in connection to the [[gold fixing]] during the period 2004\u20132013, and for manipulation of the gold price on 28 June 2012.<ref name=\"GoldFixing\">{{cite news| title=FCA fines Barclays 26mn pounds over gold price manipulation| url=http://www.thelondonnews.net/index.php/sid/222273039/scat/3a8a80d6f705f8cc/ht/FCA-fines-Barclays-26mn-pounds-over-gold-price-manipulation| accessdate=23 May 2014| publisher=The London News.Net| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525200522/http://www.thelondonnews.net/index.php/sid/222273039/scat/3a8a80d6f705f8cc/ht/FCA-fines-Barclays-26mn-pounds-over-gold-price-manipulation| archive-date=25 May 2014| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===US lawsuit alleging dark pool fraud===\nIn June 2014 the US state of New York filed a lawsuit against the bank alleging it defrauded and deceived investors with inaccurate marketing material about its unregulated trading system known as a ''[[dark pool]]''. Specifically, the firm was accused of hiding the fact that [[Tradebot]] participated in the dark pool when they were in fact one of the largest players. The state, in its complaint, said it was being assisted by former Barclays executives and it was seeking unspecified damages. The bank's shares dropped 5% on news of the lawsuit, prompting an announcement to the [[London Stock Exchange]] by the bank saying it was taking the allegations seriously, and was co-operating with the [[New York attorney general]].<ref name=\"BarclaysVsNY\">{{cite news| title=Dark pool fraud lawsuit filed against Barclays in US| url=http://www.newyorktelegraph.com/index.php/sid/223293195/scat/3a8a80d6f705f8cc/ht/Dark-pool-fraud-lawsuit-filed-against-Barclays-in-US| archive-url=https://archive.today/20140628010744/http://www.newyorktelegraph.com/index.php/sid/223293195/scat/3a8a80d6f705f8cc/ht/Dark-pool-fraud-lawsuit-filed-against-Barclays-in-US| url-status=dead| archive-date=28 June 2014| date=27 June 2014| work=New York Telegraph| accessdate=16 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nA month later the bank filed a motion for the suit to be dismissed, saying there had been no fraud, no victims and no harm to anyone. The New York Attorney General's office issued a statement saying the attorney general was confident the motion would fail.<ref name=\"BarclaysDefense\">{{cite news| title=Barclays seeks dismissal of New York dark pool suit| url=http://www.thelondonnews.net/index.php/sid/224095831/scat/3a8a80d6f705f8cc/ht/Barclays-seeks-dismissal-of-New-York-dark-pool-suit| archive-url=https://archive.today/20140806065744/http://www.thelondonnews.net/index.php/sid/224095831/scat/3a8a80d6f705f8cc/ht/Barclays-seeks-dismissal-of-New-York-dark-pool-suit| url-status=dead| archive-date=6 August 2014| accessdate=25 July 2014| publisher=The London News.Net}}</ref> On 31 January 2016, Barclays settled with both the New York Attorney General's office and the SEC, agreeing to pay $70 million split evenly between the SEC and New York state, admitting it violated securities laws and agreeing to install an independent monitor for the dark pool.<ref name=\"BarclaysSettlement\">{{cite news| title=Barclays, Credit Suisse strike record deals with SEC, NY over dark pools| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/sec-new-york-darkpools-idUSL2N15G0KS| accessdate=1 February 2015| publisher=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n===Exchange-rate rigging (last-look system)===\nBarclays agreed to pay $150 million to resolve an investigation by New York's banking regulator into a trading practice that allowed the bank to exploit a milliseconds-long lag between an order and its execution that sometimes hurt its clients, the latest fallout from the bank's foreign-exchange business.<ref name=\"WSJ_BarclaysLastLook\">{{cite news| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/barclays-to-pay-150-million-over-last-look-trading-system-1447860696| title=Barclays to Pay $150 Million Over 'Last Look' Trading System| first=Christopher M.| last=Matthews| date=18 November 2015| work=The Wall Street Journal| accessdate=19 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn certain instances, Barclays used this [[Last look (foreign exchange)|last-look]] system to automatically reject client orders that would be unprofitable for the bank because of subsequent price swings during milliseconds-long latency (\"hold\") periods. Furthermore, when clients questioned Barclays about these rejected trades, Barclays failed to disclose the reason that the trades were being rejected, instead citing technical issues or providing vague responses.<ref name=\"NYDoFS_BarclaysLastLook\">{{cite press release| title=NYDFS Announces Barclays to Pay Additional $150 Million Penalty, Terminate Employee for Automated, Electronic Foreign Exchange Trading Misconduct| publisher=New York Department of Financial Services| url=http://www.dfs.ny.gov/about/press/pr1511181.htm| date=18 November 2015| accessdate=19 March 2016| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160318213118/http://www.dfs.ny.gov/about/press/pr1511181.htm| archive-date=18 March 2016| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Unsuitable mutual fund transactions===\nAccording to the [[Financial Industry Regulatory Authority]], Barclays' inadequate supervisory procedures failed to stop many customers from swapping one mutual fund for another when the benefits of switching might be undermined by the transaction costs, resulting in $8.63 million of losses for their customers between January 2010 and June 2015. Additionally, from March to August 2014, Barclays processed 1,723 fund transactions that were inconsistent with its customers' goals, risk tolerance or other investments which caused an additional $818,000 of customer harm. As a result, Barclays was required to pay $10 million in restitution, including interest, to affected customers and was fined $3.75 million, but did not admit or deny wrongdoing.<ref>{{cite news|title=Barclays in $13.75 mln U.S. settlement over mutual funds|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/barclays-mutualfunds-settlement-idUSL1N14I0VX20151229|accessdate=1 February 2015|publisher=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n=== Staff monitoring ===\n<span name=\"OLE_LINK20\"></span>In a pilot programme at its London headquarters, the company used tracking software to assess how long employees spent at their desks and warn them if they took excessive breaks. Staff who spent too much time away could find this mentioned on their daily report cards. Following criticisms by staff, the bank said it had taken steps to ensure that individual data would no longer be visible to managers.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/feb/20/barlays-using-dytopian-big-brother-tactics-to-spy-on-staff-says-tuc|title=Barclays using 'Big Brother' tactics to spy on staff, says TUC|last=|first=|date=20 February 2020|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> \n\n<span name=\"OLE_LINK20\"></span>The bank faced similar privacy concerns in 2017 when it used OccupEye sensors to track staff through black boxes in their desks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/barclays-bank-sensors-a7901566.html|title=Barclays installs sensors to see which bankers are at their desks|last=|first=|date=19 August 2017|website=The Independent|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* The bank faced similar privacy concerns in 2017 over its use of OccupEye sensors that tracked staff through black boxes installed under their desks.\n* {{cite book|last=[[Anthony Tuke (1897\u20131975)|Tuke]]|first=A. W.|title=Barclays Bank Limited, 1926\u20131969: Some Recollections|year=1972|publisher=Barclays Bank Ltd|location=London|isbn=978-0-9500442-8-6|author2=Gillman, R. J. H.}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Banks|Business and economics|Companies|London}}\n* [[List of largest banks]]\n* [[Chip Authentication Program]] (PINsentry)\n* [[European Financial Services Roundtable]]\n* [[List of banks in the United Kingdom]]\n* [http://www.bankinghistory.org eabh (The European Association for Banking and Financial History e.V.)]\n\n==Notes==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book|last=Gamble|first=Audrey Nona|title=A History of the Bevan Family|url=https://archive.org/details/historyofbevanfa00gamb|year=1924|publisher=Headley Brothers|location=London|oclc=18546896}}\n* Raychaudhuri, Tappan, Irfan Habib, & Dharma Kumar, eds. (1983) ''The Cambridge Economic History of India: Volume 2, c.1751-c.1970''. (CUP Archive). {{ISBN|9780521228022}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.thebanker.com/Top-1000-World-Banks|accessdate=18 April 2011|title=Top 1000 World Banks 2010|work=[[The Banker]]}}\n*{{cite news|title=Amer Sajed appointed Chief Executive of Barclaycard|url=http://www.pressat.co.uk/releases/amer-sajed-appointed-chief-executive-of-barclaycard-761ce1df44019f8478cf490e1f2f7ea5/}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Barclays}}\n* {{official website|http://home.barclays}}\n* {{OpenCorp|Barclays}}\n* {{PM20|FID=co/002559|TEXT=Documents and clippings about|NAME=}}\n\n{{Barclays}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list =\n{{Commercial and retail banks in the United Kingdom}}\n{{FTSE 100 Index constituents}}\n{{Members of Euro Banking Association}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Barclays|*]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in the 1690s]]\n[[Category:Banks established in the 17th century]]\n[[Category:Banks of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the London Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the New York Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Companies formerly listed on the Tokyo Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies based in London]]\n[[Category:Systemically important financial institutions]]\n[[Category:1690 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Companies based in the London Borough of Tower Hamlets]]\n[[Category:British brands]]\n[[Category:Clan Barclay]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the British banking firm|items that may be pluralised as \"Barclays\"|Barclay (disambiguation)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Barclays plc<!--Please do not change to Barclays Bank PLC, which is a subsidiary of the holding company-->\n| logo = Barclays logo.svg\n| logo_size = 250px\n| image = Barclays HQ.jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| image_caption = The Barclays Head Office in London\n| type = [[Public limited company]]\n| traded_as = {{lse|BARC|fourway=GB0031348658GBGBXSET0}}<br>{{nyse|BCS}}<br>[[FTSE 100 Index|FTSE 100 Component]]\n| industry = [[Bank]]ing<br>[[Financial services]]\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|1690|11|17|df=yes}} in the [[City of London]], [[Kingdom of England]]\n| location_city = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| key_people = Nigel Higgins<br>{{small|(Group Chairman)}}<br>[[Jes Staley]]<br>{{small|(Group Chief Executive)}}\n| products = [[Retail Banking]]<br>[[Commercial Banking]]<br>[[Investment Banking]]<br>[[Wholesale Banking]]<br>[[Private Banking]]<br>[[Wealth Management]]\n| revenue = {{increase}} [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]21.632 billion (2019)<ref name=ar>{{cite web |url=https://home.barclays/content/dam/home-barclays/documents/investor-relations/ResultAnnouncements/2019FYResults/20200213-Barclays-PLC-FY19-Results-Announcement.pdf |title=Annual Results 2019 |accessdate=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n| operating_income = {{increase}} \u00a34.357 billion (2019)<ref name=ar/>\n| net_income = {{increase}} \u00a33.354 billion (2019)<ref name=ar/>\n| assets = {{increase}} \u00a31.140 trillion (2019)<ref name=ar/>\n| equity = {{increase}} \u00a364.429 billion (2019)<ref name=ar/>\n| num_employees = 85,000 (2020)<ref>{{cite web| url=https://joinus.barclays/eme/about-us/| title=About us| publisher=Barclays| accessdate=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n| divisions = Barclays UK<br>[[Barclays Investment Bank]]<br>Barclays Corporate Bank<br>Barclays Private Bank<br>Barclays Payments<br>Barclays US Consumer Bank\n| homepage = {{URL|https://www.barclays.co.uk/}}\n}}\n\n'''Barclays plc<!--Please do not change to Barclays Bank plc, which is a subsidiary of the holding company Barclays plc. It is legally abbreviated to plc not PLC.-->''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|\u0251\u02d0r|k|l|i|z|,_|-|l|e\u026a|z}})<!--Please do not remove /r/ after /\u0251\u02d0/, since Wikipedia guidelines for English Pronunciation recommend a diaphonemic transcription, an abstraction of speech sounds that accommodate General American, Received Pronunciation, Canadian English, South African, Australian, and New Zealand pronunciations; i.e rhotic and non rhotic pronunciations.--> is a British multinational [[Investment banking|investment bank]]<!-- Its investment banking arm is a separate institution to its financial services. They are separate components that add up to the diversified services of the company. Leave as \"investment bank and financial services company\".--> and [[financial services]] company, headquartered in [[London]]. Apart from investment banking, Barclays is organised into four core businesses: [[Retail banking|personal banking]], [[Commercial bank|corporate banking]], [[wealth management]], and [[investment management]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.home.barclays/about-barclays/business-structure.html| title=Business Structure| publisher=Barclays}}</ref>\n\nBarclays traces its origins to the [[goldsmith]] banking business established in the City of London in 1690.<ref name=archives>{{citation| url=https://www.archive.barclays.com/items/show/5419| title=Barclays \u2013 A Quick History| publisher=archive.barclays.com| accessdate=16 August 2017}}</ref> James Barclay became a partner in the business in 1736. In 1896, several banks in London and the English provinces, including [[Backhouse's Bank]] and [[Gurney's Bank]], united as a [[joint-stock company|joint-stock]] bank under the name Barclays and Co. Over the following decades, Barclays expanded to become a nationwide bank. In 1967, Barclays deployed the world's first [[Automated teller machine|cash dispenser]]. Barclays has made numerous corporate acquisitions, including of London, Provincial and South Western Bank in 1918, [[British Linen Bank]] in 1919, Mercantile Credit in 1975, [[the Woolwich]] in 2000 and the North American operations of [[Lehman Brothers]] in 2008.\n\nBarclays has a primary listing on the [[London Stock Exchange]] and is a constituent of the [[FTSE 100 Index]]. It has a secondary listing on the [[New York Stock Exchange]]. \n\nAccording to a 2011 paper by Vitali et al., Barclays was the most powerful [[transnational corporation]] in terms of ownership and thus [[corporate power|corporate control]] over [[Global financial system|global financial stability]] and [[market competition]], with [[Axa]] and [[State Street Corporation]] taking the 2nd and 3rd positions, respectively.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://images.zeit.de/wissen/2012-05/s37-infografik-wirtschaft.pdf |title=Wem geh\u00f6rt die Welt? |accessdate=16 August 2017 |url-status=dead |trans-title=Who owns the world? | work=[[Die Zeit]] |date=31 March 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161004225112/http://images.zeit.de/wissen/2012-05/s37-infografik-wirtschaft.pdf |archivedate=4 October 2016 |language=German}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title=The Network of Global Corporate Control| first1=Stefania| last1=Vitali| first2=James B.| last2=Glattfelder| first3=Stefano| last3=Battiston| last-author-amp=yes| journal= PLOS ONE|volume = 6|issue = 10|pages = e25995| date=26 October 2011| doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0025995|pmid = 22046252|pmc = 3202517| arxiv=1107.5728|bibcode = 2011PLoSO...625995V}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===1690 to 1900===\nBarclays traces its origins back to 1690 when [[John Freame]], a [[Quaker]], and Thomas Gould started trading as [[goldsmith]] bankers in [[Lombard Street, London]]. The name \"Barclays\" became associated with the business in 1736, when Freame's son-in-law James Barclay became a partner.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aboutbarclays.co.uk/content/detail.asp?NewsAreaID=138 |accessdate=30 January 2007 |title=Company History |work=Barclays Newsroom: Business History\n|publisher=Barclays}} See also: ''Barclays: The Business of Banking, 1690\u20131996'' by Margaret Ackrill and Leslie Hannah; Cambridge UP, 2001 {{ISBN|0-521-79035-2}}</ref> In 1728 the bank moved to 54 Lombard Street, identified by the 'Sign of the Black Spread [[Eagle (heraldry)|Eagle]]', which in subsequent years would become a core part of the bank's visual identity.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aboutbarclays.co.uk/content/detail.asp?NewsAreaID=138 |accessdate=11 May 2008 |title=Company History |work=Barclays.lk \u2013 About us: Our History {{!}} 1690\u20131972 |publisher=Barclays}}</ref>\n\nThe Barclay family were connected with slavery, both as proponents and opponents. David and Alexander Barclay were engaged in the slave trade in 1756.<ref>{{cite book |last=Williams |first=Eric |date=1964 |title=Slavery and Capitalism |location=London |publisher= Deutsch|page=116 }}</ref> [[David Barclay of Youngsbury]] (1729\u20131809), on the other hand, was a noted [[abolitionism in the United Kingdom|abolitionist]], and [[Verene Shepherd]], the [[history of Jamaica|Jamaican historian]] of [[diaspora studies]], singles out the case of how he chose to [[manumission|free his slaves]] in [[English Jamaica|that colony]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shepherd|first1=Verene|title=Freedom in the era of slavery: The case of the Barclay brothers in Jamaica|url=http://old.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20080224/news/news3.html|accessdate=15 January 2018|publisher=The Gleaner|date=24 February 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 1776 the firm was styled \"Barclay, Bevan and Bening\" and so remained until 1785, when another partner, John Tritton, who had married a Barclay, was admitted, and the business then became \"Barclay, Bevan, Bening and Tritton\".<ref>(Gamble 1923,46).</ref>\nIn 1896 several banks in London and the English provinces, notably [[Backhouse's Bank]] of [[Darlington]]<ref>{{cite book| first1=Margaret| last1=Ackrill| first2=Leslie| last2=Hannah| title=Barclays: The Business of Banking, 1690-1996| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yAwipk34KP0C| year=2001| publisher=Cambridge University Press| isbn=978-0-521-79035-2| page=57}}</ref> and [[Gurney's Bank]] of [[Norwich]] (both of which also had their roots in Quaker families), united under the banner of Barclays and Co., a [[joint-stock company|joint-stock]] bank.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.heritagecity.org/research-centre/industrial-innovation/the-gurney-family-and-banking-in-norwich.htm| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100717225313/http://www.heritagecity.org/research-centre/industrial-innovation/the-gurney-family-and-banking-in-norwich.htm| url-status=dead| archive-date=17 July 2010| title=The Gurney family and banking in Norwich| publisher=Heritage City| accessdate=19 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== 1900 to 1945 ===\n\n[[File:1 Crossroads Sutton Surrey London.JPG|thumb|265px|The Barclays Bank branch in [[Sutton, London|Sutton]], southern Greater London, which was originally a branch of London and Provincial prior to acquisition by Barclays]]\n\nBetween 1905 and 1916 Barclays extended its branch network by making acquisitions of small English banks. Further expansion followed in 1918 when Barclays amalgamated with the [[London, Provincial and South Western Bank]] and in 1919 when the [[British Linen Bank]] was acquired by Barclays Bank, although the British Linen Bank retained a separate board of directors and continued to issue its own banknotes (see [[Banknotes of the pound sterling]]).<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.stirlingarchives.scot/2016/02/15/bank-and-agents-house-british-linen-bank-balfron-1923/| title=Bank and Agent's House, British Linen Bank| publisher=Stirling Archives| accessdate=19 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1925 the [[Colonial Bank (West Indies)|Colonial Bank]], [[National Bank of South Africa]] and the [[Anglo-Egyptian Bank]] were amalgamated and Barclays operated its overseas operations under the name Barclays Bank (Dominion, Colonial and Overseas)\u2014Barclays DCO.<ref name=pohl/> In 1938 Barclays acquired the first Indian exchange bank, the [[Central Exchange Bank of India]], which had opened in London in 1936 with the sponsorship of [[Central Bank of India]].<ref>Raychaudhuri ''et al.'', eds. (1983), Vol. 2, p.782.</ref>\n\nIn 1941 during the German [[occupation of France]], a branch of Barclays in Paris headed by Marcel Cheradame worked directly with the invading force.<ref name=Cheradame>{{cite web| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/1999/mar/28/theobserver7| title=Holocaust shame of Barclays| publisher=The Guardian| accessdate=1 January 2019}}</ref> Senior officials at the bank volunteered the names of Jewish employees as well as ceding an estimated one hundred Jewish bank accounts to the German occupiers.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/237392.stm| title=Barclays to compensate Jews | publisher=BBC News| accessdate=1 January 2019}}</ref> The Paris branch used its funds to increase the operational power of a large quarry that helped produce steel for the Germans. There was no evidence of contact between the head office in London and the branch in Paris during the occupation. Marcel Cheradame was kept as the branch manager until he retired in the sixties.<ref name=Cheradame/>\n\n===1946 to 1980===\nIn May 1958, Barclays was the first UK bank to appoint a female bank manager. [[Hilda Harding]] managed Barclays' Hanover Square branch in London until her retirement in 1970.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.archive.barclays.com/items/show/662 |title=Head Office Circular announcing the appointment of Hilda Harding as branch manager |publisher=Barclays |date=15 May 1958 |accessdate=25 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Atmplaque.jpg|thumb|right|A plaque in [[Enfield Town|Enfield]], United Kingdom commemorating the installation of the world's first [[Automated teller machine|cash machine]] by Barclays in 1967]]\nIn 1965, Barclays established a US affiliate, Barclays Bank of California in San Francisco.<ref>{{cite news| work=Investors chronicle and stock exchange gazette| date=5 December 1969| volume=10| page=922| title=Barclays}} Accessed 4 May 2012.</ref><ref>{{cite news| author=Leith McGrandle| work=Accountancy| date=5 December 1969| volume=85| page=54 |title=Barclays}} Accessed 4 May 2012.</ref>\n\nBarclays launched the first credit card in the UK, [[Barclaycard]], in 1966. On 27 June 1967, Barclays deployed the world's first [[Automated teller machine|cash machine]], in [[Enfield Town|Enfield]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3AQAAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA32|title=Insert card here|accessdate=4 May 2012| publisher=CIO Magazine| date=July 1988}}</ref><ref name=bbc25607>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/6230194.stm |title=The man who invented the cash machine |accessdate=4 May 2012 |publisher=BBC News |date=25 June 2007 |first=Brian |last=Milligan }}</ref> The British actor [[Reg Varney]] was the first person to use the machine.<ref name=bbc25607/>\n\nIn 1969, a planned merger with [[Martins Bank]] and [[Lloyds Bank]] was blocked by the [[Competition Commission (United Kingdom)|Monopolies and Mergers Commission]], but the acquisition of [[Martins Bank]] on its own was later permitted. Also that year, the [[British Linen Bank]] subsidiary was sold to the [[Bank of Scotland]] in exchange for a 25% stake, a transaction that became effective from 1971. Barclays DCO changed its name to Barclays Bank International in 1971.<ref name=pohl>{{cite book| author=European Association for Banking History| editor-last1=Pohl| editor-first1=Manfred| editor-last2=Freitag| editor-first2=Sabine| title=Handbook on the history of European banks| date=1994| publisher=E. Elgar| location=Aldershot, Hants, England| isbn=9781781954218| pages=1198\u20131199| url=https://books.google.com/?id=eXvfNDHpfWwC&lpg=PA1198&dq=%22barclays%20bank%20international%22%20established&pg=PA1193#v=onepage&q=%22barclays%20bank%20international%22%20established&f=false|accessdate=10 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn August 1975, following the [[Secondary banking crisis of 1973\u20131975|secondary banking crash]], Barclays acquired Mercantile Credit Company.<ref>{{cite book| title=The secondary banking crisis, 1973\u201375: its causes and course| first1=Margaret| last1=Reid| publisher=Macmillan| year=1982| isbn=978-0-333-28376-9 |page=128| url=https://books.google.com/?id=_XmuAAAAIAAJ&q=The+secondary+banking+crisis,+1973-75:+its+causes+and+course&dq=The+secondary+banking+crisis,+1973-75:+its+causes+and+course| accessdate=4 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n===1980 to 2000===\nIn 1980, Barclays Bank International expanded its business to include commercial credit and took over American Credit Corporation, renaming it Barclays American Corporation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/Barclays-plc-Company-History.html |accessdate=28 March 2009 |title=Barclays plc |work=Funding Universe}}</ref>\n\nDuring 1985 <ref name=a2020214>MJ Larson, G Schnyder, G Westerhaus, J Wilson (2013) \u2014 [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Kb7cAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA53&dq=Barclays+Group&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiNhKqB-NHnAhUJQ8AKHVoDCSsQ6AEIOzAC#v=onepage&q=Barclays%20Group&f=false p.53] in (Andrea Colli, Abe De Jong, Martin Jes Iversen editors) [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Kb7cAAAAQBAJ&dq=Barclays+Group&source=gbs_navlinks_s Mapping European Corporations: Strategy, Structure, Ownership and Performance] published by [[Routledge]], September 13 2013 {{ISBN|1135754446}}, {{ISBN|9781135754440}} - accessed 2020-02-14</ref> Barclays Bank and Barclays Bank International merged, and as part of the corporate reorganisation the former Barclays Bank plc became a group holding company,<ref name=pohl/> renamed Barclays Group Plc<ref name=a2020214/>, and UK [[retail banking]] was integrated under the former BBI, and renamed ''Barclays Bank PLC'' from ''Barclays Bank Limited''.<ref name=pohl/>\n\nIn 1986 Barclays sold its South African business operating under the [[First National Bank (South Africa)|Barclays National Bank]] name after protests against Barclays' involvement in South Africa and its [[apartheid]] government. Also that year Barclays bought de Zoete & Bevan and Wedd Durlacher (formerly Wedd Jefferson)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sas-space.sas.ac.uk/2762/ |title=Abstract \u2013 SAS-Space |publisher=Sas-space.sas.ac.uk |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> to form Barclays de Zoete Wedd (BZW), now known as the [[Barclays Investment Bank]], and to take advantage of the [[Big Bang (financial markets)|Big Bang]] on the [[London Stock Exchange]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.linkedin.com/company/bzw-barclays-de-zoete-wedd- |title=About BZW (Barclays de Zoete Wedd) |publisher=LinkedIn |accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nBarclays introduced the ''Connect'' card in June 1987, the first [[debit card]] in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite book |title=Law of bank payments |first1=Michael |last1=Lerego |publisher=FT Law & Tax |year=1996 |isbn=978-0-7520-0037-4 |page=472 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=anVMAQAAIAAJ&q=Law+of+bank+payments+Michael+Lerego&dq=Law+of+bank+payments+Michael+Lerego |accessdate=4 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The banking revolution: salvation or slaughter? : how technology is creating winners and losers |first1=Mark |last1=Carrington |first2=Philip |last2=Langguth |first3=Thomas |last3=Steiner |publisher=Financial Times Pitman |year=1997 |isbn=978-0-273-63055-5 |page=119 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=fid2QgAACAAJ&dq=The+banking+revolution:+salvation+or+slaughter |accessdate=4 May 2012}} {{Dead link |date=March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, Barclays sold Barclays Bank of California, which at that time was the 17th-largest bank in California measured by assets, to [[Wells Fargo]] for US$125&nbsp;million in cash.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/01/16/business/company-news-wells-fargo-to-buy-barclays-in-california.html |title=Wells Fargo to Buy Barclays in California |accessdate=4 May 2012 |work=The New York Times |date=16 January 1988 |first=Lawrence M. |last=Fisher}}</ref>\n\n[[Edgar Pearce]], the \"Mardi Gra Bomber\", began a terror campaign against the bank and the supermarket chain [[Sainsbury's]] in 1994.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/318913.stm |title=Mardi Gra bomber jailed |publisher=BBC News |date=14 April 1999 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Barclays bought Wells Fargo Nikko Investment Advisors (WFNIA) and merged it with BZW Investment Management to form [[Barclays Global Investors]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/06/19/business/barclays-may-soon-purchase-wells-fargo-nikko.html |title=Barclays may well soon buy Wells Fargo Nikko |work=The New York Times |date=19 June 1995 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nTwo years later, in 1998, the BZW business was broken up and parts were sold to [[Credit Suisse First Boston]]: Barclays retained the debt business which formed the foundation of what is now Barclays Capital.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4885056.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102215642/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4885056.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2 November 2012 |title=Revealed: what Credit Suisse really thinks about BZW |date=14 November 1997 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, in an unusual move as part of the trend at the time for [[free ISP]]s, Barclays launched an internet service called Barclays.net: this entity was acquired by [[British Telecom]] in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barclays.net |title=Barclays webpage |accessdate=18 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070517045409/http://www.barclays.net/ |archivedate=17 May 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2000, Barclays took over the recently de-mutualised Woolwich PLC, formerly [[the Woolwich]] Building Society,<ref>{{Cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/875639.stm |title= Barclays buys rival Woolwich |publisher= BBC News |date= 11 August 2000 |accessdate= 18 April 2011}}</ref> in a \u00a35.4 billion acquisition. Woolwich thus joined the Barclays group of companies, and the Woolwich name was retained after the acquisition. The company's head office remained in [[Bexleyheath]], south-east [[London]], four miles from the original head office in [[Woolwich]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/875639.stm Barclays buys rival Woolwich] BBC News, 11 August 2000</ref>\n\n===21st century===\n[[File:Barclays Bank, Stratford-upon-Avon - DSC08949.JPG|thumb|right|A Barclays branch in [[Stratford-upon-Avon]], United Kingdom]]\nIn 2001 Barclays closed 171 branches in the UK, many of them in rural communities: Barclays called itself \"The Big Bank\" but this name was quickly given a low profile after a series of embarrassing PR stunts.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/everythings-big-at-barclays-the-chairmans-pay-has-quadrupled-just-as-171-branches-are-closing-722358.html |title=Everything is big at Barclays: the chairman's pay has quadrupled just as 171 branches are closing |work=The Independent |location=UK |date=31 March 2000 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 October 2001, Barclays and [[Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce|CIBC]] agreed to combine their [[Caribbean]] operations to establish a joint venture company known as [[FirstCaribbean International Bank]] (FCIB).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/cibc-barclays-planning-caribbean-joint-venture/article18416752/|title=CIBC, Barclays planning Caribbean joint venture|date=24 July 2001|website=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Barclays bought the American credit card company [[Juniper Bank]] from [[Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce|CIBC]], re-branding it as \"Barclays Bank Delaware\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Timmons |first=Heather |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/08/19/business/barclays-pays-293-million-for-us-credit-card-issuer.html |title=Barclays pays $293&nbsp;million for US credit card issuer |work=The New York Times |date=19 August 2004 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> The same year saw the acquisition of Banco Zaragozano, the 11th-largest Spanish bank.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Timmons |first=Heather |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/05/09/business/barclays-agrees-to-buy-spanish-bank-in-cash-deal.html |title=Barclays agrees to buy Spanish bank in cash deal |location=SPAIN |work=The New York Times |date=9 May 2003 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nBarclays took over sponsorship of the [[Premier League]] from [[Barclaycard]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportbusiness.com/news/160512/barclays-secures-fa-premier-league-sponsorship |title=Barclays secures FA Premier League sponsorship |publisher=Sportbusiness.com |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> In May 2005, Barclays moved its group headquarters from [[Lombard Street, London|Lombard Street]] in the [[City of London]] to [[One Churchill Place]] in [[Canary Wharf]]. Also in 2005 Barclays sealed a \u00a32.6bn takeover of [[Absa Group Limited]], South Africa's largest retail bank, acquiring a 54% stake on 27 July 2005.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/low/business/3683830.stm |title=Barclays looks to buy Absa stake |publisher=BBC News |date=23 September 2004 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nThen in 2006, Barclays purchased the HomEq Servicing Corporation for US$469&nbsp;million in cash from [[Wachovia]] Corp.<ref>{{cite web |first=Aaron |last=Siegel |date=23 June 2006 |url=http://www.investmentnews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20060623/REG/606230708/1094/INDaily03 |title=Barclays buys Wachovia unit for $469&nbsp;million |work=InvestmentNews |accessdate=16 August 2017}}</ref> That year also saw the acquisition of the financial website CompareTheLoan<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comparetheloan.co.uk |title=Cheap Homeowner Loans , Compare Loans , UK Secured Loans |publisher=Comparetheloan |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> and Barclays announcing plans to rebrand Woolwich branches as Barclays, migrating Woolwich customers onto Barclays accounts and migrating back-office processes onto Barclays systems\u2014the Woolwich brand was to be used for Barclays mortgages.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mad.co.uk/BreakingNews/BreakingNews/Articles/dc366386b91141a4bd605f83c3d36f8c/Barclays-plans-rebrand-of-Woolwich.html |title=Barclays plans rebrand of Woolwich |publisher=Mad.co.uk |date=28 June 2006 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> Barclays also exited retail-banking operations in the Caribbean-region which extended as far back as 1837 through selling of its joint venture stake in FirstCaribbean International Bank (FCIB) to CIBC for between $989 million and $1.08 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/caribbean/news/story/2006/12/printable/061228_barclays.shtml |title=Barclays sells Caribbean stake |date=28 December 2006|publisher=BBC|accessdate=2 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2007, Barclays announced that it had purchased the naming rights to the [[Barclays Center]], a proposed 18,000-seat arena in [[Brooklyn]], New York, where the [[New Jersey Nets]] planned to relocate.<ref>{{cite news |date=17 January 2007 |url=http://www.ny1.com/archives/nyc/all-boroughs/2007/01/17/nets-new-arena-reportedly-to-be-called-barclays-center-NYC_65958.old.html |title=Nets' new arena reportedly to be called Barclays Centre |publisher=[[NY1]] |accessdate=16 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170817163058/http://www.ny1.com/archives/nyc/all-boroughs/2007/01/17/nets-new-arena-reportedly-to-be-called-barclays-center-NYC_65958.old.html |archive-date=17 August 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n\n\n====Abandoned merger with ABN AMRO====\nIn March 2007, Barclays announced plans to merge with [[ABN AMRO]], the largest bank in the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite press release |date=20 March 2007 |url=http://www.newsroom.barclays.co.uk/content/Detail.asp?ReleaseID=985&NewsAreaID=2 |title=Barclays and ABN AMRO Announce Outline of Preliminary Discussions |publisher=Barclays |accessdate=18 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107012336/http://www.newsroom.barclays.co.uk/content/Detail.asp?ReleaseID=985&NewsAreaID=2 |archivedate=7 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Werdigier |first=Julia |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/19/business/19deal.html |title=Barclays Bank Makes Inquiry on Takeover of ABN Amro |work=The New York Times |date=19 March 2007 |accessdate=2 February 2012}}</ref> However, on 5 October 2007 Barclays announced that it had abandoned its bid,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/low/business/7029297.stm |title=Barclays abandons ABN Amro offer |publisher=BBC News |date=5 October 2007 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> citing inadequate support by ABN shareholders. Fewer than 80% of shares had been tendered to Barclays' cash-and-shares offer.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mollenkamp |first=Carrick |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB119158340445950068?mod=googlenews_wsj |title=Barclays's CEO Shifts to Plan B |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=3 February 2011 |accessdate=18 April 2011 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> This left the consortium led by [[Royal Bank of Scotland]] free to proceed with its counter-bid for ABN AMRO.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cityam.com/index.php?news=8833 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090125174939/http://www.cityam.com/index.php?news=8833 |url-status=dead |archive-date=25 January 2009 |title=Does RBS's acquisition of ABN AMRO really do what it says on the tin? |work=[[City A.M.]] |date= |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nTo help finance its bid for ABN AMRO, Barclays sold a 3.1% stake to [[China Development Bank]] and a 3% stake to [[Temasek Holdings]], the investment arm of the Singaporean government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marketwatch.com/news/story/barclays-looks-east-fund-new/story.aspx?guid=%7B273CEEA5-1246-44E0-B0B4-B1AAC48C312B%7D |title=Barclays looks East to fund ABN AMRO purchase |work=[[MarketWatch]] |date=23 July 2007 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2007, Barclays agreed to purchase Equifirst Corporation from [[Regions Financial Corporation]] for US$225&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9501E7D71E30F933A15752C0A9619C8B63 |title=Barclays to buy sub-prime lender |work=The New York Times |date=20 January 2007 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> That year also saw Barclays Personal Investment Management announcing the closure of their operation in Peterborough and its re-siting to Glasgow, laying off nearly 900 members of staff.<ref>{{cite news |date=8 May 2014 |publisher=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-27321589/ |title=Barclays To Cut 19,000 Jobs Over Three Years |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Financing====\nOn 30 August 2007, Barclays was forced to borrow \u00a31.6&nbsp;billion (US$3.2&nbsp;billion) from the [[Bank of England]] sterling standby facility. This is made available as a last-resort when banks are unable to settle their debts to other banks at the end of daily trading.<ref>{{cite news |first1=Ashley |last1=Seager |first2=Larry |last2=Elliott |first3=Julia |last3=Kollewe |last-author-amp=yes |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2007/aug/31/money |title=Barclays admits borrowing hundreds of millions |work=The Guardian |location=UK |date= 31 August 2007 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> Despite rumours about liquidity at Barclays, the loan was necessary due to a technical problem with their computerised settlement network. A Barclays spokesman was quoted as saying \"There are no liquidity issues in the U.K markets. Barclays itself is flush with liquidity.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Menon |first=Jon |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601102&sid=aqA8hFXWD3JY&refer=uk |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930055730/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601102&sid=aqA8hFXWD3JY&refer=uk |url-status=dead |archive-date=30 September 2007 |title=UK & Ireland |publisher=Bloomberg |date=31 August 2007 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 November 2007, Barclays shares dropped 9% and were even temporarily suspended for a short period of time, due to rumours of a \u00a34.8&nbsp;billion (US$10&nbsp;billion) exposure to bad debts in the US. However, a Barclays spokesman denied the rumours.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/7087451.stm |title=Barclays denies bad debt rumour |publisher=BBC News |date=9 November 2007 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nBarclays sought to raise capital privately, avoiding direct equity investment from the UK government, which was offered to boost its capital ratio.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lee |first=Peter |url=http://www.euromoney.com/Article/2225039/Barclays-keeps-apologizing-for-saving-the-bank.html |title=Barclays keeps apologizing for saving the bank |work=[[Euromoney]]}}</ref> Barclays believed that \"maintaining its independence from government was in the best interests of its shareholders\".<ref>{{cite news |date=2 April 2013 |work=The Wall Street Journal |url=http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/SalzReview04032013.pdf |title=An Independent Review of Barclays' Business Practices |accessdate=25 April 2014 |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2008, Barclays attempted to raise \u00a34.5&nbsp;billion through a non-traditional rights issue to shore up its weakened [[Tier 1 capital|Tier 1 capital ratio]], which involved a rights offer to existing shareholders and the sale of a stake to [[Sumitomo Mitsui Banking Corporation]]. Only 19% of shareholders took up their rights leaving investors [[China Development Bank]] and [[Qatar Investment Authority]] with increased holdings in the bank.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/7513178.stm |title=Barclays share sale raises \u00a34.5bn |publisher=BBC News |date=18 July 2008 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nBarclays launched a further round of capital raising, approved by special resolution on 24 November 2008, as part of its overall plan to achieve higher capital targets set by the UK's [[Financial Services Authority]] to ensure it would remain independent.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.euromoney.com/Article/2038377/Abigail-Hofman-The-loser-list.html#strategy |title=Abigail Hofman: The loser list |work=Euromoney |date=30 October 2008}}</ref> Barclays raised \u00a37&nbsp;billion from investors from Abu Dhabi and Qatar.<ref name=nytqatar>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/01/business/worldbusiness/01barclays.html |title=Barclays Seeks $11.8 Billion From Abu Dhabi and Qatar |date=1 November 2008 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=19 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.euromoney.com/Article/2059789/Abigail-with-attitude-More-zeroes-than-heroes.html#barclays |title=Abigail Hofman: More zeroes than heroes \u2013 Barclays |work=Euromoney |date=1 December 2008}}</ref> Existing Barclays shareholders complained they were not offered full pre-emption rights in this round of capital raising, even threatening to revolt at the extraordinary meeting. Sheikh Mansour and Qatar Holding agreed to open up \u00a3500&nbsp;million of their new holdings of reserve capital instruments for clawback. Existing investors now took this up.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.euromoney.com/Article/3198818/Barclays-Qatari-capital-raising-timeline.html |title=Barclays' Qatari capital-raising timeline |work=Euromoney |first=Erica |last=Jeffery |date=12 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Barclays bought the credit card brand Goldfish for US$70&nbsp;million gaining 1.7&nbsp;million customers, and US$3.9&nbsp;billion in receivables.<ref>{{cite news|\n url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/banking_and_finance/article3330860.ece| title=Barclays buys Goldfish as US Group calls time on credit cards| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611162430/http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/banking_and_finance/article3330860.ece |date=8 February 2008 |archive-date=11 June 2011 |first1=Miles |last1=Costello |first2=Siobhan |last2=Kennedy |work=[[The Times]] |url-access=subscription }}</ref> Barclays also bought a controlling stake in the Russian retail bank Expobank for US$745&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/banking_and_finance/article3473418.ece| title=Barclays seals Expobank deal in Russia| work=The Times| first1=Miles |last1=Costello| date=3 March 2008| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081008015533/http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/banking_and_finance/article3473418.ece |archive-date=8 October 2008}}</ref> Later in the year Barclays commenced its [[Pakistan]] operations with initial funding of US$100&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news| work=Pakistan Daily| url=http://www.daily.pk/business/businessnews/6078.html?task=view| title=Barclays Bank UK commences operation in Pakistan|  date=25 July 2008| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080912123124/http://www.daily.pk/business/businessnews/6078.html?task=view |archive-date=12 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n====Lehman Brothers acquisition====\n[[File:Lehman Brothers Times Square by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|The former headquarters of [[Lehman Brothers]] in New York City, now owned by Barclays]]\n[[File:BBNY.jpg|right|thumb|300px|The New York building at night]]\nOn 16 September 2008, Barclays announced its agreement to purchase, subject to regulatory approval, the investment-banking and trading divisions of [[Lehman Brothers]] (including its New York skyscraper) which was a United States financial conglomerate that had filed for bankruptcy.<ref>{{cite news| last=Treanor| first=Jill| title=Barclays to buy Lehman Brothers assets| url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/sep/16/barclay.lehmanbrothers1| newspaper=The Guardian| date=16 April 2013| location=London}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 September 2008, a revised version of the deal, a US$1.35&nbsp;billion (\u00a3700&nbsp;million) plan for Barclays to acquire the core business of Lehman Brothers (mainly Lehman's US$960&nbsp;million [[Midtown Manhattan]] office skyscraper, with responsibility for 9,000 former employees), was approved. After a seven-hour hearing, New York [[United States bankruptcy court|bankruptcy court]] Judge James Peck ruled:\n{{quote|\"I have to approve this transaction because it is the only available transaction. Lehman Brothers became a victim, in effect the only true icon to fall in a tsunami that has befallen the credit markets. This is the most momentous bankruptcy hearing I've ever sat through. It can never be deemed precedent for future cases. It's hard for me to imagine a similar emergency.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/7626624.stm |title=Judge approves $1.3bn Lehman deal |publisher=BBC News |date=20 September 2008 |accessdate=18 April 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110512055650/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/7626624.stm| archivedate= 12 May 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n\nLuc Despins, the creditors committee counsel, said: \"The reason we're not objecting is really based on the lack of a viable alternative. We did not support the transaction because there had not been enough time to properly review it.\" In the amended agreement, Barclays would absorb US$47.4&nbsp;billion in securities and assume US$45.5&nbsp;billion in trading liabilities. Lehman's attorney [[Harvey R. Miller]] of [[Weil, Gotshal & Manges]], said \"the purchase price for the real estate components of the deal would be US$1.29&nbsp;billion, including US$960&nbsp;million for Lehman's New York headquarters and US$330&nbsp;million for two New Jersey data centres. Lehman's original estimate valued its headquarters at US$1.02&nbsp;billion but an appraisal from CB Richard Ellis this week valued it at US$900&nbsp;million.\" Further, Barclays will not acquire Lehman's Eagle Energy unit, but will have entities known as Lehman Brothers Canada Inc, Lehman Brothers Sudamerica, Lehman Brothers Uruguay and its Private Investment Management business for high-net-worth individuals. Finally, Lehman will retain US$20&nbsp;billion of securities assets in Lehman Brothers Inc that are not being transferred to Barclays.<ref>{{cite news |last=Chasan |first=Emily |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/rbssFinancialServicesAndRealEstateNews/idUSN1932554220080920 |title=Judge approves Lehman, Barclays pact |agency=Reuters |date=20 September 2008 |accessdate=18 April 2011| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090626052050/https://www.reuters.com/article/rbssFinancialServicesAndRealEstateNews/idUSN1932554220080920| archivedate=26 June 2009 |url-status= live}}</ref> Barclays had a potential liability of US$2.5&nbsp;billion to be paid as [[severance package|severance]], if it chooses not to retain some Lehman employees beyond the guaranteed 90 days.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1988&dat=20080921&id=wYkxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=s6kFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1538,1373426 |title=Judge says Lehman can sell units to Barclays |agency=[[Associated Press]] |first=Vinnee |last=Tong |date=21 September 2008 |work=[[The Argus-Press]] |location=[[Owosso, Michigan]] |page=6A}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title=Barclays clinches deal to buy Lehman assets for $2bn| url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/sep/17/barclay.lehmanbrothers| date=16 September 2008| first1=David| last1=Teather| first2=Jill| last2=Treanor| work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, Barclays was ordered to pay $15&nbsp;million in settlement charges that alleged the bank had failed to maintain an adequate internal compliance system after its acquisition of Lehman Brothers during the 2008 financial crisis.<ref>{{cite news| agency=Reuters| date=23 September 2014| title=Barclays to pay $15&nbsp;million over compliance failures tied to Lehman deal| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/09/23/us-sec-barclays-violations-idUSKCN0HI1ZE20140923}}</ref>\n\n====2009 to present====\n[[File:Barclays Global Investors HQ, south side 1.JPG|thumb|The former headquarters of Barclays Global Investors in San Francisco, United States. Barclays sold Barclays Global Investors to [[BlackRock]] in 2009.]]\n[[Reuters]] later reported that the [[HM Treasury|British government]] would inject \u00a340&nbsp;billion (US$69&nbsp;billion) into three banks including Barclays, which might seek over \u00a37&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/innovationNewsIndustryMaterialsAndUtilities/idUSTRE49B37P20081012?sp=true |title=British banks set for 40&nbsp;billion pound rescue: sources |agency=Reuters |date=12 October 2008 |first1=John |last1=Bowker |first2=Ralph |last2=Gowling |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> Barclays later confirmed that it rejected the Government's offer and would instead raise \u00a36.5&nbsp;billion of new capital (\u00a32&nbsp;billion by cancellation of dividend and \u00a34.5&nbsp;billion from private investors).<ref name=nytqatar/><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.bankingtimes.co.uk/13102008-barclays-confirms-65bn-fundraising/| title=Barclays confirms \u00a36.5bn fundraising| \n archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014034029/http://www.bankingtimes.co.uk/13102008-barclays-confirms-65bn-fundraising/| date=13 October 2008| archive-date=14 October 2008| work=Banking Times}}</ref>\n\nBarclays' share price fell 54% in June 2009 after the [[International Petroleum Investment Company]] (IPIC), which had invested up to \u00a34.75&nbsp;billion in November 2008, sold 1.3&nbsp;billion Barclays shares.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.euromoney.com/Article/2231148/Euromoney-40th-anniversary-special-Focus-on-Ipic.html |title=Euromoney 40th anniversary special: Focus on Ipic | work=Euromoney |date=June 2009}}</ref>\n[[Qatar Investment Authority|Qatar Holding]] sold a 3.5% stake worth \u00a310&nbsp;billion in October 2009,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.euromoney.com/Article/2350993/Abigail-with-attitude-Barclays-tea-leaves.html |title=Abigail with attitude: Barclays' tea leaves |work=Euromoney |first=Abigail |last=Hofman |date=3 December 2009}}</ref> and a further sale of warrants worth around \u00a3750&nbsp;million in November 2012, but remains one of the bank's largest shareholders.<ref name=\"Euromoney\">{{cite news| first=Erica| last=Jeffery| url=http://www.euromoney.com/Article/3198818/Barclays-Qatari-capital-raising-timeline.html |title=Barclays' Qatari capital-raising timeline |work=Euromoney |date=12 May 2014}}</ref> In July 2012, Barclays revealed that the FSA was investigating<ref name=\"Euromoney\"/> whether the bank adequately disclosed fees paid to [[Qatar Investment Authority]]. In August 2012, the [[Serious Fraud Office (United Kingdom)|Serious Fraud Office]] announced an investigation into the Middle East capital raising. The [[Financial Services Authority]] announced an expansion of the investigation into the Barclays-Qatar deal in January 2013, focusing on the disclosure surrounding the ownership of the securities in the bank.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/47d412ce-6bd1-11e2-a700-00144feab49a.html |title=Barclays in Qatar loan probe |work=Financial Times |date=31 January 2013 |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2009, the press reported that further capital may be required and that while the government might be willing to fund this, it may be unable to do so because the previous capital investment from the Qatari state was subject to a proviso that no third party might put in further money without the Qataris receiving compensation at the value the shares had commanded in October 2008.<ref>[http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/banking_and_finance/article5570035.ece John Varley perplexed as Barclays' share price dives] ''The Times'', 23 January 2009</ref> In March 2009, it was reported that in 2008, Barclays received billions of dollars from its insurance arrangements with [[American International Group|AIG]], including US$8.5 billion from funds provided by the United States to bail out AIG.<ref>{{cite news| title=Big European Banks Benefit from AIG Bailout| url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/29714822| first1=Mary| last1=Thompson| first2=Steve| last2=Liesman| date=5 August 2010| publisher=[[CNBC]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| first=Eamon| last=Javers| url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0309/20039.html| title=AIG ships billions in bailout abroad| work=[[Politico]]| date=15 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 June 2009, Barclays sold its Global Investors unit, which included its exchange-traded fund business, [[iShares]], to [[BlackRock]] for US$13.5 billion.<ref>{{cite news |agency=Press Association |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2009/jun/12/blackrock-to-buy-barclays-bank-arm |title=US giant BlackRock buys arm of Barclays bank |work=The Guardian |location=UK |accessdate=21 February 2010 |date=12 June 2009}}</ref> Standard Life sold Standard Life Bank to Barclays in October 2009. The sale was completed on 1 January 2010.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/8326313.stm Barclays buys Standard Life Bank] BBC News. 26 October 2009</ref> On 11 November 2009, Barclays and [[First Data]], a global technology provider of information commerce, had entered into an agreement according to which Barclays would migrate a range of card portfolios to First Data's issuing and consumer finance platform.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.finextra.com/fullpr.asp?id=30902 |title=First Data reports Barclays contract |publisher=Finextra.com |date=11 November 2009 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> On 13 February 2010, Barclays announced it would pay more than \u00a32&nbsp;billion in bonuses.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/8514650.stm |title=Barclays bank bonuses expected to reach \u00a32bn |publisher=BBC News |date=13 February 2010 |accessdate=21 February 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100220174039/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/8514650.stm| archivedate= 20 February 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> In March 2011 it was reported that Barclays had overtaken [[Santander UK]] to claim top spot as the UK's most complained against bank, with the country's official banking regulator, the [[Financial Services Authority]] having recorded 276,315 new customer complaints against Barclays Bank during the second half of 2010.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/barclays-tops-fsa-rankings-for-bank-complaints-2257800.html Barclays tops FSA rankings for bank complaints.] The Independent 31 March 2011</ref> Barclays nevertheless ranks only third in the UK among the mainstream clearing banks in terms of the number of its branches. Inline with costs cut, Barclays cut 1,400 jobs during the first half of 2011 and cut another 1,600 jobs for the rest of 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/08/02/us-barclays-idUSTRE77114Q20110802 |title=Barclays to cut 3,000 jobs as profit sags |date=2 August 2011 | publisher=Reuters}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2012, the trading names of Barclays Capital, Barclays Wealth and Barclays Corporate were each changed to simply \"Barclays\", as part of an effort to simplify the operations of the company and to promote greater integration between its divisions.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thisismoney.co.uk/money/news/article-2117723/Barclays-drops-Capital-Diamond-puts-end-BarCap-brand.html| title=Barclays drops the name 'Capital' from its investment bank division as the bank aligns under one name| accessdate=11 June 2012| work=This is Money| date=20 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2012 Barclaycard acquired Analog Analytics, a digital coupon and daily deal business similar to [[Groupon]].<ref name=LN1>{{cite web| last1=Bigelow| first1=Bruce| title=Barclaycard Acquires Social Couponing Startup Analog Analytics| url=http://www.xconomy.com/national/2012/06/04/barclaycard-acquires-social-couponing-startup-analog-analytics/| website=xconomy.com| accessdate=6 April 2015| ref=LN1}}</ref><ref name=LN2>{{cite web| last1=Kamanec| first1=Kara| title=Barclays Group PLC Member, Barclaycard, Purchases Analog Analytics| url=http://www.dailydealmedia.com/726barclays-group-plc-memeber-barclaycard-purchases-analog-analytics/| website=dailydealmedia.com| accessdate=6 April 2015|ref=LN2}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2012, Barclays announced it had agreed to buy the ING Direct UK business of the [[ING Group]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Barclays to acquire ING Direct UK |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-19880659 |publisher=BBC News |date=9 October 2012 |accessdate=19 June 2013}}</ref> The transfer of the business to Barclays was approved at the High Court on 20 February 2013 and ING Direct was renamed Barclays Direct and will be integrated into the existing Barclays business within two years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ingdirect.co.uk/saleannouncement.asp |title=Barclays welcomes customers of ING Direct UK |website=Barclays Direct |accessdate=19 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2013, Barclays announced a net loss of \u00a31.04&nbsp;billion for 2012, its first annual loss in two decades, together with plans to cut 3,700 jobs, reduce annual costs by \u00a31.7&nbsp;billion, and scale back its retail banking activities in Europe and Asia.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-02-12/barclays-to-cut-3-700-jobs-after-full-year-loss.html |title=Barclays to Cut 3,700 Jobs After Full-Year Loss |date=12 February 2013 | work=Bloomberg}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, Barclays announced it would cut 19,000 jobs over three years with 12,000 jobs cut in 2014. Investment banking will cut 2,000 jobs in 2014 and up to 7,000 jobs totally in 2016 making the investment banking portion shrink from 50 per cent in 2014 to 30 per cent of Barclay's assets in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ky3.com/news/business/Barclays-to-shed-19-000-jobs-over-three-years/21049046_25870878 |title=Barclays to shed 19,000 jobs over three years |first=Sophia |last=Yan |date=8 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140524062136/http://www.ky3.com/news/business/Barclays-to-shed-19-000-jobs-over-three-years/21049046_25870878 |archivedate=24 May 2014 |publisher=[[KYTV (TV)|KYTV News]]}}</ref>\n\nBarclays announced in June 2015 that it would sell its US wealth and investment management business to [[Stifel]] for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite news|author=Richa Naidu |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/06/08/us-barclayswealth-stifel-financial-m-a-idUSKBN0OO1CB20150608 |title=Stifel to buy former Lehman brokerage from Barclays |agency=Reuters |date=9 June 2015 |accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nBarclays sold its Retail Banking unit in Spain to [[CaixaBank]] in 2014. At its peak, Barclays had 5,100 employees and 600 offices in Spain. In 2014 the bank had 2,800 employees and 270 offices. With the sale, Caixabank acquired around 550,000 new retail and private banking clients and 2,400 employees.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/caixabank-to-buy-barclays-retail-banking-in-spain-1409515069| work=The Wall Street Journal| first=Jeannette| last=Neumann| title=Caixabank to Buy Barclays Retail Banking in Spain| date=1 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/fae5d374-3147-11e4-8313-00144feabdc0.html#axzz3hmjgufeX|title=Barclays loses \u00a3500m on sale of Spanish business |work=Financial Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-08-31/caixabank-to-buy-barclays-spain-units-for-1-05-billion| work=Bloomberg News| first=Charles| last=Penty| title=CaixaBank to Buy Barclays's Spanish Unit for 1.1 Billion| date=1 September 2014|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, it was announced that Barclays has plans to sell its Africa business amid falling profits.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/03/01/barclays-to-sell-african-bank-and-slash-dividend-as-profits-fall/ |title=Barclays to sell African bank and slash dividend as profits fall |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=1 March 2016 |first=Tim |last=Wallace |access-date=2 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, Barclays announced a deal that allowed its UK customers to use [[Apple Pay]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-35968102 |title=Barclays bank joins Apple Pay in UK |last=Kelion |first=Leo |work=BBC News |access-date=5 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe bank announced in May 2017 that it would sell \u00a31.5 billion worth of shares of its [[Barclays Africa Group]] subsidiary as part of its strategy to refocus its business from Africa to the UK and US.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-barclays-africa/barclays-shares-rise-on-report-of-africa-stake-sale-idUKKBN18R1KL|title=Barclays set to sell 1.5 billion pound stake in Africa business|date=31 May 2017|work=Reuters|access-date=8 September 2017}}</ref> In September 2017, Barclay's sold off the last part of its retail banking segment on continental [[Europe]] after selling its [[France|French]] retail, wealth and investment management operations to [[AnaCap Financial Partners|AnaCap]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/d3970784-0bc3-3ccf-95f7-83a051e4b1cc|title=Barclays continues pullback with final exit from European retail banking|last=|first=|date=|website=Financial Times|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nTo ward off the effects of [[Brexit]], Barclays borrowed \u00a36 billion from the [[Bank of England]] between April and June 2017, as part of a post-referendum stimulus package launched in August 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cityam.com/271591/barclays-and-lloyds-gbp10bn-borrowing-boost-bank-england|title=Barclays and Lloyds in \u00a310bn BoE borrowing boost|last=Jolly|first=Jasper|date=7 September 2017|access-date=8 September 2017|language=en}}</ref> The former boss of Barclays, [[Bob Diamond (banker)|Bob Diamond]], opined in an interview with ''[[The Independent]]'' in September 2017 that the [[City of London]] would feel a stronger negative impact from [[Brexit]] than generally expected.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/brexit-latest-bank-jobs-move-new-york-london-barclays-bob-diamond-eu-leave-a7935546.html|title=Ex-Barclays boss predicts Brexit-hit London will lose out to New York|date=8 September 2017|work=The Independent|access-date=8 September 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref> Diamond argued that both banking jobs and legal and support operations would eventually relocate to the [[Continental Europe|Continent]].<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n==Operations==\nBarclays' operations are organised within two business 'clusters': [[Wholesale banking|Corporate]] and [[Investment Banking]] and [[wealth management|Wealth]] and [[Investment management|Investment Management]]; and [[retail banking|Retail]] and [[business banking|Business Banking]].<ref name=grouporg>{{cite web |url=https://www.home.barclays/barclays-investor-relations/investing-in-barclays/fact-sheet.html |title=About Barclays |publisher=Group Barclays |accessdate=16 August 2017}}</ref> The Corporate and Investment Banking and Wealth and Investment Management cluster comprises three business units: Corporate banking; [[Barclays Investment Bank|Investment banking]]; and [[Barclays Wealth|Wealth and investment management]].<ref name=grouporg/> The Retail and Business Banking cluster comprises four business units: Africa Retail and Business Banking; [[Barclaycard]] (credit card and loan provision); Europe Retail and Business Banking; and UK Retail and Business Banking.<ref name=grouporg/>\n\n===Principal divisions and subsidiaries===\n[[File:Barclays group worldwide locations.png|thumb|A map showing the countries of the world in which Barclays currently has operations]]\nBarclays' principal divisions and subsidiaries include:\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Barclaycard]] \u2013 global credit card business\n* Barclays Bank LLC (Russia)\n* Barclays Bank plc \u2013 UK corporate bank\n* Barclays Bank UK plc \u2013 UK retail bank\n* Barclays Bank Delaware (formerly Barclaycard US, originally Juniper Bank, acquired 2003)\n* Barclays Corporate\n* Barclays Croatia\n* Barclays Execution Services\n* Barclays France\n* Barclays India\n* Barclays Indonesia<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/7865195.stm |title=Barclays slides after downgrade |publisher=BBC News |date=2 February 2009 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bankakita.co.id/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=38&Itemid=1 |title=Bank Akita News |accessdate=30 December 2009 |language=id |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721120204/http://www.bankakita.co.id/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=38&Itemid=1 |archive-date=21 July 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n* [[Barclays Investment Bank]]\n* Barclays Private Clients International \u2013 subsidiary based in the [[Isle of Man]] with branches in the [[Channel Islands]]\n* Barclays Morocco\n* Barclays Mauritius\n* [[First National Bank (South Africa)|Barclays National Bank]]: former vice chairman, [[Julian Ogilvie Thompson]].\n* Barclays Pakistan\n* Barclays Partner Finance\n* Barclays Portugal (162 branches)<ref name=spain>{{cite news |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/mergersNews/idUKL271397520080902 |title=Barclays mulls Spanish insurance stake sale |agency=Reuters |date=2 September 2008|accessdate=18 April 2011 |first=Steve |last=Slater}}</ref>\n* Barclays Rise (fintech accelerator with locations in New York, London, Manchester, Vilnius, Cape Town, Tel Aviv and Mumbai)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thinkrise.com/|title=Think Rise - Home|website=thinkrise.com|access-date=2 February 2017}}</ref>\n* Barclays Shared Services Chennai (India)\n* Barclays Shared Services Noida (India)\n* Barclays Technologies Centre China (closed)\n* Barclays Technologies Centre India\n* Barclays Technologies Centre Singapore (closed)\n* Barclays Technologies Centre Lithuania\n* [[Barclays Wealth]] \u2013 provides stockbroking and [[Offshore bank|offshore]] and [[private banking]]\n* Firstplus Financial Group plc\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Branches and ATMs===\n[[File:Barclays Bank, Park Lane Branch - geograph.org.uk - 218753.jpg|thumb|A Barclays branch on [[Park Lane (road)|Park Lane]] in London, United Kingdom]]\n[[File:Le Green Hall (Vilnius) (7692990530).jpg|thumb|Barclays office in [[Vilnius]], Lithuania]]\nBarclays has over 4,750 branches in about 55 countries and of which about 1,600 are in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/mergersNews/idUKLG49160920080916 |title=Key facts about Barclays |agency=Reuters |date=16 September 2008 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> In the UK, Barclays also offers some personal banking services through branches of the [[Post Office Ltd|Post Office]]. Most Barclays branches have 24/7 [[Automated teller machine|ATMs]]. Barclays customers and the customers of many other banks can use Barclays ATMs for free in the UK, although in some other countries fees are charged. Barclays is a member of the [[Global ATM Alliance]], an alliance of international banks which allows each banks' customers to use their ATM or [[debit card]] at all other member banks with no ATM access fees when travelling internationally.<ref>[http://www.atmmarketplace.com/article.php?id=1886 \"Five big banks form Global ATM Alliance\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070507142245/http://www.atmmarketplace.com/article.php?id=1886 |date=7 May 2007}}, ATMmarketplace.com. 9 January 2002. Retrieved 22 June 2007.</ref>\n\n===Senior management===\nThe Group Chairman is Nigel Higgins (ex-CEO of [[Rothschild & Co]]), who succeeded [[John McFarlane]] on 2 May 2019.\n\nOn 28 October 2015 Barclays announced that [[Jes Staley]], managing partner at [[BlueMountain Capital]], ex-CEO of [[J.P. Morgan & Co.]] and member of the board of directors of [[UBS]], has been appointed as Group Chief Executive Officer of Barclays effective 1 December 2015.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.home.barclays/news/2015/10/barclays-appoints-jamesestaley-as-group-chief-executive.html| title=Barclays appoints James E. Staley as Group Chief Executive| publisher=Barclays}}</ref>\n\n====Group Executive Committee==== \n\nThe current members of Barclays' Executive Committee are:<ref name=\"leadership\">{{cite web |title=Barclays Leadership |url=https://home.barclays/who-we-are/structure-and-leadership/leadership/ |website=home.barclays |accessdate=14 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Jes Staley]] (Group Chief Executive Officer)\n* Tushar Morzaria (Group Finance Director)\n* Matt Hammerstein (Chief Executive Officer of Barclays UK)\n* Paul Compton (President of Barclays Bank PLC (BBPLC))\n* Mark Ashton-Rigby (Group Chief Operating Officer and Chief Executive Officer of Barclays Execution Services (BX))\n* Ashok Vaswani (Global Head of Consumer Banking and Payments)\n* Stephen Dainton (Global Head of Markets)\n* Joe McGrath (Global Head of Banking)\n* Alistair Currie (Global Head of Corporate Banking)\n* Bob Hoyt (Group General Counsel)\n* Tristram Roberts (Group Human Resources Director)\n* Laura Padovani (Group Chief Compliance Officer)\n* C. S. Venkatakrishnan (Group Chief Risk Officer)\n* Lindsay O'Reilly (Group Chief Internal Auditor)\n\n====Board of directors====\n\nThe current members of Barclays'Group board of directors are:<ref name=\"leadership\"/>\n* Nigel Higgins (Group Chairman)\n* [[Jes Staley]] (Group Chief Executive)\n* Tushar Morzaria (Group Finance Director)\n* [[Ian Cheshire (businessman)|Sir Ian Cheshire]] (Chairman of Barclays Bank UK PLC and Barclays Group Non-Executive Director)\n* Mary Francis CBE (Barclays Group Non-Executive Director)\n* Diane Schueneman (Barclays Group Non-Executive Director)\n* Mike Ashley (Barclays Group Non-Executive Director)\n* Tim Breedon CBE (Barclays Group Non-Executive Director)\n* Crawford Gilles (Senior Independent Director)\n* Mary Anne Citrino (Barclays Group Non-Executive Director)\n* Dawn Fitzpatrick (Barclays Group Non-Executive Director)\n* Matthew Lester (Barclays Group Non-Executive Director)\n\n==Sponsorships==\n[[File:Barclays Cycle Hire, St. Mary Axe, Aldgate.jpg|thumb|right|A [[Barclays Cycle Hire]] docking station in central London]]\nBarclays sponsored the [[2008 Dubai Tennis Championships]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dubaitennischampionships.com/ |title=Dubai Tennis Championships |publisher=Dubai Tennis Championships |date=20 February 2011 |accessdate=18 April 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204233458/http://www.dubaitennischampionships.com/ |archivedate=4 December 2008 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nBarclays was the sponsor of the [[Barclays Cycle Hire]] scheme in London from 2010 to 2015, as part of a \u00a325&nbsp;million deal with Transport for London.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2010/jul/27/boris-johnson-london-cycle-hire-barclays |title=Boris Johnson's London Cycle Hire scheme flogs our birthright to Barclays |accessdate=28 April 2012 |work=The Guardian |date=27 July 2010 |first=Justin |last=McGuirk}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10182833 |title=Barclays' \u00a325m sponsorship of London cycle hire scheme |accessdate=28 April 2012 |publisher=BBC News |date=28 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n===Compensation to Jewish Holocaust survivors===\nIn 1998, Barclays Bank agreed to pay $3.6m to Jews whose assets were seized from French branches of the British-based bank during World War II.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news| title=Barclays to Compensate Jews| work=[[BBC News]]| publisher=BBC.com| date=17 December 1998| accessdate=13 September 2013| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/237392.stm}}</ref> Barclays, along with seven French banks, was named in a lawsuit filed in New York on behalf of Jews who were unable to reclaim money they deposited during the Nazi era.<ref name=\"bbc\"/>\n\n===Financial support for the government in Zimbabwe===\nBarclays helped to fund President [[Robert Mugabe]]'s government in [[Zimbabwe]].<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article2848046.ece Barclays bankrolls Mugabe\u2019s brutal regime] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007172946/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article2848046.ece |date=7 October 2008}}</ref> The most controversial of a set of loans provided by Barclays is the \u00a330 million it gave to help sustain land reforms that saw Mugabe seize white-owned farmland and drive more than 100,000 black workers from their homes. Opponents have called the bank's involvement a 'disgrace' and an 'insult' to the millions who have suffered human rights abuses.<ref>{{cite news |first1=Antony |last1=Barnett |first2=Christopher |last2=Thompson |url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/2007/jan/28/accounts.Zimbabwenews |title=Barclays' millions help to prop up Mugabe regime |work=The Guardian |location=Manchester |date=28 January 2007 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> Barclays spokesmen say the bank has had customers in Zimbabwe for decades and abandoning them now would make matters worse, \"We are committed to continuing to provide a service to those customers in what is clearly a difficult operating environment\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Macleod |first=Murdo |url=http://news.scotsman.com/zimbabwe/Barclays-helping-to-fund-Mugabe.3497546.jp |title=Barclays' 'helping to fund Mugabe regime' |work=The Scotsman |date=11 November 2007 |accessdate=18 April 2011 |location=Edinburgh}}</ref>\n\nBarclays also provides two of Mugabe's associates with bank accounts, ignoring European Union sanctions on Zimbabwe.<ref>{{cite web|last=Macleod |first=Murdo |url=http://scotlandonsunday.scotsman.com/zimbabwe/Barclays-helping-to-fund-Mugabe.3497546.jp |title=Barclays 'helping to fund Mugabe regime' |work=The Scotsman |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> The men are Elliot Manyika and minister of public service Nicholas Goche. Barclays has defended its position by insisting that the EU rules do not apply to its 67%-owned Zimbabwean subsidiary because it was incorporated outside the EU.<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/africa/article4232283.ece Robert Mugabe henchmen backed by Barclays] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604144412/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/africa/article4232283.ece |date=4 June 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Accusations of money laundering===\nIn March 2009, Barclays was accused of violating international anti-[[money laundering]] laws. According to the NGO [[Global Witness]], the Paris branch of Barclays held the account of Equatorial Guinean President [[Teodoro Obiang Nguema Mbasogo|Teodoro Obiang]]'s son, [[Teodoro Nguema Obiang Mangue|Teodorin Obiang]], even after evidence that Obiang had siphoned oil revenues from government funds emerged in 2004. According to Global Witness, Obiang purchased a [[Ferrari]] and maintains a mansion in [[Malibu, California|Malibu]] with the funds from this account.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/7936335.stm |title= Barclays 'corrupt regime' claim |accessdate=9 March 2009 |last=Shankleman |first=Martin |date=11 March 2009 |publisher=BBC News |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090314035815/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/7936335.stm |archivedate=14 March 2009| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA 2010 report by the Wall Street Journal described how [[Credit Suisse]], Barclays, [[Lloyds Banking Group]], and other banks were involved in helping the [[Alavi Foundation]], [[Bank Melli Iran|Bank Melli]], the Iranian government, and/or others circumvent US laws banning financial transactions with certain states. They did this by 'stripping' information out of wire transfers, thereby concealing the source of funds. Barclays settled with the government for US$298&nbsp;million.<ref>\"Probe Circles Globe to Find Dirty Money\", Carrick Mollenkamp, ''The Wall Street Journal'', 3 September 2010</ref>\n\n===Tax avoidance===\n{{further|tax avoidance}}\nIn March 2009, Barclays obtained an injunction against ''[[The Guardian]]'' to remove from its website confidential leaked documents describing how SCM, Barclays' structured capital markets division, planned to use more than \u00a311 billion of loans to create hundreds of millions of pounds of tax benefits, via \"an elaborate circuit of [[Cayman Islands]] companies, US partnerships and [[Luxembourg]] subsidiaries\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2009/mar/17/barclays-guardian-injunction-tax |title=Barclays gags Guardian over tax |work=[[The Guardian]] |date= 17 March 2009|accessdate=2 February 2012 |location=London}}</ref> In an editorial on the issue, ''The Guardian'' pointed out that, due to the mismatch of resources, tax-collectors ([[HMRC]]) now have to rely on websites such as [[WikiLeaks]] to obtain such documents,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2009/mar/17/barclays-tax-secret-documents |title=Editorial: Barclays' secret documents |work=The Guardian |date=24 January 2012 |accessdate=2 February 2012 |location=London}}</ref> and indeed the documents in question have now appeared on WikiLeaks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/wiki/The_Guardian:_Censored_Barclays_tax_avoidance_leaked_memos%2C_16_Mar_2009 |title=Barclays Bank gags Guardian over leaked memos detailing offshore tax scam |publisher=WikiLeaks |date=16 March 2009 |accessdate=2 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090414025059/http://wikileaks.org/wiki/The_Guardian%3A_Censored_Barclays_tax_avoidance_leaked_memos%2C_16_Mar_2009 |archivedate=14 April 2009  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://weblogs3.nrc.nl/klaver/2009/03/17/guardian-moet-documenten-van-site-verwijderen/ |title=Marie-Jose Klaver \" Guardian moet documenten van site verwijderen |work=NRC Handelsblad |accessdate=2 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120802105804/http://weblogs3.nrc.nl/klaver/2009/03/17/guardian-moet-documenten-van-site-verwijderen/ |archivedate=2 August 2012 }}</ref> Separately, another Barclays [[whistleblower]] revealed several days later that the SCM transactions had produced between \u00a3900 million and \u00a31 billion in tax avoidance in one year, adding that \"The deals start with tax and then commercial purpose is added to them.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Felicity Lawrence and [[David Leigh (journalist)|David Leigh]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2009/mar/19/new-barclays-tax-whistleblower-claims |title=New whistleblower claims over \u00a31bn Barclays tax deals |work=The Guardian |date= 19 March 2009 |accessdate=2 February 2012 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012 Barclays was forced to pay \u00a3500&nbsp;million in tax which it had tried to avoid. Barclays was accused by [[HMRC]] of designing two schemes that were intended to avoid substantial amounts of tax. Tax rules forced the bank to tell the UK authorities about its plans.<ref name=\"BBCFeb28\">{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-17181213| title=Barclays Bank told by Treasury to pay \u00a3500 million avoided tax| work=[[BBC News]]| accessdate=29 February 2012| date=28 February 2012}}</ref> [[David Gauke]], [[Exchequer Secretary to the Treasury]], said that \"We do not take today's action lightly, but the potential tax loss from this scheme and the history of previous abuse in this area mean that this is a circumstance where the decision to change the law with full retrospective effect is justified.\"<ref name=\"BBCFeb28\"/>\n\n===Rate-fixing scandal===\n{{main|Libor scandal}}\nIn June 2012, as a result of an international investigation, Barclays Bank was fined a total of \u00a3290&nbsp;million (US$450&nbsp;million) for manipulating the daily settings of London Interbank Offered Rate ([[Libor]]) and the Euro Interbank Offered Rate ([[Euribor]]). The United States Department of Justice and Barclays officially agreed that \"the manipulation of the submissions affected the fixed rates on some occasions\".<ref name=\"usdoj statement of facts\">{{cite web| url=http://www.justice.gov/iso/opa/resources/9312012710173426365941.pdf | title=Statement of Facts| publisher=United States Department of Justice| date=26 June 2012| accessdate=11 July 2012}}</ref> The bank was found to have made 'inappropriate submissions' of rates which formed part of the Libor and Euribor setting processes, sometimes to make a profit, and other times to make the bank look more secure during the financial crisis.<ref name=bbc_libor_manipulation/> This happened between 2005 and 2009, as often as daily.<ref name=cbs_libor_manipulation/>\n\nThe [[BBC]] said revelations concerning the fraud were \"greeted with almost universal astonishment in the banking industry.\"<ref>{{cite news| first=Ian| last=Pollock| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-18622907| title=Libor scandal: Who might have lost?| work=BBC News |date=28 June 2012| accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> The UK's [[Financial Services Authority]] (FSA), which levied a fine of \u00a359.5&nbsp;million ($92.7&nbsp;million), gave Barclays the biggest fine it had ever imposed in its history.<ref name=cbs_libor_manipulation>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-505123_162-57462315/barclays-to-pay-$453m-for-attempting-to-manipulate-rates/| title=Barclays to pay largest civil fine in CFTC history| work=CBS News| date=27 June 2012| accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref> The FSA's director of enforcement described Barclays' behaviour as \"completely unacceptable\", adding \"Libor is an incredibly important benchmark reference rate, and it is relied on for many, many hundreds of thousands of contracts all over the world.\"<ref name=bbc_libor_manipulation/> The bank's chief executive [[Bob Diamond (banker)|Bob Diamond]] decided to give up his bonus as a result of the fine.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/business/2012-06/28/c_123339718.htm| title=Barclays to pay over 450 million dollars to settle charges regarding LIBOR| agency=Xinhua News Agency| date=27 June 2012| accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref> [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] politician [[Lord Oakeshott]] criticised Diamond, saying: \"If he had any shame he would go. If the Barclays board has any backbone, they'll sack him.\"<ref name=bbc_libor_manipulation>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-18612279|title=Barclays fined for attempts to manipulate Libor rates |publisher=BBC News |date=27 June 2012 |accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref> The US Department of Justice has also been involved, with \"other financial institutions and individuals\" under investigation.<ref name=bbc_libor_manipulation/> On 2 July 2012, Marcus Agius resigned from the chairman position following the interest rate rigging scandal.<ref>{{cite news |agency=Reuters |title=Barclays chairman resigns over interest rate rigging scandal |url=http://profit.ndtv.com/News/Article/barclays-chairman-to-resign-over-interest-rate-rigging-scandal-307175 |accessdate=2 July 2012 |newspaper=NDTV profit |date=2 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120704215734/http://profit.ndtv.com/News/Article/barclays-chairman-to-resign-over-interest-rate-rigging-scandal-307175 |archivedate=4 July 2012  }}</ref> On 3 July 2012, Bob Diamond resigned with immediate effect, leaving Marcus Agius to fill his post until a replacement is found.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-18685040 |title=Barclays boss Bob Diamond resigns amid Libor scandal |publisher=BBC News |date=3 July 2012 |accessdate=30 July 2012}}</ref> Within the space of a few hours, this was followed by the resignation of the Bank's chief operating officer, Jerry del Missier.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://business.inquirer.net/68943/bob-diamond-quits-as-barclays-ceo |title=Bob Diamond quits as Barclays CEO |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |accessdate=25 April 2014}}</ref> Barclays subsequently announced that Antony Jenkins, its existing chief executive of Global Retail & Business Banking would become group chief executive on 30 August 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=25068045&ticker=BARC:LN |title=Executive Profile Antony P. Jenkins |publisher=[[Bloomberg Business]] |date=23 June 2015}}</ref> On 17 February 2014 the [[Serious Fraud Office (United Kingdom)|Serious Fraud Office]] charged three former bank employees with manipulating Libor rates between June 2005 and August 2007.<ref name=\"SFO-arrests\">{{cite news |url=http://www.londonmercury.com/index.php/sid/220121417/scat/fad6c6ce3bc72160/ht/Three-former-Barclays-staff-charged-for-alleged-Libor-rates-manipulation |archive-url=https://archive.today/20140218021810/http://www.londonmercury.com/index.php/sid/220121417/scat/fad6c6ce3bc72160/ht/Three-former-Barclays-staff-charged-for-alleged-Libor-rates-manipulation |url-status=dead |archive-date=18 February 2014 |title=Three former Barclays staff charged for alleged Libor rates manipulation |work=London Mercury |date=17 February 2014 }}</ref> Four employees were jailed in July 2016 for up to six-and-a-half years, with two others cleared after a retrial.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-39514924|title=Traders found not guilty in Libor retrial|last=Johnston|first=Chris|date=2017-04-06|access-date=2019-04-28|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===Qatari capital raising regulatory investigations===\nBarclays' June and November 2008 capital raisings are the subject of investigations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.euromoney.com/Article/3198818/Category/17/ChannelPage/0/Barclays-Qatari-capital-raising-timeline.html |title=Barclays' Qatari capital-raising timeline |work=Euromoney |date=21 May 2013}}</ref>\nThe UK's [[Serious Fraud Office (United Kingdom)|Serious Fraud Office]] commenced its investigation in August 2012. In October 2012, the [[United States Department of Justice]] and the [[US Securities and Exchange Commission]] informed Barclays they had commenced an investigation into whether the group's relationships with third parties who assist Barclays to win or retain business are compliant with the US [[Foreign Corrupt Practices Act]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://reports.barclays.com/ar12/financialstatements/notes/accrualsprovisionslegalproceedingsandcontingentliabilities/30competitionandregulatorymatters.html |title=30 Competition and regulatory matters \u2013 Annual Report 2012 |publisher=Barclays.com}}</ref>\nThe [[Financial Services Authority]] announced an expansion of the investigation into the Barclays-Qatar deal in January 2013, focusing on the disclosure surrounding the ownership of the securities in the bank.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/47d412ce-6bd1-11e2-a700-00144feab49a.html |title=Barclays in Qatar loan probe |work=Financial Times |date=31 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nBarclays had sought to raise capital privately, avoiding direct equity investment from the [[Government of the United Kingdom]] and, therefore, a bailout. The result was Abu Dhabi's \u00a33.5&nbsp;billion investment in the bank, a deal in which [[Sheikh Mansour bin Zayed al Nahyan|H.H. Sheikh Mansour bin Zayed Al Nahyan]] made a profit of \u00a33.5&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.euromoney.com/Article/3198637/Category/17/ChannelPage/0/Revealed-The-truth-about-Barclays-and-the-Abu-Dhabi-investment.html |title=Revealed: The truth about Barclays and the Abu Dhabi investment |publisher=Euromoney.com |date=30 April 2013}}</ref>\nMuch of the focus to date has been on the injections by Qatar in June and November 2008, notably the so far unproven allegation that Barclays lent Qatar the money to invest in the bank. Other questions include what happened to the \u00a3110&nbsp;million in fees paid by Barclays ostensibly to Sheikh Mansour, and the \u00a366&nbsp;million provided by Barclays to the Qataris for unexplained \"advisory fees\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.euromoney.com/Article/3198635/Barclays-needs-to-come-clean-about-its-Gulf-investments.html |title=Barclays needs to come clean about its Gulf investments |publisher=Euromoney.com |date=30 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, following a five-year investigation by the UK's [[Serious Fraud Office (United Kingdom)|Serious Fraud Office]] covering Barclays' activities during the [[financial crisis of 2007\u20132008]], former CEO [[John Silvester Varley|John Varley]] and three former colleagues, [[Roger Jenkins (banker)|Roger Jenkins]], [[Thomas Kalaris]] and [[Richard Boath]], were charged with [[Conspiracy to defraud|conspiracy to commit fraud]] and the provision of [[Financial assistance (share purchase)|unlawful financial assistance]] in connection with capital raising.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-40338220 |title=Barclays charged with fraud in Qatar case |work=BBC News |date=1 January 1970 |accessdate=20 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Jill |last=Treanor |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2017/jun/20/sfo-charges-barclays-bank-executives-ceo-2008-qatar-fundraising |title=Senior Barclays bankers charged with fraud over credit crunch fundraising |work=The Guardian |date=1 January 1970 |accessdate=20 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, the Serious Fraud Office charged Barclays with \"unlawful financial assistance\" related to billions of pounds raised from the Qatar deal.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-43029731|title=Barclays Bank charged over Qatar loans| date=12 February 2018| work=BBC News| access-date=12 February 2018| language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===US electricity market manipulation===\nIn July 2013 US energy regulator the [[Federal Energy Regulatory Commission]] (FERC) ordered Barclays to pay \u00a3299 million fine penalty for attempting to manipulate the electricity market in the US. The fine by FERC relates to allegations in December 2008.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/jul/17/us-energy-regulator-barclays-fine US energy regulator orders Barclays to pay \u00a3299m fine] The Guardian 17 July 2013</ref>\n\n===Gold price manipulation===\nIn May 2014 the [[Financial Conduct Authority]] fined the bank \u00a326&nbsp;million over systems and controls failures, and conflict of interest in relation to the bank and its customers in connection to the [[gold fixing]] during the period 2004\u20132013, and for manipulation of the gold price on 28 June 2012.<ref name=\"GoldFixing\">{{cite news| title=FCA fines Barclays 26mn pounds over gold price manipulation| url=http://www.thelondonnews.net/index.php/sid/222273039/scat/3a8a80d6f705f8cc/ht/FCA-fines-Barclays-26mn-pounds-over-gold-price-manipulation| accessdate=23 May 2014| publisher=The London News.Net| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525200522/http://www.thelondonnews.net/index.php/sid/222273039/scat/3a8a80d6f705f8cc/ht/FCA-fines-Barclays-26mn-pounds-over-gold-price-manipulation| archive-date=25 May 2014| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===US lawsuit alleging dark pool fraud===\nIn June 2014 the US state of New York filed a lawsuit against the bank alleging it defrauded and deceived investors with inaccurate marketing material about its unregulated trading system known as a ''[[dark pool]]''. Specifically, the firm was accused of hiding the fact that [[Tradebot]] participated in the dark pool when they were in fact one of the largest players. The state, in its complaint, said it was being assisted by former Barclays executives and it was seeking unspecified damages. The bank's shares dropped 5% on news of the lawsuit, prompting an announcement to the [[London Stock Exchange]] by the bank saying it was taking the allegations seriously, and was co-operating with the [[New York attorney general]].<ref name=\"BarclaysVsNY\">{{cite news| title=Dark pool fraud lawsuit filed against Barclays in US| url=http://www.newyorktelegraph.com/index.php/sid/223293195/scat/3a8a80d6f705f8cc/ht/Dark-pool-fraud-lawsuit-filed-against-Barclays-in-US| archive-url=https://archive.today/20140628010744/http://www.newyorktelegraph.com/index.php/sid/223293195/scat/3a8a80d6f705f8cc/ht/Dark-pool-fraud-lawsuit-filed-against-Barclays-in-US| url-status=dead| archive-date=28 June 2014| date=27 June 2014| work=New York Telegraph| accessdate=16 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nA month later the bank filed a motion for the suit to be dismissed, saying there had been no fraud, no victims and no harm to anyone. The New York Attorney General's office issued a statement saying the attorney general was confident the motion would fail.<ref name=\"BarclaysDefense\">{{cite news| title=Barclays seeks dismissal of New York dark pool suit| url=http://www.thelondonnews.net/index.php/sid/224095831/scat/3a8a80d6f705f8cc/ht/Barclays-seeks-dismissal-of-New-York-dark-pool-suit| archive-url=https://archive.today/20140806065744/http://www.thelondonnews.net/index.php/sid/224095831/scat/3a8a80d6f705f8cc/ht/Barclays-seeks-dismissal-of-New-York-dark-pool-suit| url-status=dead| archive-date=6 August 2014| accessdate=25 July 2014| publisher=The London News.Net}}</ref> On 31 January 2016, Barclays settled with both the New York Attorney General's office and the SEC, agreeing to pay $70 million split evenly between the SEC and New York state, admitting it violated securities laws and agreeing to install an independent monitor for the dark pool.<ref name=\"BarclaysSettlement\">{{cite news| title=Barclays, Credit Suisse strike record deals with SEC, NY over dark pools| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/sec-new-york-darkpools-idUSL2N15G0KS| accessdate=1 February 2015| publisher=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n===Exchange-rate rigging (last-look system)===\nBarclays agreed to pay $150 million to resolve an investigation by New York's banking regulator into a trading practice that allowed the bank to exploit a milliseconds-long lag between an order and its execution that sometimes hurt its clients, the latest fallout from the bank's foreign-exchange business.<ref name=\"WSJ_BarclaysLastLook\">{{cite news| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/barclays-to-pay-150-million-over-last-look-trading-system-1447860696| title=Barclays to Pay $150 Million Over 'Last Look' Trading System| first=Christopher M.| last=Matthews| date=18 November 2015| work=The Wall Street Journal| accessdate=19 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn certain instances, Barclays used this [[Last look (foreign exchange)|last-look]] system to automatically reject client orders that would be unprofitable for the bank because of subsequent price swings during milliseconds-long latency (\"hold\") periods. Furthermore, when clients questioned Barclays about these rejected trades, Barclays failed to disclose the reason that the trades were being rejected, instead citing technical issues or providing vague responses.<ref name=\"NYDoFS_BarclaysLastLook\">{{cite press release| title=NYDFS Announces Barclays to Pay Additional $150 Million Penalty, Terminate Employee for Automated, Electronic Foreign Exchange Trading Misconduct| publisher=New York Department of Financial Services| url=http://www.dfs.ny.gov/about/press/pr1511181.htm| date=18 November 2015| accessdate=19 March 2016| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160318213118/http://www.dfs.ny.gov/about/press/pr1511181.htm| archive-date=18 March 2016| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Unsuitable mutual fund transactions===\nAccording to the [[Financial Industry Regulatory Authority]], Barclays' inadequate supervisory procedures failed to stop many customers from swapping one mutual fund for another when the benefits of switching might be undermined by the transaction costs, resulting in $8.63 million of losses for their customers between January 2010 and June 2015. Additionally, from March to August 2014, Barclays processed 1,723 fund transactions that were inconsistent with its customers' goals, risk tolerance or other investments which caused an additional $818,000 of customer harm. As a result, Barclays was required to pay $10 million in restitution, including interest, to affected customers and was fined $3.75 million, but did not admit or deny wrongdoing.<ref>{{cite news|title=Barclays in $13.75 mln U.S. settlement over mutual funds|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/barclays-mutualfunds-settlement-idUSL1N14I0VX20151229|accessdate=1 February 2015|publisher=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n=== Staff monitoring ===\n<span name=\"OLE_LINK20\"></span>In a pilot programme at its London headquarters, the company used tracking software to assess how long employees spent at their desks and warn them if they took excessive breaks. Staff who spent too much time away could find this mentioned on their daily report cards. Following criticisms by staff, the bank said it had taken steps to ensure that individual data would no longer be visible to managers.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/feb/20/barlays-using-dytopian-big-brother-tactics-to-spy-on-staff-says-tuc|title=Barclays using 'Big Brother' tactics to spy on staff, says TUC|last=|first=|date=20 February 2020|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> \n\n<span name=\"OLE_LINK20\"></span>The bank faced similar privacy concerns in 2017 when it used OccupEye sensors to track staff through black boxes in their desks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/barclays-bank-sensors-a7901566.html|title=Barclays installs sensors to see which bankers are at their desks|last=|first=|date=19 August 2017|website=The Independent|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* The bank faced similar privacy concerns in 2017 over its use of OccupEye sensors that tracked staff through black boxes installed under their desks.\n* {{cite book|last=[[Anthony Tuke (1897\u20131975)|Tuke]]|first=A. W.|title=Barclays Bank Limited, 1926\u20131969: Some Recollections|year=1972|publisher=Barclays Bank Ltd|location=London|isbn=978-0-9500442-8-6|author2=Gillman, R. J. H.}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Banks|Business and economics|Companies|London}}\n* [[List of largest banks]]\n* [[Chip Authentication Program]] (PINsentry)\n* [[European Financial Services Roundtable]]\n* [[List of banks in the United Kingdom]]\n* [http://www.bankinghistory.org eabh (The European Association for Banking and Financial History e.V.)]\n\n==Notes==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book|last=Gamble|first=Audrey Nona|title=A History of the Bevan Family|url=https://archive.org/details/historyofbevanfa00gamb|year=1924|publisher=Headley Brothers|location=London|oclc=18546896}}\n* Raychaudhuri, Tappan, Irfan Habib, & Dharma Kumar, eds. (1983) ''The Cambridge Economic History of India: Volume 2, c.1751-c.1970''. (CUP Archive). {{ISBN|9780521228022}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.thebanker.com/Top-1000-World-Banks|accessdate=18 April 2011|title=Top 1000 World Banks 2010|work=[[The Banker]]}}\n*{{cite news|title=Amer Sajed appointed Chief Executive of Barclaycard|url=http://www.pressat.co.uk/releases/amer-sajed-appointed-chief-executive-of-barclaycard-761ce1df44019f8478cf490e1f2f7ea5/}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Barclays}}\n* {{official website|http://home.barclays}}\n* {{OpenCorp|Barclays}}\n* {{PM20|FID=co/002559|TEXT=Documents and clippings about|NAME=}}\n\n{{Barclays}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list =\n{{Commercial and retail banks in the United Kingdom}}\n{{FTSE 100 Index constituents}}\n{{Members of Euro Banking Association}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Barclays|*]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in the 1690s]]\n[[Category:Banks established in the 17th century]]\n[[Category:Banks of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the London Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the New York Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Companies formerly listed on the Tokyo Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies based in London]]\n[[Category:Systemically important financial institutions]]\n[[Category:1690 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Companies based in the London Borough of Tower Hamlets]]\n[[Category:British brands]]\n[[Category:Clan Barclay]]\n", "name_user": "Tapwreck", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barclays"}
{"title_page": "Adore You (Harry Styles song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name          = Adore You\n| cover         = Adore You - Harry Styles.png\n| alt           =\n| type          = single\n| artist        = [[Harry Styles]]\n| album         = [[Fine Line (album)|Fine Line]]\n| B-side        = \n| released      = {{Start date|2019|12|6|df=y}}\n| format        = {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| recorded      = \n| studio        =\n| genre         = <!-- Please source genres -->\n* [[Soul music|Soul]]\n* [[pop rock]]<!--both genres sourced in Composition-->\n| length        = {{Duration|m=3|s=27}}\n| label         = {{hlist|Erskine|[[Columbia Records|Columbia]]}}\n| writer        = {{hlist|[[Harry Styles]]|[[Amy Allen (songwriter)|Amy Allen]]|[[Tyler Johnson (musician)|Tyler Johnson]]|[[Kid Harpoon|Thomas Hull]]}}\n| producer      = {{hlist|Johnson|[[Kid Harpoon]]}}\n| prev_title    = [[Watermelon Sugar]]\n| prev_year     = 2019\n| next_title    = [[Falling (Harry Styles song)|Falling]]\n| next_year     = 2020\n| misc          = {{External music video|{{YouTube|yezDEWako8U|\"Adore You\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Adore You'''\" is a song by English singer and songwriter [[Harry Styles]].<ref name=\"Idolator\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.idolator.com/7903744/harry-styles-announces-new-single-adore-you|title=Harry Styles Announces New Single 'Adore You'|date=2 December 2019|website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|access-date=3 December 2019}}</ref> It was released through Erskine and [[Columbia Records]] on 6 December 2019 as the third single from his second studio album, ''[[Fine Line (album)|Fine Line]]''. \"Adore You\" was a commercial success, reaching the top 10 in the United Kingdom, United States, Australia, New Zealand and the top 15 in Canada.\n\n==Background== \nOn 20 November, a [[Twitter]] account with the username \"@visiteroda\" began a marketing campaign in which they promoted the island of Eroda, setting up a website, posting photos, and answering questions from fellow Twitter users.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Vincent|first=Alice|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/artists/inside-eroda-fictional-harry-styles-island-baffled-internet/|title=Inside Eroda, the fictional Harry Styles island that\u2019s baffled the internet|date=2019-12-04|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2020-03-23|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> The island was soon proven to not exist. On 2 December, Styles announced that a new single, \"Adore You\", would be released on 6 December, with Eroda, \"adore\" backwards, being the main focus of the music video.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.idolator.com/7903744/harry-styles-announces-new-single-adore-you|title=Harry Styles Announces New Single &#8220;Adore You&#8221;|date=2019-12-02|website=idolator|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n\"Adore You\" is a [[Soul music|soul]]<ref name=\"The A.V. Club\">{{cite web|title=With Fine Line, Harry Styles transforms into a California-pop iconoclast|url=https://www.avclub.com/with-fine-line-harry-styles-transforms-into-a-californ-1840463199|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|last=Zaleski|first=Annie|date=17 December 2019|accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref> and [[pop rock]]<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite web |last1=Catucci |first1=Nick |title=Harry Styles Is a Rock God and a Gentleman on 'Fine Line' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/harry-styles-fine-line-album-review-925337/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref> track written in the key of C minor and is 99 beats per minute.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://musicstax.com/track/3jjujdWJ72nww5eGnfs2E7|title=Key and BPM of Adore You by Harry Styles - Musicstax|website=Musicstax|accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\n\nOn 17 December 2019, \"Adore You\" debuted at number 35 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. As of April 2020, the song has peaked at number 6, becoming Styles' first top ten single since 2017's \"[[Sign of the Times (Harry Styles song)|Sign of the Times]]\" debuted at number 4.<ref name=\"Hot 100 Top 4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9340653/roddy-ricch-the-box-harry-styles-adore-you-hot-100|title=Roddy Ricch's 'The Box' Leads Hot 100 for 11th Week, Harry Styles' 'Adore You' Hits Top 10|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Hot 100 Top 6\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9352114/the-weeknd-blinding-lights-number-one-second-week-hot-1000|title=The Weeknd's 'Blinding Lights' Shines at No. 1 on Billboard Hot 100 For Second Week|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=April 6, 2020|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> It also became Styles' longest running top 10 single on the Hot 100.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.billboard.com/music/harry-styles/chart-history/HSI/song/1180286|title=Harry Styles Chart History (Hot 100)|accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> This gave Style' his second top 10 of his solo career on the Hot 100, tied with former band-mate [[Zayn Malik]] for the most among all One Direction members.<ref name=\"Hot 100 Top 4\" />  \nAdditionally, the song peaked at number 1 on the [[Mainstream Top 40]] chart, which ranks the most played songs on US pop radio, marking the first number 1 hit for Styles along with other 3 former band-mates,<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9351741/adore-you-tops-pop-songs-chart|title=Harry Styles Earns First Pop Songs No. 1 With 'Adore You,' Becomes Fourth One Direction Member to Reign|work=Billboard|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=6 April  2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"PopSongs3\">{{cite web| url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Harry-Styles/chart-history/TFM|title=Harry Styles Chart History (Pop Songs)|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> and career best since One Direction's \"[[What Makes You Beautiful]]\" peaked at number 3.<ref name=\"PopSongs3\">{{cite web| url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Harry-Styles/chart-history/TFM|title=Harry Styles Chart History (Pop Songs)|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> The song also peaked at number 5 on the [[Adult Top 40]] chart,<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.billboard.com/music/harry-styles/chart-history/ATF|title=Harry Styles, AC Top 40 Chart History|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> and 13 on [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]] chart.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.billboard.com/music/harry-styles/chart-history/ASI|title=Harry Styles, Adult Contemporary Chart History|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the singer's native UK, the song peaked at number 7 on the [[UK Singles Chart]], his third top 10 solo entry on the chart.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/51376/harry-styles/|title=Harry Styles, Full Official Charts History|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> On the [[Canadian Hot 100]] chart, the song peaked at number 13, making it the highest performing single of the album in Canada. <ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.billboard.com/music/harry-styles/chart-history/CAN|title=Chart History;Harry Styles: BILLBOARD CANADIAN HOT 100|accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> In Australia, the single reached number 1 on the ''[[The Music Network]]'' Australian Airplay Chart, marking Styles' first ever number 1 on Australian radio.<ref name=Aussie100>{{cite web| url=https://themusicnetwork.com/harry-styles-adore-you/|title=Harry Styles claims first Aussie airplay #1 with 'Adore You'|work=The Music Network|last=Wilson|first=Zanda|date=18 April 2020|accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video was also released on 6 December 2019, directed by [[Dave Meyers (director)|Dave Meyers]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8545142/harry-styles-shares-adore-you-teaser-video|title=Harry Styles Visits Eroda, Takes Magical Journey Under the Sea in 'Adore You' Teaser: Watch|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=3 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://diymag.com/2019/12/02/harry-styles-official-trailer-new-track-adore-you|title=Harry Styles shares official trailer for new track 'Adore You'|last=Subscribe|website=DIY|language=en|access-date=3 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spin1038.com/music/watch-harry-styles-drops-official-trailer-adore-music-video-932452|title=WATCH: Harry Styles Drops Official Trailer For His Adore You Music Video|last=Walsh|first=Tara|website=SPIN1038|access-date=3 December 2019}}</ref> The video, just under eight minutes long, shows Styles as a boy from the fishing village of Eroda who is an outcast due to him being the only one on the island who smiles.<ref>https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/watch-harry-styles-adore-you-music-video.html</ref> In the video, Styles finds a fish who is washed up on shore, and cares for it as it grows, much to the judgement of fellow Eroda citizens. At the end of the video, the fish bursts out of its tank, and residents help Styles return the fish back to the water.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/harry-styles-adore-you-video-921040/|title=Harry Styles Finds Common Ground With a Fish out of Water in 'Adore You' Video|last=Shaffer|first=Claire|last2=Shaffer|first2=Claire|date=2019-12-06|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> The main scenes of the video featuring Harry Styles were filmed in the Scottish fishing village of [[St Abbs]]. Additional supporting scenes were filmed in Cockenzie and Port Seton. The first two minutes of the video contains a narration by Spanish singer [[Rosal\u00eda (singer)|Rosal\u00eda]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/harry-styles-shares-new-song-adore-you-listen/|title=Harry Styles Shares Rosal\u00eda-Narrated Video for New Song \u201cAdore You\u201d: Watch|website=Pitchfork|language=en-US|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Live performances==\nOn 7 December 2019, Styles performed the song for the first time on ''[[The Graham Norton Show]]''. On 10 December 2019, he performed the song on ''[[The Late Late Show with James Corden]]''.\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2019\u20132020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|Australia|7|artist=Harry Styles|song=Adore You|rowheader=true|accessdate=21 December 2019}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|59|artist=Harry Styles|song=Adore You|rowheader=true|accessdate=16 January 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders|12|artist=Harry Styles|song=Adore You|rowheader=true|accessdate=29 February 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Wallonia|8|artist=Harry Styles|song=Adore You|rowheader=true|accessdate=4 April 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Bolivia ([[Monitor Latino]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://charts.monitorlatino.com/top20/Print/Bolivia/general/20200323|title=Top 20 Bolivia \u2013 Del 23 al 29 de Marzo, 2020|accessdate=2 April 2020|language=Spanish|publisher=[[Monitor Latino]]}}</ref>\n| 11\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Brazil ([[Top 100 Brasil]])<ref name=\"brazilianchart\">{{cite web|url=https://charts.crowley.com.br/index.html|title=Top 100 Brasil \u2013 06/04/2020 - 10/04/20|publisher=[[Crowley Broadcast Analysis]]|accessdate=15 April 2020|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n| 70\n|-\n{{single chart|Canada|12|artist=Harry Styles|rowheader=true|accessdate=21 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Czech Republic|32|year=2020|week=15|rowheader=true|accessdate=15 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Czechdigital|17|year=2019|week=51|rowheader=true|accessdate=24 December 2019}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Denmark ([[Tracklisten]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitlisten.nu/default.asp?w=2&y=2020&list=t40|title=Track Top-40 Uge 2, 2020|publisher=[[Hitlisten]]|accessdate=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n| 28\n|-\n{{single chart|Finland|19|artist=Harry Styles|song=Adore You|r