 HIV/AIDS}}\n[[File:People specially women visiting the Red Ribbon Express on tour creating AIDS awareness all over India arrived in Chennai on May 27, 2012.jpg|thumb|People specially women visiting the [[Red Ribbon Express]] on tour creating AIDS awareness all over India arrived in Chennai on May 27, 2012.]]\n[[File:Know Aids - No Aids.jpg|thumb|\"Know AIDS - No AIDS\" sign on a road in India.]]\n\nIndia has been praised for its extensive anti-AIDS campaign.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4583071.stm|title=Clinton lauds India Aids campaign|author=|date=26 May 2005|publisher=|accessdate=6 April 2018|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> According to Michel Sidib\u00e9, Executive Director of UNAIDS, India's success comes from using an evidence-informed and human rights-based approach that is backed by sustained political leadership and civil society engagement. India must now strive to achieve universal access to HIV prevention, treatment, care and support.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nacoonline.org/upload/HomePage/NACO%20Press%20Release%20on%20HIV%20Estimates.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110101135322/http://www.nacoonline.org/upload/HomePage/NACO%20Press%20Release%20on%20HIV%20Estimates.pdf |archivedate=2011-01-01 |title=HIV declining in India; New infections reduced by 50% from 2000\u20132009; Sustained focus on prevention required |publisher=Government of India, Ministry of Health & Family Welfare, Department of AIDS Control, National AIDS Control Organisation }}</ref>\n\nThe 2012 UNAIDS report lauded India for doing \"particularly well\" in halving the number of adults newly infected between 2000 and 2009 and said some smaller countries in Asia like [[Afghanistan]] and [[Philippines]] are experiencing increases in the number of people acquiring HIV infection. In India, the figure for deaths due to AIDS stood at 170,000 in 2009. The report says India has contributed enormously to the AIDS response. \"With 80 per cent of these drugs being generics purchased in India, several billion dollars have been saved over the past five years. The country is also committed to new forms of partnership with low-income countries through innovative support mechanisms and South Asia cooperation\" the UNAIDS report says. It also points out that India already provides substantial support to neighbouring countries and other Asian countries \u2013 in 2011, it allocated [[USD]] 430 million to 68 projects in [[Bhutan]] across key socio-economic sectors, including health, education and capacity-building. In 2011 at Addis Ababa, the [[Government of India]] further committed to accelerating technology transfer between its [[pharmaceutical]] sector and African manufacturers.\n\nThe National AIDS Control Organisation (NACO) has increased the number of centres providing free Antiretroviral Treatment (ART) from 54 to 91 centres with another 9 more centres also getting operational soon{{when|date=June 2019}}. At these 91 centres medicines for treating 8,500 patients have been made available. All the 91 centres have specially appointed and trained doctors, counsellors and laboratory technicians to help initiate patients on ART and follow them up regularly. The ART is a combination of three potent drugs, which is being given to the persons with advanced stage of AIDS. Although these drugs do not cure HIV infection, they suppress multiplication of the virus and reduce the number of opportunistic infections thereby improving the quality of life and prolonging the life span. Apart from providing free treatment, all the ART centres are providing counselling to the infected persons so that they maintain regularity of their medication. Continuity is the most important factor for the long term effectiveness of the ART drugs as disruption can lead to drug resistance.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}} At present 40,000 are on ART, which are expected to go up to 85,000 by March end.{{when|date=June 2019}} All these centres have a plan to ensure that patients take their medicines regularly and are followed up, in case of default, while maintaining their confidentiality.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\nResponding to a petition made by NGO's, in December 2010, the [[Supreme Court of India]] directed Indian government to provide second-line [[Antiretroviral drug|Antiretroviral Therapy (ART)]] to all AIDS patients in the country, by warning the government against abdicating its constitutional duty of providing treatment to HIV positive patients on grounds of financial constraint, as it was issue of the [[right to life]] guaranteed under Article 21 of the [[Indian Constitution]]. Previously in an affidavit before the Supreme Court, NACO had said second-line ART treatment for HIV patients, costing Rs28,500 each, could not be extended to those who had received \"irrational treatment\" by private medical practitioners for the first round, which costs around Rs 6,500. The court rejected both the arguments of financial constraints and only 10 [[viral load]] testing centres needed for test patients for migrating from first line of treatment to the second line being are available, raised by the [[Solicitor General of India|Solicitor General]] representing the government. The court further asked the government to give a clear-cut and \"workable\" solution response within a week's time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-12-11/india/28231314_1_hiv-patients-second-line-treatment-second-line-drugs|title=SC forces govt to agree to second-line ART to all AIDS patients|date=11 Dec 2010|work=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/SC-cautions-govt-over-HIV-treatment/Article1-636976.aspx|title=SC cautions govt over HIV treatment|date=11 December 2010|work=Hindustan Times}}</ref>\n\n=== Funding ===\n{{See also|Cost of HIV treatment}}\n\nHIV spending increased in India from 2003 to 2007, and fell by 15% in 2008 to 2009. Currently, India spends about 5% of its health budget on HIV/AIDS. Spending on HIV/AIDS may create a burden in the health sector which faces a variety of other challenges like malaria, diabetes, heart disease and cancer. Thus, it is crucial for India to step up on its prevention efforts to decrease its spending of the health budget on HIV/AIDS in future.<ref name=avert/>\n\nApart from government funding, there are various international foundations like [[United Nations Development Programme|UNDP]], [[World Bank Group|World Bank]], [[Elton John AIDS Foundation]], [[United States Agency for International Development|USAID]] and others who are providing funding for HIV/AIDS in India.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://london.ejaf.org/grants/|title=Grants \u2013 Elton John AIDS Foundation|work=Elton John AIDS Foundation|access-date=2018-08-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://naco.gov.in/about-us/funds-and-expenditures-0|title=Funds and Expenditures {{!}} National AIDS Control Organization {{!}} MoHFW {{!}} GoI|website=naco.gov.in|access-date=2018-08-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/usaid-amcham-join-hands-to-address-indias-development-challenges/articleshow/65200612.cms|title=USAID, AMCHAM join hands to address India's development challenges \u2013 Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2018-08-28}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{see also|History of HIV/AIDS}}\n\nIn [[1986 in India|1986]], the first known case of HIV in India was diagnosed by Dr. [[Suniti Solomon]] and her student Dr. [[Sellappan Nirmala]] amongst six female sex workers in [[Chennai]], Tamil Nadu.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/health/2005-02-23-aids-india_x.htm | title=HIV scars India | first1=Steve | last1=Sternberg | date=23 February 2005 | work=USA Today}}</ref><ref name=nirmala>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-37183012|title=The woman who discovered India's first HIV cases|last=Pandey|first=Geeta|date=2016-08-30|newspaper=BBC News|access-date=2016-12-08}}</ref> In the same year, the [[Government of India]] established the National AIDS Committee within the Ministry of Health and Family Welfare.<ref name=ODI1>Fiona Samuels and Sanju Wagle 2011. [http://www.odi.org.uk/resources/details.asp?id=5733&title=hiv-aids-migration-emphasis-bangladesh-nepal-india Population mobility and HIV and AIDS: review of laws, policies and treaties between Bangladesh, Nepal and India]. London: [[Overseas Development Institute]]</ref>\n\nIn 1992, on the basis of National AIDS Committee, the government set up the National AIDS Control Organisation (NACO) to oversee policies and prevention and control programmes relating to HIV and AIDS and the National AIDS Control Programme (NACP) for HIV prevention.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://naco.gov.in/about-us|title=About Us &#124; National AIDS Control Organization &#124; MoHFW &#124; GoI|website=naco.gov.in}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.radionetherlandsarchives.org/the-next-battleground-aids-in-india/|title=The next battleground: AIDS in India|date=10 October 1993}}</ref> Subsequently, the State AIDS Control Societies (SACS) were set up in states and union territories. SACS implement NACO programme at state level, but have functional independence to upscale and innovate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://naco.gov.in/sacs|title=SACS &#124; National AIDS Control Organization &#124; MoHFW &#124; GoI|website=naco.gov.in}}</ref> The first phase was implemented over seven years (1992\u20131999), focused on monitoring HIV infection rates among risk populations in selected urban areas.<ref name=ODI1/>\n\nIn 1999, the second phase of the National AIDS Control Programme (NACP II) was introduced to decrease the reach of HIV by promoting behaviour change. The prevention of mother-to-child transmission programme (PMTCT) and the provision of antiretroviral treatment were materialised.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sharma|first=Deepak|date=|title=HIV/AIDS: A Life Threatening Disease|url=http://www.thepharmajournal.com/archives/2013/vol2issue2/PartA/19.pdf|journal=The Pharma Innovation|volume= No. 2|pages=146\u2013161|via=TPI International Journal}}</ref>{{citation needed|date=November 2015}} A National Council on AIDS was formed during this phase, consisting of 31 ministries and chaired by the Prime Minister.<ref name=ODI1/> The second phase ran between 1999 and 2006.<ref name=ODI1/>\n\nA 2006 study published in the British medical journal \"[[The Lancet]]\" reported an approximately 30% decline in HIV infections among young women aged 15 to 24 years attending prenatal clinics in selected southern states of India from 2000 to 2004 where the epidemic is thought to be concentrated. Recent studies suggest that many married women in India, despite practising monogamy and having no other risk behaviours, acquire HIV from their husbands and HIV testing of married males can be an effective HIV prevention strategy for general population.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=Epidemiologic+correlates+of+willingness+to+be+tested+for+HIV+and+prior+testing+among+married+men+in+India|title=Epidemiologic correlates of willingness to be tested for HIV and prior testing among married men in India|first1=Aritra|last1=Das|first2=Giridhara R.|last2=Babu|first3=Puspen|last3=Ghosh|first4=Tanmay|last4=Mahapatra|first5=Roberta|last5=Malmgren|first6=Roger|last6=Detels|date=1 December 2013|journal=International Journal of STD & AIDS|volume=24|issue=12|pages=957\u2013968|accessdate=6 April 2018 |doi=10.1177/0956462413488568|pmid=23970619|pmc=5568248}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, the third phase of the National AIDS Control Programme (NACP III) targeted the high-risk groups, conducted outreach programmes,amongst others. It also decentralised the effort to local levels and non-governmental organisations (NGOs) to provide welfare services to the affected.<ref name=avert/> The US$2.5 billion National AIDS Control Plan III was set up by India in 2007 and received support from [[UNAIDS]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unaids.org/en/KnowledgeCentre/Resources/FeatureStories/archive/2007/20070622_India_National_AIDS_control_plan_III.asp|title=India: Driving forward an effective AIDS response|author=|date=|website=unaids.org|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref> The third stage dramatically increased targeted interventions, aiming to halt and reverse the epidemic by integrating programmes for prevention, care, support and treatment.<ref name=ODI1/> By the end of 2008, targeted interventions covered almost 932,000 of those most at risk, or 52% of the target groups (49% of FSWs, 65% of IDUs and 66% of MSM).<ref name=ODI1/>\n\nSome efforts have been made to tailor educational literature to those with low literacy levels, mainly through local libraries as this is the most readily accessible locus of information for interested parties.<ref>Ghosh, Maitrayee 2007 ICT and AIDS Literacy: A Challenge for Information Professionals in India. Electronic Library & Information Systems 41(2):134\u2013147</ref> Increased awareness regarding the disease and citizen's related rights is in line with the [[Universal Declaration on Human Rights]].\n\nIn 2009, India established a National HIV and AIDS Policy and the World of Work, which sought to end discrimination against workers on the basis of their real or perceived HIV status.<ref name=ODI1/> Under this policy all enterprises in the public, private, formal and informal sectors are encouraged to establish workplace policies and programmes based on the principles of non-discrimination, gender equity, health work environment, non-screening for the purpose of employment, confidentiality, prevention and care and support.<ref name=ODI1/> Researchers at the [[Overseas Development Institute]] have called for greater attention to [[migrant workers]], whose concerns about their immigration status may exclude them from these policies and leave them particularly vulnerable.<ref name=ODI1/>\n\nNo agency is tasked with enforcing non-discrimination policy, instead multisectoral approach has been developed involving awareness campaigns in the private sector. The AIDS Bhedbhav Virodhi Andolan (AIDS Anti-Discrimination Movement) had prepared many citizens reports challenging discriminatory policies, and filed a petition in the Delhi High Court regarding the proposed segregation of gay men in prisons. A play titled 'High Fidelity Transmission' by author Rajesh Talwar<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aumag.org/2018/04/22/high-fidelity-transmission-review/|title=High Fidelity Transmission: Review \u2013 A&U Magazine|first=Chael|last=Needle|publisher=}}</ref> has focused on discrimination.the importance of the condom as compared with abstinence and illegal testing of vaccines.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lilainteractions.in/hiv-aids/|title=HIV/AIDS: Closing the Legacy|author=|date=28 November 2014|website=lilainteractions.in|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref> HIV/AIDS-related television shows and movies have appeared in the past few years, mostly in an effort to appeal to the middle class.<ref>Pathak, Prachee 2005 \"Sterling Towers\": A Soap Opera for HIV Awareness Among the Middle Class in Urban India. Dissertations and Theses 2005.</ref> An important component of these programs has been the depiction of HIV/AIDS affected persons interacting with non-infected persons in everyday life.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Bourgault, Louise M. 2009 AIDS Messages in Three AIDS-Themed Indian Movies: Eroding AIDS-Related Stigma in India and Beyond. Critical Arts: A South-North Journal of Cultural & Media Studies 23(2):171\u2013189.</ref>\n\nAs per [[UNDP]]'s 2010 report, India had 2.395 million people living with HIV at the end of 2009, up from 2.27 million in 2008. Adult prevalence also rose from 0.29% in 2008 to 0.31% in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Health-care-fails-to-reach-migrants/Article1-632918.aspx|title=Health care fails to reach migrants|date=1 December 2010|work=Hindustan Times}}</ref> Setting up HIV screening centres was the first step taken by the government to screen its citizens and the blood bank.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\nThe adult HIV prevalence in India is declining from estimated level of 0.41% in 2000 through 0.36% in 2006 to 0.31% in 2009. Adult HIV prevalence at a national level has declined notably in many states, but variations still exist across the states. A decreasing trend is also evident in HIV prevalence among the young population of 15\u201324 years.\n\nA 2012 report described a need for youth HIV counselings.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mothi |first1=SN |last2=Swamy |first2=VH |last3=Lala |first3=MM |last4=Karpagam |first4=S |last5=Gangakhedkar |first5=RR |title=Adolescents living with HIV in India - the clock is ticking. |journal=Indian Journal of Pediatrics |date=December 2012 |volume=79 |issue=12 |pages=1642\u20137 |doi=10.1007/s12098-012-0902-x |pmid=23150229}}</ref>\n\nAccording to NACO data, India has demonstrated an overall reduction of 57 percent in estimated annual new HIV infections (among adult population) from 0.274 million in 2000 to 0.116 million in 2011, and the estimated number of people living with HIV was 2.08 million in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/world-aids-day-india-records-sharp-drop-in-number-of-cases-299730|title=World AIDS Day: India records sharp drop in number of cases|author=|date=|website=ndtv.com|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-sees-50-decline-in-new-hiv-infections-un-report/Article1-680333.aspx | title= India sees 50% decline in new hiv infections: un report | newspaper= Hindustan Times | accessdate= 2011-04-02 | url-status= dead | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110404012150/http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-sees-50-decline-in-new-hiv-infections-un-report/Article1-680333.aspx | archive-date= 4 April 2011 | df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAccording to NACO, the prevalence of AIDS in India in 2015 was 0.26%, down from 0.41% in 2002;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/video/player/news/world-aids-day-india-records-sharp-drop-in-number-of-cases/299798|title=World AIDS Day: India records sharp drop in number of cases|author=|date=|website=ndtv.com|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref> in 2016, it had risen to 0.30%.<ref name=CIA2/>\n\n==Society and culture==\n=== HIV/AIDS (Prevention and Control) Bill 2014 ===\nA long-awaited legislation that seeks to end stigma and discrimination against HIV positive persons in workplace, hospitals and society, while also ensuring their privacy was introduced in the Rajya Sabha on 11-2-2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/content/385858/hivaids-bill-tabled-rajya-sabha.html|title=HIV/Aids bill tabled in Rajya Sabha|date=12 February 2014|website=Deccan Herald}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zeenews.india.com/news/health/health-news/bill-to-end-hiv/aids-discrimination-introduced-in-rajya-sabha_26637.html|title=Bill to end HIV/AIDS discrimination introduced in Rajya Sabha|date=11 February 2014|website=Zee News}}</ref>\nThe HIV and AIDS Bill, 2014 was finally passed by the Rajya Sabha on 21 March 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mishra|first1=Nikita|title=Decoded: The Good and Bad of the HIV Bill Passed by Rajya Sabha|url=https://www.thequint.com/fitness/2016/12/01/world-aids-day-hiv-bill-weak-and-watered-down-prevention-bill-to-be-tabled-in-the-parliament-activists-fuming|website=www.thequint.com|publisher=The Quint|accessdate=23 March 2017|date=December 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Litigation for right of access to treatment ===\n*Voluntary Health Association of Punjab v. Union of India<ref>Writ Petition (Civil) No. 311 of 2003, Supreme Court of India</ref>\n*Love Life Society v. Union of India & Others<ref>Writ Petition (Civil) No. 8700 of 2006, High Court of Delhi</ref>\n*Wahengbam Joykumar v. Union of India & Others<ref>Writ Petition (Civil) No. 7 of 2005, Gauhati High Court</ref>\n*Delhi Network of Positive People & Another v. Union of India & Others<ref>Writ Petition (Civil) No. 2885 of 2007, High Court of Delhi</ref>\n\n=== Orphans ===\n{{see also|AIDS orphan}}\n{{Overly detailed|section|date=February 2020}}\n[[File:Love for all the other AIDS Orphans.jpg|thumb|upright|Orphans who have lost a parent to AIDS celebrate World AIDS Day in Hyderabad, India.]]\n\nStudies show that there are 2 million children in India that have lost one or both parents due to AIDS.<ref name=\":02\" /> There are also millions of vulnerable children living in India, or children \"whose survival, well-being, or development is threatened due to the possibility of exposure to HIV/AIDS.\"<ref name=\":02\">{{cite web |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/223968099|title=AIDS Orphans and Vulnerable Children in India: Problems, Prospects, and Concerns|website=ResearchGate|access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref> Because there are many new cases of AIDS epidemics in various parts of India, the number of these AIDS orphans will continue to grow.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shetty|first=Avinash|date=January 2003|title=Children orphaned by AIDS: A global perspective|url=|journal=Seminars in Pediatric Infectious Disease|volume=14|issue=1|pages=25\u201331|doi=10.1053/spid.2003.127214|pmid=12748919}}</ref>\n\nDue to the negative treatment and lack of resources for these children, AIDS orphans and vulnerable children (OVC) in India are \"vulnerable to be malnourished, uneducated, stigmatised, and discriminated.\" Specifically, the discrimination and stigma surrounding HIV/AIDS has resulted in many health and educational disparities for children orphaned by AIDS or children with an HIV-infected parent. These orphans are also at high risk for becoming infected with HIV themselves, [[Child labour in India|child labour]], [[human trafficking|trafficking]], and [[prostitution]].<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://iussp.confex.com/iussp/ipc2017/meetingapp.cgi/Paper/5863|title=An In-depth Study of Psychological Distress among Orphan Children Living in Institutional Care in New Delhi and their Coping Mechanisms|website=IUSSP \u2013 2017 International Population Conference|access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref>\n\n==== Stigma ====\nAIDS orphans are usually taken care of by extended family members after the passing of a parent.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gilborn|first=Laelia Zoe|date=January 2002|title=The effects of HIV infection and AIDS on children in Africa|journal=Western Journal of Medicine|volume=176|issue=1|pages=12\u201314|issn=0093-0415|pmc=1071640|pmid=11788529|doi=10.1136/ewjm.176.1.12}}</ref> These extended family members may be vulnerable as well, as they are often elderly or ill themselves. A human rights study from 2004 found that many AIDS orphans felt that \"their guardians felt like they could demand anything of them\"<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite journal|last=Csete|first=Joanne|date=2004-06-01|title=Missed Opportunities: Human rights and the politics of HIV/AIDS|journal=Development|language=en|volume=47|issue=2|pages=83\u201390|doi=10.1057/palgrave.development.1100033|issn=1461-7072}}</ref> because no one else could take them in. These children may be forced to look after a sibling or other family members, so they live in their original home even after parents are deceased. The children may be worried about seizure of land by landlords or other neighbours.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nDue to the stigma surrounding HIV in India, children of HIV-infected parents are treated poorly and often do not have access to basic resources. A study done by the Department of Rural Management in Jharkhand, India showed that 35% of children of HIV-infected adults were denied basic amenities.<ref name=\":02\" /> Things like proper nutritious food are often not given to AIDS orphans by their extended families or caretakers.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Ghanashyam|first=Bharathi|date=2010-01-30|title=India failing children orphaned by AIDS|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(10)60151-1/abstract|journal=The Lancet|language=English|volume=375|issue=9712|pages=363\u2013364|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(10)60151-1|issn=0140-6736|pmid=20135747}}</ref> This, combined with the abuse that many orphans face, leads to a higher rate of mortality among AIDS orphans.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Mukiza-Gapere|first=Jackson|last2=Ntozi|first2=James P. M.|date=1995|title=Care for AIDS orphans in Uganda: findings from focus group discussions|url=https://openresearch-repository.anu.edu.au/handle/1885/41300|language=en-AU}}</ref> Higher education rates in caregivers has shown to decrease this stigma.<ref name=\":7\" /> AIDS orphans are often not allowed in orphanages because of the concern that they could have AIDS themselves.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/report/2004/07/28/future-forsaken/abuses-against-children-affected-hiv/aids-india|title=Future Forsaken {{!}} Abuses Against Children Affected by HIV/AIDS in India|last=Avenue|first=Human Rights Watch {{!}} 350 Fifth|last2=York|first2=34th Floor {{!}} New|date=2004-07-28|website=Human Rights Watch|language=en|access-date=2019-04-11|last3=t 1.212.290.4700|first3=NY 10118-3299 USA {{!}}}}</ref>\n\nAIDS orphans were more likely to be bullied by friends or relatives due to the prevalence of stigma against HIV/AIDS in India.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/261442094|title=Depression among AIDS-orphaned children higher than among other orphaned children in southern India|website=ResearchGate|access-date=2019-03-18}}</ref> People may believe HIV can be contracted by proximity, so these orphans lose their friends.<ref name=\":5\" /> Often, women widowed by HIV/AIDS face blame for the outcome of her orphaned child,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Van Hollen|first=Cecilia|date=2010-12-01|title=HIV/AIDS and the Gendering of Stigma in Tamil Nadu, South India|journal=Culture, Medicine, and Psychiatry|language=en|volume=34|issue=4|pages=633\u2013657|doi=10.1007/s11013-010-9192-9|pmid=20842521|issn=1573-076X|url=https://surface.syr.edu/ant/2}}</ref> while families face much isolation during the time of illness and after. Parents often lose their jobs due to workplace discrimination.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Todres|first=Jonathan|date=December 2007|title=Rights Relationships and the Experience of Children Orphaned by AIDS|url=|journal=UC Davis Law Review|volume=41|pages=|via=}}</ref> The Human Rights Watch has found many cases of sexual abuse among female AIDS orphans, which often result in trafficking and prostitution involvement.<ref name=\":9\" /> Policy studies have shown that an increase in quality HIV treatment and care can drastically decrease this discrimination and stigma.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Messer|first=Lynne C.|last2=Pence|first2=Brian W.|last3=Whetten|first3=Kathryn|last4=Whetten|first4=Rachel|last5=Thielman|first5=Nathan|last6=O'Donnell|first6=Karen|last7=Ostermann|first7=Jan|date=2010-08-19|title=Prevalence and predictors of HIV-related stigma among institutional- and community-based caregivers of orphans and vulnerable children living in five less-wealthy countries|journal=BMC Public Health|volume=10|issue=1|page=504|doi=10.1186/1471-2458-10-504|issn=1471-2458|pmc=2936424|pmid=20723246}}</ref>\n\n==== Mental health ====\nThe emotional and social effects on AIDS orphans are very detrimental to their health and future life. Specifically, the [[mental health]] of AIDS orphans in India is shown to be poor as compared to children who were orphaned by other factors.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nBefore becoming orphans, children whose parents suffer from AIDS face many obstacles. There is \"tremendous emotional trauma\" associated with having a parent ill with HIV, and the child often worries about resource scarcity, being separated from siblings, and grief of the impending death of the parent.<ref name=\":6\" /> While the parent is ill, the child experiences long periods of uncertainty and episodic crises, which decreases the child's sense of security and stability.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Children orphaned by AIDS : front-line responses from eastern and southern Africa|date=1999|publisher=UNICEF|oclc=59176094}}</ref>\n\nA study done in orphanages in Hyderabad, India showed that orphans in India who have lost one or both parents to AIDS are 1.3 times as likely to be clinically depressed than children orphaned due to other reasons.<ref name=\":0\" /> The study used The [[Center for Epidemiologic Studies Depression Scale]] (CES-DC) to measure depression in children orphaned by AIDS and children orphaned by other reasons. The mean depression score for AIDS orphans was 34.6, while that of other orphans was 20.6. When questioned, 58.3% of AIDS orphans answered \u201cI felt like crying\u201d a lot as compared to 20.8% of children orphaned by other reasons. 60.3% of AIDS orphans also answered \u201cI felt sad\u201d a lot, while only 20.8% of children orphaned by other reasons answered the same level. In addition, the study showed that the bulk of the depression score was concentrated among children of younger ages for AIDS orphans, while in other orphans it was mostly seen in older children. A distinction was also made between genders; girls orphaned due to AIDS had a higher rate of depression than boys.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nStudies also show that the likelihood of post traumatic stress disorder is common among AIDS orphans. In a study done in South Africa of the mental health of 60 orphans, 73% of the HIV orphans were shown to have PTSD.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Lata|first=Swaran|date=October 2013|title=Mental health of HIV/AIDS orphans: A review|url=|journal=Journal of AIDS and HIV Research|volume=5|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nAnother study done on mental health of different AIDS orphans around the world showed more behavioral problems later in life as compared to other vulnerable children.<ref name=\":3\" /> For example, AIDS orphans were more likely to smoke, be engaged in crime, and drink alcohol.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nWhile further studies about mental health in AIDS orphans in India is limited, a study done in South Africa showed that AIDS orphans viewed themselves as having \"no good friends\" than non-orphans.<ref name=\":3\" /> However, they were less likely to have anger problems. The orphans in this study also showed more frequency of nightmares.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==== Education ====\nBecause AIDS OVC often have many family members either deceased or ill, these orphans are often forced into taking jobs at a young age in order to provide for the rest of their family, resulting in lower attendance at school or being forced to drop out from school completely. For example, orphans that have lost their father due to AIDS are forced to take on field or manual labor jobs, which may be high risk occupations. Orphans that have lost their mothers take on housework and childcare. Girls are more often taken out of school to help with domestic work and care for sick parents.<ref name=\":10\" /> Studies show that 17% of children with HIV-infected parents took on a job to assist with household income.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nThe cost of treatment for HIV is so high that many families often do not have the means to pay for care or education of the child.<ref name=\":8\" /> If a child is forced to drop out of school in order to take on additional responsibility at home due to the illness of his parent, the child is named a \u201cde-facto\u201d orphan.<ref name=\":02\" />&nbsp; There has been no correlation found between gender and risk of poor educational outcomes or risk of dropping out of school.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Sinha|first=Aakanksha|last2=Lombe|first2=Margaret|last3=Saltzman|first3=Leia Y.|last4=Whetten|first4=Kathryn|last5=Whetten|first5=Rachel|date=March 2016|title=Exploring Factors Associated with Educational Outcomes for Orphan and Abandoned Children in India |journal=Global Social Welfare |volume=3|issue=1|pages=23\u201332|doi=10.1007/s40609-016-0043-7|issn=2196-8799|pmc=4830269|pmid=27088068}}</ref> Because of stigma, many AIDS orphans are expelled from school.<ref name=\":10\" />\n\nIn a study on education of orphans in India, the caretaker's health was found to be very important in determining if the orphan was at a target educational standard.<ref name=\":1\" /> When a primary caregiver was in poor health, the odds of the orphan being in the target grade level decreased by 54%.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe prevalence of AIDS orphans around the world has been shown to be a threat to economic development in many countries.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|last=Salaam|first=Tiaji|title=AIDS Orphans and Vulnerable Children (OVC): Problems, Responses, and Issues for Congress|publisher=Congressional Research Service|date=February 11, 2005|url=http://ovcsupport.org/wp-content/uploads/Documents/AIDS_Orphans_and_Vulnerable_Children_OVC_Problems_Responses_and_Issues_for_Congress_1.pdf }}</ref> Because AIDS orphans have a lower chance of completing primary and secondary education, they have a lower chance of entering professions that depend on education level and professional training. These orphans will be more at risk to grow up and engage in high-risk behaviours, resulting in more chance of HIV transmission. Therefore, countries may face a cycle of national poverty and low economic development due to the prevalence of AIDS orphans.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==== Responses ====\nWhile much research has gone into community programming for AIDS orphans, only a few efforts focus on saving the lives of the HIV-infected parents themselves.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Beckerman|first=Karen Palmore|date=2002-04-06|title=Mothers, orphans, and prevention of paediatric AIDS |journal=The Lancet|language=English|volume=359|issue=9313|pages=1168\u20131169|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(02)08248-X |pmid=11955530}}</ref>\n\nWhen comparing institution based care verses community based care, studies have shown that there is less discrimination in the former.<ref name=\":7\" /> However, the government of India has used institutionalizing orphans as the norm, and have not fully explored other options like fostering or community based care for AIDS orphans.<ref name=\":10\" />\n\nIndia pledged to provide better resources for AIDS orphans at the UN General Assembly Special Session on HIV/ AIDS in 2001.<ref name=\":4\" /> In 2007, India was the first country in South Asia to create a national response to children affected by AIDS.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unicef.org/aids/files/NPA_Review_Final__13_August_.pdf|title=National responses for children affected by AIDS: Review of progress and lessons learned|last=Ackerman Gulaid|first=Laurie|date=|website=Unicef|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=}}</ref> India created the Policy Framework For Children, which acknowledges the goal of providing the resources for at least 80% of children affected by HIV/AIDS. This policy takes a rights-based approach. However, this policy fails to address many social determinants of care of AIDS orphans including the social stigma and discrimination, lack of education, and proper nutrition.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nBeginning in 2009, The Department of Women and Child Development in Karnataka allocated $200,000 to address the inequalities that AIDS orphans face. Most of this budget was unspent when evaluated 1 year later.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n[[Juvenile Justice (Care and Protection of Children) Act, 2015|The Juvenile Justice (Care and Protection of Children) Act]] of 2015 was created to provide orphans and vulnerable children in India with the resources and care necessary to reintegrate them into society.\n\n== See also ==\n=== Lists of ART centres ===\nThese centres provide antiretroviral therapy (ART) to the patients.\n* [http://naco.gov.in/sites/default/files/List%20of%20ARTC.pdf List of ARTCs]\n* [http://cnls.lanl.gov/~rajan/AIDS-india/doctors.html HOSPITALS AND DOCTORS SPECIALISING IN HIV/AIDS]\n\n=== Non-governmental organisations ===\nThese are some of the various NGOs working in India for the prevention of HIV/AIDS and accessibility of treatment and medicines. These centres also provide psycho-social support through sustained counselings, acting to function as a bridge between hospital & home care.\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* Aarogya<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aidssupport.aarogya.com/|title=AIDS Support Group|website=aidssupport.aarogya.com}}</ref>\n* [[Ashraya]]\n* End Aids India<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.endaidsindia.org/|title=NGO for AIDS in India, HIV/AIDS Non Profit Campaign in India &#124; End AIDS India|website=www.endaidsindia.org}}</ref>\n* [[Humsafar Trust]]\n* [[India HIV/AIDS Alliance]]\n* [[Naz Foundation (India) Trust]]\n* SAATHII<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Tiruchirapalli/bridging-the-gap-in-hivaids-treatment-in-private-hospitals/article4319192.ece|title=Bridging the gap in HIV-AIDS treatment in private hospitals|last=Gerald|first=Olympia Shilpa|date=2013-01-18|work=The Hindu|access-date=2018-08-28|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n* Samapathik Trust<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punemirror.indiatimes.com/pune/civic/city-hospital-ngo-sign-mou-for-better-lgbti-healthcare/articleshow/67730028.cms|title=City hospital, NGO sign MoU for better LGBTI healthcare|last=Khandge|first=Sukhada|date=|website=Pune Mirror|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-02-03}}</ref>\n* [[Sankalp Rehabilitation Trust]]\n* [[Suraksha Clinic]]\n* [[YRG Care]]\n* [[Udaan Trust]]\n{{colend}}\n\n=== Other topics ===\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[AIDS pandemic]]\n* [[Indian states ranking by HIV awareness]]\n* [[Health in India]]\n* [[Public health system in India]]\n* [[Pharmaceutical industry in India]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://www.avert.org/professionals/hiv-around-world/asia-pacific/india Avert, 'HIV and AIDS in India']\n* [http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=955723 Controlling Hiv/Aids - a Judicial Measure, Recommendations by Supreme Court of India, HIV/AIDS e-Conference, Vrajlal K. Sapovadia, 2003]\n* [http://inpplus.healthunlocked.com/ HealthUnlocked] a support forum for HIV and AIDS.\n* [http://www.prsindia.org/uploads/media/HIV/HIV-AIDS%20Bill,%202014.pdf HIV/AIDS Prevention and Control Bill 2014]\n\n{{Social issues in India}}\n{{AIDS}}\n{{Asia topic|HIV/AIDS in}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hiv Aids In India}}\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS in India| ]]\n", "name_user": "Fababbey", "label": "safe", "comment": "minor ce and deletion of repeated portions", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HIV/AIDS_in_India"}
